Inc. (Wild Mule Games\rquote  successor) published the first widely distributed Fudge book, containing the June 1995 version of the rules (the version that Steffan was satisfied enough with to stop tinkering ).\par Six years later, Grey Ghost Press published a new Fudge book \endash  the Expanded Edition. The Expanded Edition had everything from the 1995 edition, plus additional material including Fantasy Fudge, a pre-customized version of Fudge for use in a fantasy setting. This Fudge System Reference Document contains the text from the 2000 Fudge Expanded Edition.\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Now in 2005, in celebration of the company\rquote s 10}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\super\kerning1 th}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  anniversary, Grey Ghost Press is releasing a hardcover edition of Fudge. In addition to most of the material in the Expanded Edition (and in this Fudge System Reference Document), the 10}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\super\kerning1 th}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  Anniversary edition of Fudge has extensive lists of gifts, faults, skills, and attributes, alternative rules, advice on \ldblquote fudging\rdblquote  Fudge games, and more \endash  more than twice as much material as in the Expanded Edition. Much of that new material will also be released under the Open Game License (although not as part of the core Fudge System Reference Document).\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For more information on the history of the Fudge roleplaying game, please visit Steffan\rquote s Fudge Designer Notes webpage at http://www.panix.com/~sos/rpg/fud-des.html.\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For more information on Grey Ghost Press and commercial Fudge publishing, please visit http://www.fudgerpg.com\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 What is Fudge?\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge is a rules-light roleplaying game (RPG), concentrating on role-playing rather than endless dice rolls and tables and similar detailed game mechanics. It also uses words rather than numbers to describe character traits. For example, a character might be a Great swordsman rather than a "14th level fighter." Combined with simple action resolution, Fudge's descriptive nature makes ideal it for novice players. Fudge is also flexible enough to satisfy experienced role-players. There are no artificial limits placed on character creation; any character the player can imagine can be described in Fudge terms. (The GM has final say over whether or not a character is acceptable in a given game.)\par The basic Fudge rules contain no campaign world information (except for a few examples). But the game's flexibility allows it to be easily used with nearly any other role-playing game's campaign world - and, of course, with Gamemasters' own personal creations.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Some Highlights of Fudge}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 No Fixed Attributes.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  The GM chooses attributes that match the genre played and suit individual taste. A GM designing a simple Fudge game may choose only two attributes (Body and Mind, for instance), or may dispense with attributes entirely and have a character's abilities entirely defined by skills, gifts, and faults. Another Gamemaster may choose 6 attributes, or 10, or more. There are a lot of attributes to choose from.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Skill-driven system.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  The GM selects the skills, whether they are broadly defined skill groups or finely defined individual skills. You can even mix broad definitions with narrow ones without any loss of playability.\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Simple action resolution.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  Players use normal six-sided dice - or, optionally, special Fudge dice - to determine how well their characters perform any action. Results describe degrees of success (or failure!) in words - from Superb down to Terrible. Alternative dice methods allow for 20-sided or percentile dice to be used.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Painless translation.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  The word-based system lets you easily translate any campaign world or adventure written in Fudge into any other system - and vice versa! Fudge thus works as a "universal translator" of gaming systems.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Design your own.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  If you are thinking of designing your own home rules role-playing game, simply reading Fudge can provide an excellent introduction to everything you need consider as a game designer!\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Goodies Galore.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  The Fudge game was first published on the Internet, and alternative rules and supplementary materials are freely available at various on-line sites. The Grey Ghost Games website includes links to many of these Fudge-related sites. There is also an active Fudge e-mail list.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Terminology:\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 To avoid confusion, \ldblquote he,\rdblquote  \ldblquote him,\rdblquote  etc., are used to describe a player and PC, and \ldblquote she,\rdblquote  \ldblquote her,\rdblquote  etc., are used to describe a Gamemaster and NPC.\par The core rules of }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  are divided into six Chapters plus the Addenda, each of which is divided into Sections. The decimal point in Section numbers is a true decimal. For example, Section 1.35 comes between Section 1.3 and Section 1.4. Additional material has no section numbering.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Fudge in a Nutshell\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Although Fudge is designed to be customized by each Gamemaster, there are some game design decisions at the core of Fudge that are used by most Fudge Gamemasters.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Characters and Character Traits\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge characters are described by \ldblquote traits,\rdblquote  including attributes (any trait that everyone in the game world has), skills (any trait that isn\rquote t an attribute and can be improved through practice), gifts (any trait that isn\rquote t an attribute or skill but is something positive for the character), and faults (any trait that limits a character\rquote s actions or earns him a bad reaction from other people). Supernormal powers are treated as potent gifts.\par Fudge uses ordinary words to describe some traits, especially attributes and skills. The following terms of a seven-level sequence are the words suggested by the Fudge author and used in Grey Ghost Games products:\par \par Superb\par Great\par Good\par Fair\par Mediocre\par Poor\par Terrible\par \par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 There is an additional level not listed above: Legendary, which is beyond Superb. GMs may restrict Legendary traits to non-player characters.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Character Creation\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge provides two basic means of creating characters: the \ldblquote subjective\rdblquote  and \ldblquote objective\rdblquote  systems. \par In the subjective system, the player and GM work together to describe the character in Fudge terms, building from a strong character concept.\par In the objective system, a character\rquote s traits start at a default level (Fair for attributes; Poor for most skills) and the GM grants each player a number of \ldblquote free\rdblquote  levels to allocate. She may also grant \ldblquote free\rdblquote  gifts, or require one or more faults. The player can then spend two free levels to raise an attribute from Fair to Great, for instance; or sacrifice a number of levels to gain a gift, or give his character a fault in return for levels to apply somewhere else. \par The trading \ldblquote values\rdblquote  of various traits and trait levels are:\par \par 1 attribute level = 3 skill levels\par 1 gift = 6 skill levels\par 1 gift = 2 attribute levels\par 1 gift = 1 fault\par Scale \emdash  Strength and Mass\par \par Some characters or creatures have certain attributes that are way beyond the human norm. Prime examples include Strength, Mass, and Speed. Such attributes are rated in Scale, which acts as a modifier in interactions between creatures or items of different Scale.\par In a human-based game, Human Scale is 0. A race of greater-than-human average strength would be Scale +1 Strength or more, while a race of lesser average strength would be Scale \endash 1 Strength or less. Individuals are then of Fair or Good Strength, etc., relative to those of their own Scale. \par In a \ldblquote Bunnies\rdblquote  game, where the player characters are rabbits, Rabbit Scale would be 0, while Human Scale would likely be +7. In a \ldblquote Mecha\rdblquote  game, where the player characters were giant robots, Mecha Scale would be 0, while Human Scale would depend on the actual size difference between the Mechs and humans; a Human Scale of \endash 15 relative to the Mecha Scale of 0 would not be unreasonable.\par To calculate appropriate Strength/Mass Scale values, figure that each level of Strength Scale represents an increase of about 1.5 times the Strength and Mass of the previous Scale level. This is because the Fudge core rules define each level of Strength (from Terrible to Superb) to be 1.5 times stronger than the previous level. (This progression isn\rquote t necessarily true for other attributes. Superb Dexterity is only about twice as good as Fair Dexterity, and each level of Speed is 1.2 times faster than the previous level.) Strength Scale increases at the same rate: a Scale 1, Fair Strength individual is 1.5 times stronger than a Scale 0, Fair Strength individual.\par Note that Scale 1 Fair Strength is not exactly equal to a Scale 0 Good Strength \emdash  Scale really measures Mass, or Density, and affects how easily a creature may be hurt. A Scale 1 Fair Strength fighter has an advantage over a Scale 0 Good Strength fighter, even though their Strengths are equal. The Scale 1 fighter is less affected by the other\rquote s damage due to his greater mass.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Action Resolution\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For any action the player character wishes to perform, the GM must determine which trait is tested. (This will usually be a skill or an attribute.) If the action is Unopposed, the GM determines the Difficulty Level. Some actions are so easy that the character succeeds automatically; others are impossible (no rolls needed).\par \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Unopposed Actions\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When a character performs an action that isn\rquote t influenced by anyone else, it is referred to as an Unopposed action. Examples include jumping a wide chasm, climbing a cliff, etc.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Difficulty Level:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  The GM will set a Difficulty Level when a character tries an Unopposed Action. Usually the Difficulty Level will be Fair, but some tasks are easier or harder. \par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Rolled Degree:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  This refers to how well a character does at a particular task. If someone is Good at Climbing in general, but the die-roll shows a +1 to the character\rquote s skill, then the rolled degree is one level higher than the character\rquote s skill level \emdash  Great, in this case. Rolled degrees from Superb +1 to Superb +4 are possible; a GM may thus set a Difficulty Level beyond Superb for nearly impossible actions. Likewise, there are rolled degrees from Terrible \endash 1 down to Terrible \endash 4. The GM should use her imagination in determining the consequences of such abysmal failures.\par \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Opposed Actions\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Actions are Opposed when other people (or animals, etc.) may have an effect on the outcome of the action. In this case, the player of each contestant rolls some dice, and the results are compared to determine the outcome.\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Relative Degree:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  This refers to how well a character did compared to another participant in an Opposed Action. The relative degree is expressed as a number of levels. If a PC gets a rolled degree result of Good in a fight, and his NPC foe gets a rolled degree result of Mediocre, the PC beat his foe by two levels \emdash  the relative degree is +2 from his perspective, \endash 2 from hers.\par \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge Dice and Other Random Generators\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge dice are six-sided dice with two sides marked + (+1), two sides marked \endash  (\endash 1), and two sides left blank (+/\endash 0). Rolling four Fudge dice (4dF) gives results from \endash 4 (sub-Terrible) to +4 (trans-Superb). To determine the result of an action, roll the dice; use the result to modify the trait level being tested. For example, a +3 dice result added to a Fair trait is a Superb rolled degree; a \endash 1 result added to a Fair trait indicates a Mediocre result.\par Alternative 3d6 dice method: Roll 3 six-sided dice. Add the numbers and compare to the following table:\par \par Rolled:\tab 3-4\tab 5\tab 6-7\tab 8-9\tab 10-11\tab 12-13\tab 14-15\tab 16\tab 17-18\par Result:\tab \endash 4\tab \endash 3\tab \endash 2\tab \endash 1\tab +0\tab +1\tab +2\tab +3\tab +4\par \par When setting Difficulty Levels, it may help to keep the statistical results of rolling four Fudge dice in mind:\par \par \tab Odds of rolling\tab Odds of Rolling\par \tab exactly on 4dF:\tab Target or Higher\par +4\tab 1.2%\tab 1.2%\par +3\tab 4.9%\tab 6.2%\par +2\tab 12.3%\tab 18.5%\par +1\tab 19.8%\tab 38.3%\par 0\tab 23.5%\tab 61.7%\par \endash 1\tab 19.8%\tab 81.5%\par \endash 2\tab 12.3%\tab 93.8%\par \endash 3\tab 4.9%\tab 98.8%\par \endash 4\tab 1.2%\tab 100.0%\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Wounds\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Combat damage to a character can be described as being at one of seven stages of severity:\par \par Undamaged (no wounds at all)\par Just a Scratch (no real game effect)\par Hurt (\endash 1 to traits)\par Very Hurt (\endash 2 to traits)\par Incapacitated (only the most basic actions allowed)\par Near Death (unconscious; death without medical help)\par Dead\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Determining Wound Levels:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  Fudge offers many ways to track combat damage. The Objective Damage System assumes each character will have an Offensive Damage Factor (the total of modifiers, including any applicable Strength and Scale bonuses, that reflects the deadliness of the weapon used) and a Defensive Damage Factor (the total of modifiers, including Scale and armor, that reflects the character\rquote s ability to withstand or avoid damage). To determine how much damage is done in a given combat round, the following formula may be used:\par \par Winner\rquote s Relative Degree + Offensive Damage Factor \endash  Loser\rquote s Defensive Damage Factor\par \par Damage:\tab 1-2\tab 3-4\tab 5-6\tab 7-8\tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab Hurt\tab Very Hurt\tab Incap.\tab Nr. Death\par \par Most characters can withstand three Scratches, one Hurt, and one Very Hurt. Further Scratches are marked as Hurts, further Hurts are marked as Very Hurt, etc. For more cinematic games, GMs may adjust the wound boxes, allowing two Hurts instead of one, for example.\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge games will vary, of course, but many have these simple character creation and action resolution rules at their core. See Fantasy Fudge, later in this document, as an example.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Fudge 2000 Expanded Edition Text\par Chapter 1: Character Creation\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 This chapter contains all the information you\rquote ll need to create human characters, including character traits and trait levels, and some different ways to allocate them.\par For non-human characters \emdash  or characters with supernormal abilities (magic, psionics, super powers, etc.) \emdash  you will also need to read Chapter 2, Supernormal Powers, before your characters will be complete.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.1  Character Creation Terms\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Trait: anything that describes a character. A trait can be an attribute, skill, inherited gift, fault, supernormal power, or any other feature that describes a character. The GM is the ultimate authority on what is an attribute and what is a skill, gift, etc.\par Level: most traits are described by one of seven adjectives. These seven descriptive words represent levels a trait may be at. In addition, the Objective Character Creation method grants the player free levels, and demands he keep track of them. In this case, one level is required to raise a trait to the next better adjective.\par Attribute: any trait that everyone in the game world has, in some degree or other. See Section 1.31, Attributes, for a sample list of attributes. On a scale of Terrible ... Fair ... Superb, the average human will have an attribute at Fair.\par Skill: any trait that isn\rquote t an attribute, but can be improved through practice. The default for an unlisted skill is usually Poor, though that can vary up or down a little.\par Gift: any trait that isn\rquote t an attribute or skill, but is something positive for the character. Some GMs will define a certain trait as a gift, while others will define the same trait as an attribute. In general, if the trait doesn\rquote t easily fit the Terrible ... Fair ... Superb scale, it\rquote s probably a gift.\par Fault: any trait that limits a character\rquote s actions, or earns him a bad reaction from other people.\par Supernormal Power: although technically gifts, supernormal powers are treated separately in Chapter 2.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.2  Fudge Trait Levels\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge uses ordinary words to describe various traits of a character. The following terms of a seven-level sequence are suggested (from best to worst):\par \par Superb\par Great\par Good\par Fair\par Mediocre\par Poor\par Terrible\par These levels should be written on each character sheet for easy reference.\par A GM may alter this list in any way she desires, including expanding or shrinking it. For example, if Superb doesn\rquote t sound right to you, use Awesome \emdash  or even Way Cool. If the words Mediocre and Fair don\rquote t make sense to you, change them. These seven terms will be used in the rules, however, for clarity.\par To remember the order, compare adjacent words. If, as a beginner, your eventual goal is to become an excellent game player, for example, ask yourself if you\rquote d rather be called a Fair game player or a Mediocre game player.\par There is an additional level that can be used in Fudge, but is not listed above: Legendary, which is beyond Superb. Those with Legendary Strength, for example, are in the 99.9th percentile, and their names can be found in any book of world records.\par Important Note: not every GM will allow PCs to become Legendary. Even in games that do include the Legendary level, it is not recommended that any character be allowed to start the game as Legendary. Superb represents the 98th to 99.9th percentile of any given trait, which should be enough for any beginning PC. Of course, if a player character gets a bit overconfident, meeting an NPC Legendary swordswoman can be a grounding experience\u8230\'c9\par If someone really has to begin play as a Legendary swordsman, strong man, etc., doing the GM\rquote s laundry for half a year or so (in advance) should be a sufficient bribe to be allowed to start at that level. Of course, working towards Legendary makes a great campaign goal, and so PCs may rise to that height, given enough playing time and a generous GM.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.3  Character Traits\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Traits are divided into Attributes, Skills, Gifts, Faults, and Supernormal Powers. Not every GM will have all five types of traits in her game. These traits are defined under Section 1.1, Character Creation Terms, above.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.31  Attributes\par }\pard \fi187\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Gamers often disagree on how many attributes a game should have. Some prefer few attributes, others many. Even those that agree on the number of attributes may disagree on the selection. While Fudge discusses some attributes (Strength, Fatigue, Constitution, etc.) in later sections, none of these are mandatory. The only attribute the basic Fudge rules assume is Damage Capacity, and even that is optional \emdash  see Section 4.52, Damage Capacity.\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Here is a partial list of attributes in use by other games; select to your taste, or skip these altogether:\par Body: Agility, Aim, Appearance, Balance, Brawn, Build, Constitution, Coordination, Deftness, Dexterity, Endurance, Fatigue, Fitness, Health, Hit Points, Manual Dexterity, Muscle, Nimbleness, Quickness, Physical, Reflexes, Size, Smell, Speed, Stamina, Strength, Wound Resistance, Zip, and so on.\par Mind: Cunning, Education, Intelligence, Knowledge, Learning, Mechanical, Memory, Mental, Mental Strength, Perception, Reasoning, Smarts, Technical, Wit, and so on.\par Soul: Channeling, Charisma, Charm, Chutzpah, Common Sense, Coolness, Disposition, Drive, Ego, Empathy, Fate, Honor, Intuition, Luck, Magic Resistance, Magic Potential, Magical Ability, Power, Presence, Psyche, Sanity, Self Discipline, Social, Spiritual, Style, Will, Wisdom, and so on, and so on.\par Other: Rank, Status, Wealth.\par Most games combine many of these attributes, while others treat some of them as gifts or even skills. In Fudge, if you wish, you can even split these attributes into smaller ones: Lifting Strength, Carrying Strength, Damage-dealing Strength, etc.\par At this point, the GM decides how many attributes she deems necessary \endash  or she might leave it up to each player. (Commercial games range from one or two to over 20.) See Section 6.3, Character Examples, for some possibilities.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.32  Skills\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Skills are not related to attributes or their levels in Fudge. Players are encouraged to design their characters logically \emdash  a character with a lot of Good physical skills should probably have better than average physical attributes, for example. On the other hand, Fudge allows a player to create someone like Groo the Wanderer*, who is very clumsy yet extremely skilled with his swords.\par (*GROO is a trademark of Sergio Aragon\u233\'8es. If you don\rquote t know Groo, go to a comic book store and check him out!)\par The GM should then decide what level of skill depth she wants. Are skills broad categories such as \ldblquote Social skills,\rdblquote  or moderately broad abilities, such as \ldblquote Inspire People, Parley, and Market Savvy,\rdblquote  or are they specific abilities such as \ldblquote Barter, Seduce, Repartee, Persuade, Fast-Talk, Bully, Grovel, Carouse, Flatter, Bribe,\rdblquote  etc.?\par \par Examples of Skill Depth:\par Animal Skills\tab Riding\tab Riding Horses\par \tab \tab \tab Riding Camels\par \tab \tab \tab Riding Elephants\par \tab \tab \tab Driving Oxen\par \tab \tab Driving\tab Driving Mules & Horses\par \tab \tab \tab Driving Dogs\par \tab \tab \tab Grooming\par \tab \tab Care\tab Feeding\par \tab \tab \tab Breeding\tab \par \tab \tab \tab Veterinary\tab First Aid\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab Diagnosis\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab Medicine\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab Surgery\par \par An attribute is, in some ways, a very broad skill group, and skills may be ignored altogether if desired.\par Combat skills require special consideration. The broadest possible category is simply that: Combat Skills. A broad range breaks that down to Melee Weapons, Unarmed Combat, and Missile Weapons. A somewhat narrower approach would break down Melee Weapons into Close Combat Melee Weapons (knives, blackjacks, etc.), One-handed Melee Weapons (one-handed swords, axes, maces, etc.) and Two-handed Melee Weapons (polearms, spears, battle-axes, two-handed swords, etc.). Or, for a precise list of skills, each group in parentheses could be listed as a separate skill; a character skilled at using a broadsword knows nothing about using a saber, for example.\par Each choice has its merits. Broad skill groups that include many sub-skills make for an easy character sheet and fairly competent characters, while specific skills allow fine-tuning a character to a precise degree.\par See Section 6.3, Character Examples, for an idea of how broadly or finely skills can be defined in a game.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.33  Gifts\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A gift is a positive trait that doesn\rquote t seem to fit the Terrible ... Fair ... Superb scale that attributes and skills fall into. However, this will vary from GM to GM: a photographic memory is a gift to one GM, while it is a Superb Memory attribute to another. Some GMs will define Charisma as an attribute, while others define it as a gift. To one Gamemaster, a character either has Night Vision or he doesn\rquote t; another will allow characters to take different levels of it. A Gamemaster may not even have gifts in her game at all.\par Alternatively, gifts can come in levels, but the levels don\rquote t necessarily coincide with the levels used by other traits. For example, Status might be three- or four-tiered, or even nine-tiered instead of fitting into the seven levels of attributes and skills. Wealth might come only in five different levels \emdash  whatever each GM desires.\par Supernormal powers, such as the ability to cast magic spells, fly, read minds, etc., are technically powerful gifts, but are handled separately in Chapter 2. Likewise, traits above the human norm, such as a super strong fantasy or alien race, are treated by definition as supernormal powers.\par In general, if a gift isn\rquote t written on the character sheet, the character doesn\rquote t have it.\par Some possible gifts include:\par Absolute Direction; Always keeps his cool; Ambidextrous; Animal Empathy; Attractive; Beautiful speaking voice; Bonus to one aspect of an attribute; Combat Reflexes; Contacts in police force; Danger Sense; Extraordinary Speed; Healthy Constitution; Keen senses; Literate; Lucky; Many people owe him favors; Never disoriented in zero Gravity; Never forgets a name/face/whatever; Night Vision; Patron; Perfect Timing; Peripheral Vision; Quick Reflexes; Rank; Rapid Healing; Reputation as Hero; Scale; Sense of empathy; Single-minded (+1 to any lengthy task); Status; Strong Will; Tolerant; Tough Hide (\endash 1 to damage) Wealth; etc.\par See also Section 6.3, Character Examples, for examples of different gifts. Many others are possible.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.34  Faults\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Faults are anything that makes life more difficult for a character. The primary faults are those that restrict a character\rquote s actions or earn him a bad reaction from chance-met NPCs. Various attitudes, neuroses and phobias are faults; so are physical disabilities and social stigmas. There are heroic faults, too: a code of honor and inability to tell a lie restrict your actions significantly, but are not signs of flawed personality.\par Some sample faults: Absent-Minded; Addiction; Ambitious; Amorous heartbreaker; Bloodlust; Blunt and tactless; Bravery indistinguishable from foolhardiness; Can\rquote t resist having the last word; Code of Ethics limits actions; Code of Honor; Compulsive Behavior; Coward; Curious; Finicky; Easily Distractible; Enemy; Fanatic patriot; Full of bluff and bluster and machismo; Garrulous; Getting old; Glutton; Goes Berserk if Wounded; Gossip; Greedy; Gullible; Humanitarian (helps the needy for no pay); Idealist (not grounded in reality); Indecisive; Intolerant; Jealous of Anyone Getting More Attention; Lazy; Loyal to Companions; Manic-Depressive; Melancholy; Multiple Personality; Must obey senior officers; Nosy; Obsession; Outlaw; Overconfident; Owes favors; Phobias; Poor; Practical Joker; Quick-Tempered; Quixotic; Self-defense Pacifist; Socially awkward; Soft-hearted; Stubborn; Quick to take offense; Unlucky; Vain; Violent when enraged; Vow; Worry Wart; Zealous behavior; etc.\par See also Section 6.3, Character Examples, for examples of different faults. Many others are possible.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.35  Personality\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A character\rquote s personality may be represented by one or more traits, or it can be written out as character background or description.\par As an example of the first case, courage is an attribute, a gift, or even a fault. As an attribute, Superb Courage or Terrible Courage has an obvious meaning. As a gift, obvious bravery gives the character a positive reaction from people he meets (assuming they see him being courageous, or have heard of his deeds, of course).\par However, both Very Courageous and Very Cowardly can be faults because they can limit a character\rquote s actions. A courageous character might not run away from a fight even if it were in his best interest, while a cowardly one would have a hard time staying in a fight even if he stood to gain by staying.\par Or a character\rquote s level of courage might not be a quantified trait at all, but something the player simply decides. \ldblquote Moose is very brave,\rdblquote  a player jots down, and that is that. It doesn\rquote t have to count as a high attribute, gift, or fault.\par A player should ask the GM how she wants to handle specific personality traits. If the player describes his character in detail, the GM can easily decide which personality traits are attributes, gifts, or faults. However they are handled, most characters benefit by having their personalities fleshed out.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.36  Fudge Points\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge Points are meta-game gifts that may be used to buy \ldblquote luck\rdblquote  during a game \emdash  they let the players fudge a game result. These are \ldblquote meta-game\rdblquote  gifts because they operate at the player-GM level, not character-character level. Not every GM will allow Fudge Points \emdash  those who prefer realistic games should probably not use them.\par The GM sets the starting number of Fudge Points. The recommended range is from one to five. Unused Fudge Points are saved up for the next gaming session. Each player may get an additional number each gaming session. (This is also set by the GM, and may or may not equal the starting level.) Alternately, the GM may simply allow Experience Points (EP) to be traded for Fudge Points at a rate appropriate for the campaign: 3 EP = 1 Fudge Point, down to 1 EP = Fudge Point.\par Fudge Points can be used in many ways, depending on what level on the realistic-legendary scale the game is played at. Here are some suggested ways to use them \emdash  the GM can create her own uses, of course. A GM may allow as few or many of these options as she wishes \emdash  the players should ask her before assuming they can do something with Fudge Points.\par 1) Spending a Fudge Point may accomplish an Unopposed action automatically and with panache \emdash  good for impressing members of the appropriate sex, and possibly avoiding injury in the case of dangerous actions. The GM may veto this use of Fudge Points for actions with a Difficulty Level of Beyond Superb. The GM may disallow this option for an Opposed action, such as combat.\par 2) A player may spend one Fudge Point to alter a die roll one level, up or down as desired. The die roll can be either one the player makes, or one the GM makes that directly concerns the player\rquote s character.\par 3) A player may spend one Fudge Point to declare that wounds aren\rquote t as bad as they first looked. This reduces the intensity of each wound by one or two levels (a Hurt result becomes a Scratch, for example, or even a Very Hurt becomes a Scratch). Or it can mean that any one wound (or more), regardless of level, is just a Scratch. This latter option may cost more than one Fudge point. The GM can restrict this to outside of combat time.\par 4) A player may spend one (or more) Fudge Points to get an automatic +4 result, without having to roll the dice. This use is available in Opposed actions, if allowed.\par 5) For appropriately legendary games, a GM-set number of Fudge Points can be spent to ensure a favorable coincidence. (This is always subject to GM veto, of course.) For example, if the PCs are in a maximum security prison, perhaps one of the guards turns out to be the cousin of one of the PCs \emdash  and lets them escape! Or the captain of the fishing boat rescuing the PCs turns out to be someone who owes a favor to one of them, and is willing to take them out of his way to help them out\u8230\'c9 And so on. This option should cost a lot of Fudge Points, except in certain genres where bizarre coincidences are the norm.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.4  Allocating Traits\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Character creation in Fudge assumes the players will design their characters, rather than leaving attributes and other traits to chance. The GM may allow randomly determined traits if she desires \emdash  a suggested method is given in Section 1.8, Random Character Creation.\par There are no mandatory traits in Fudge. The GM should inform the players which traits she expects to be most important, and the players may suggest others to the GM for her approval. The GM may even make a template, if desired \emdash  a collection of traits she deems important (with room for customization) \emdash  and let the players define the level of each trait. See Section 6.12, Templates.\par When a character is created, the player should define as many character traits as he finds necessary \emdash  which may or may not coincide with a GM-determined list. If a player adds an attribute the GM deems unnecessary, the GM may treat that attribute as simply a description of the character. She may require a roll against a different attribute than the player has in mind, and the player must abide by her decision.\par As an example, a certain GM decides she wants characters to have a general Dexterity attribute. A player takes Good Dexterity for his PC, but wants to show that the character is better at whole body dexterity than at manual dexterity. So he writes: Great Agility and Fair Manual Dexterity. However, the GM can ignore these distinctions, and simply require a Dexterity roll, since that is the trait she has chosen. (She can average the PC-chosen levels, or simply select one of them.) Of course, she can also allow him to roll on the attributes he has created.\par In Fudge, a character with a trait at Fair will succeed at ordinary tasks 62% of the time \emdash  there is usually no need to create a superstar. In fact, Great is just that: great! Superb should be reserved for the occasional trait in which your character is the best he\rquote s ever met.\par Any trait that is not defined at character creation will be at a default level:\par For attributes: Fair.\par For most skills: Poor (easier skills are at Mediocre, while harder ones are at Terrible). A skill default means untrained, or close to it. However, it is possible to take a skill at Terrible (below the default level for most skills), which implies an ineptitude worse than untrained.\par For most gifts, supernormal powers and certain GM-defined skills: Non-Existent. (That is, the default is non-existent. The trait itself exists in some character, somewhere.)\par Each player should expect the GM to modify his character after creation \emdash  it\rquote s the nature of the game. The GM should expect to review each character before play. It would, in fact, be best if the characters were made in the presence of the GM so she can answer questions during the process.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.5  Subjective Character Creation\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 An easy way to create a character in Fudge is simply to write down everything about the character that you feel is important. Any attribute or skill should be rated using one of the levels Terrible through Superb (see Section 1.2, Fudge Trait Levels).\par It may be easiest, though, if the GM supplies a template of attributes she\rquote ll be using. See Section 6.3, Character Examples, for template ideas.\par The GM may also tell the player in advance that his character can be Superb in a certain number of attributes, Great in so many others, and Good in yet another group. For example, in an epic-style game with eight attributes, the GM allows one Superb attribute, two Greats, and three Goods. In a more realistic game, this is one Superb, one Great, and two Goods.\par This can apply to skills, too: one Superb skill, two Great skills, and six Good skills is a respectable number for a realistic campaign, while two Superbs, three Greats, and ten Goods is quite generous, even in a highly cinematic game.\par The GM may also simply limit the number of skills a character can take at character creation: 10, 15, or 20 are possible choices.\par Gifts and faults can be restricted this way, also. For example, a GM allows a character to have two gifts, but he must take at least three faults. Taking another fault allows another gift, or another skill at Great, and so on.\par These limitations help the player define the focus of the character a bit better: what is his best trait (what can he do best)?\par A simple \ldblquote two lower for one higher\rdblquote  trait-conversion mechanic can also be used. If the GM allows one Superb attribute, for example, the player may forego that and take two attributes at Great, instead. The converse may also be allowed: a player may swap two skills at Good to get one at Great.\par Example: a player wants a Jack-of-all-trades character, and the GM has limits of one Superb skill, two Great skills and six Good skills. The player trades the one Superb skill limit for two Great skills: he can now take four skills at Great. However, he trades all four Great skills in order to have eight more Good skills. His character can now have 14 skills at Good, but none at any higher levels.\par In the Subjective Character Creation system, it is easy to use both broad and narrow skill groups, as appropriate for the character. In these cases, a broad skill group is assumed to contain the phrase, \ldblquote except as listed otherwise.\rdblquote \par For example, a player wishes to play the science officer of a starship. He decides this character has spent so much time studying the sciences, that he\rquote s weak in most physical skills. So on his character sheet he could simply write:\par \par Physical Skills: Poor\par \par He also decides that his character\rquote s profession would take him out of the ship in vacuum quite a bit, to examine things. So he\rquote d have to be somewhat skilled at zero-G maneuvering. So he then adds:\par \par Zero-G Maneuvering: Good\par \par Even though this is a physical skill, it is not at Poor because he specifically listed it as an exception to the broad category.\par When the character write-up is done, the player and GM meet and discuss the character. If the GM feels the character is too potent for the campaign she has in mind, she may ask the player to reduce the character\rquote s power \emdash  see Section 1.9, Minimizing Abuse.\par The GM may also need to suggest areas that she sees as being too weak \emdash  perhaps she has a game situation in mind that will test a trait the player didn\rquote t think of. Gentle hints, such as \ldblquote Does he have any social skills?\rdblquote  can help the player through the weak spots. Of course, if there are multiple players, other PCs can compensate for an individual PC\rquote s weaknesses. In this case, the question to the whole group is then, \ldblquote Does anyone have any social skills?\rdblquote \par Instead of the player writing up the character in terms of traits and levels, he can simply write out a prose description of his character. This requires the GM to translate everything into traits and appropriate levels, but that\rquote s not hard to do if the description is well written. This method actually produces some of the best characters.\par \par An example:\par GM: \ldblquote I see you rate Captain Wallop\rquote s blaster skill highly, and also his piloting and gunnery, but I\rquote m only allowing one Superb skill \emdash  which is he best at?\rdblquote \par Player: \ldblquote Blaster!\rdblquote \par GM: \ldblquote Okay, Superb Blaster. That would then be Great Piloting and Great Gunnery, all right? That leaves you with two more skills to be at Great, since I allow four to start out. Hmmm \emdash  I notice he successfully penetrated the main Khothi hive and rescued the kidnapped ambassador \emdash  that sounds like a Great Ability to Move Quietly to me \emdash  is that accurate, or would you describe it as some other ability?\rdblquote \par Player: \ldblquote Uh, no \emdash  sorry, I didn\rquote t write that clearly enough. He disguised himself and pretended to be a Khothi worker!\rdblquote \par GM: \ldblquote Ah, I see! How about Great Disguise skill and Great Acting ability, then? And he must be Good at the Khothi language, right?\rdblquote \par And so on.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.6  Objective Character Creation\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For those who don\rquote t mind counting numbers a bit, the following method creates interesting and well-balanced characters.\par In this system, all traits start at default level. The GM then allows a number of free levels the players may use to raise selected traits to higher levels. Players may then lower certain traits in order to raise others even further. Finally, a player may opt to trade some levels of one trait type (such as attributes) for another (skills, for example). The whole process insures that no single character will dominate every aspect of play.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.61  Attributes\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A GM using the Objective Character Creation system should decide how many attributes she deems necessary in the campaign. She can choose to leave it up to each player, if she wishes. Players then have a number of free attribute levels equal to half the number of attributes (round up). For example, if she selects four attributes, each player starts with two free levels he can use to raise his character\rquote s attributes.\par For a more high-powered game, the GM may allow a number of free levels equal to the number of attributes chosen.\par All attributes are considered to be Fair until the player raises or lowers them. The cost of raising or lowering an attribute is:\par \tab +3  \tab Superb\par \tab +2  \tab Great\par \tab +1  \tab Good\par  \tab 0  \tab Fair\par \tab \endash 1  \tab Mediocre\par \tab \endash 2  \tab Poor\par \tab \endash 3  \tab Terrible\par \par Thus, a player may raise his Strength attribute (which is Fair by default) to Good by spending one free attribute level. He could then spend another free level to raise Strength again to Great. This would exhaust his free levels if there were only four attributes \emdash  but he would have one more if there were six attributes, and eight more free levels if there were 20 attributes.\par When the free attribute levels have been exhausted, an attribute can be raised further by lowering another attribute an equal amount. (See also Section 1.64, Trading Traits.) From the previous example, Strength can be raised one more level (to Superb) if the player lowers the character\rquote s Charm to Mediocre to compensate for the increase in Strength.\par If the GM allows the players to choose their own attributes, she may simply tell them to take half as many free levels as attributes they choose. If a player chooses an attribute and leaves it at Fair, that attribute does not count towards the total of attributes which determines the amount of free levels. That is, a player cannot simply add twelve attributes, all at Fair, in order to get six more free levels to raise the others with. GM-mandated attributes left at Fair do count when determining the number of free levels, though.\par As an interesting possibility for those who want attributes and skills to reflect each other accurately, do not let the players adjust attribute levels at all. Instead, they select only skill levels, gifts and faults for their characters. When the character is done, the GM can then determine what attribute levels make sense for the skill levels chosen, and discuss it with the player.\par Example: a character is made with many combat and wilderness skills, but no social skills. He also has a smattering of intelligence skills. The GM decides that this character has Strength, Dexterity and Health of Great from spending a lot of time outdoors, practicing with weapons, etc. She will even let the player choose one to be at Superb, if desired. Perception is probably Good, since wilderness survival depends on it. Any social attribute is Mediocre at best \emdash  possibly even Poor \emdash  while Intelligence is Mediocre or Fair. If the player objects to the low Intelligence ranking, the GM can point out that the character hasn\rquote t spent much time in skills that hone Intelligence, and if he wants his character\rquote s IQ to be higher, he should adjust his skill list.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.62  Skills\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 In the Objective Character Creation system, each player has a number of free skill levels with which to raise his skills. Suggested limits are:\par \par For Extremely Broad Skill Groups: 15 levels.\par For Moderately Broad Skill Groups: 30 levels.\par For Specific Skills: 40 to 60 levels.\par \par Ask the GM for the allotted amount, which will give you a clue as to how precisely to define your skills. Of course, the GM may choose any number that suits her, such as 23, 42, or 74\u8230\'c9. See Section 6.3, Character Examples. Gamemasters may devise their own skill lists to choose from \emdash  some possibilities are included in the skill lists on page 126.\par Most skills have a default value of Poor unless the player raises or lowers them \emdash  see Section 1.4, Allocating Traits.\par Certain skills have a default of non-existent. These would include Languages, Karate, Nuclear Physics, or Knowledge of Aztec Rituals, which must be studied to be known at all. When a character studies such a skill (puts a level into it at character creation, or experience points later in the game), the level he gets it at depends on how hard it is to learn. Putting one level into learning the Spanish language, for example, would get it at Mediocre, since it\rquote s of average difficulty to learn. Nuclear Physics, on the other hand, might only be Poor or even Terrible with only one level put into it. It would take four levels just to get such a skill at Fair, for example.\par For ease in character creation, use the following table:\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Cost of Skills in Objective Character Creation\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab Very\par \tab \tab Easy\tab Most\tab Hard\tab Hard\par Terrible\tab \tab \endash 2\tab \endash 1\tab 0\tab 1\par Poor\tab \tab \endash 1\tab 0\tab 1\tab 2\par Mediocre\tab 0\tab 1\tab 2\tab 3\par Fair\tab \tab 1\tab 2\tab 3\tab 4\par Good\tab \tab 2\tab 3\tab 4\tab 5\par Great\tab \tab 3\tab 4\tab 5\tab 6\par Superb\tab \tab 4\tab 5\tab 6\tab 7\par \par Easy = Cost of GM-Determined Easy Skills\par Most = Cost of Average Skill\par Hard = Cost of GM-Determined Hard Skills\par VH = Cost of GM-Determined Very Hard Skills\par (usually related to Supernormal Powers)\par \par As in the Subjective Character Creation system, the GM may limit the number of Superb and Great skills each character may have at character creation. For a highly cinematic or super-powered game, no limit is necessary. For example, the GM sets a limit of one Superb skill, three or four Great skills, and eight or so Good skills. These limits can be exceeded through character development, of course. See Section 6.3, Character Examples.\par Once the free levels are used up, a skill must be dropped one level (from the default Poor to Terrible) to raise another skill one level. (See also Section 1.64, Trading Traits.) All choices are subject to GM veto, of course.\par It is possible to mix different breadths of skill groupings. A GM who has little interest in combat can simply choose Unarmed Combat, Melee Weapons and Ranged Weapons as the only three combat skills. But this does not stop her from using all the individual Social skills (and many more) listed as examples on page 126. If this option is chosen, the broad groups cost double the levels of the narrower groups.\par Mixing skill group sizes within the same areas is awkward in the Objective Character Creation system. For example, it is difficult to have a generic Thief Skills group and also have individual skills of lockpicking, pick-pocketing, palming, security-device dismantling, etc. If she does wish to do this, then the broad skill group in this case has a maximum limit of Good, and triple cost to raise \emdash  or more, if the GM so mandates.\par If the GM is using broad groups, a player may raise a specific skill (such as Poker, for example, instead of general Gambling skill). A player would give his character a specific skill when the GM is using broad-based skill groups to fit a character concept. Do not expect the character to be equally adept with the other skills in the group. This would be true for Groo* the Wanderer, for instance, who would simply raise Sword skill, even if the GM is using the broad term Melee Weapons as a skill group. Groo would have, in fact, a Poor rating with all other Melee weapons, and this would accurately reflect the character.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.63  Gifts & Faults\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If the GM has gifts in her game, she may allow player characters to start with one or two free gifts \emdash  more for epic campaigns. Any further gifts taken must be balanced by taking on a fault, or by trading traits.\par A player may gain extra trait levels by taking GM-approved faults at the following rate:\par 1 fault = 1 gift.\par 1 fault = 2 attribute levels.\par 1 fault = 6 skill levels.\par \par However, the GM may rule that a particular fault is not serious enough to be worth two attribute levels, but may be worth one attribute level or three skill levels. On the other hand, severe faults may be worth more attribute levels.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 1.64  Trading Traits\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 During character creation, free levels may be traded (in either direction) at the following rate:\par \par 1 attribute level = 3 skill levels.\par 1 gift = 6 skill levels.\par 1 gift = 2 attribute levels.\par \par Fudge Points cannot be traded without GM permission. (If tradable, each Fudge Point should be equal to one or two gifts.)\par \par So a player with three free attribute levels and 30 free skill levels may trade three of his skill levels to get another free attribute level, or six skill levels to get another free gift.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.7  Uncommitted Traits\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Whether the character is created subjectively or objectively, each character has some free uncommitted traits (perhaps two or three). At some point in the game, a player will realize that he forgot something about the character that should have been mentioned. He may request to stop the action, and define a previously undefined trait, subject to the GM\rquote s approval. A sympathetic GM will allow this to happen even during combat time.\par GM-set skill limits (such as one Superb, three Greats) are still in effect: if the character already has the maximum number of Superb skills allowed, he can\rquote t make an uncommitted trait a Superb skill.\par See the sample character, Dolores Ramirez, Section 6.331.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.8  Random Character Creation\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Some players like to roll their attributes randomly. Here is one possible method to use in such cases. Alternate techniques can be easily designed.\par Have the player roll 2d6 for each attribute. Use the following table to find the attribute level:\par \par \tab 2\tab  = \tab Terrible\par \tab 4\tab  = \tab Poor\par \tab 3,5\tab  = \tab Mediocre\par \tab 6-8\tab  = \tab Fair\par \tab 9,11\tab  = \tab Good\par \tab 10\tab  = \tab Great\par \tab 12\tab  = \tab Superb\par \par The GM needs to decide if the player still gets the standard number of free levels or not. She may also restrict trading levels.\par For skills, the results are read as:\par \par \tab 2-5,12\tab  = \tab Terrible\par \tab 6-8\tab  = \tab Poor\par \tab 9-10\tab  = \tab Mediocre\par \tab 11\tab  = \tab Fair\par \par The player still gets the standard number of free skill levels, or the GM may allow only half the normal levels.\par The GM can let the players choose their gifts and faults, or she may wish to make up separate tables of gifts and faults, and have the players roll once or twice on each. (Conflicting traits should be rerolled.) For example:\par \par Roll\tab Gift\tab \tab \tab Fault\par 2\tab Nice Appearance\tab \tab Poor Appearance\par 3\tab Tough Hide\tab \tab Bruises Easily\par 4\tab Charismatic\tab \tab Aura of Untrustworthiness\par 5\tab Keen Hearing\tab \tab Hard of Hearing\par 6\tab Detects Lies Easily\tab Gullible\par 7\tab Melodious Voice\tab \tab Stammers\par 8\tab \u8230\'c9\tab \tab \tab \u8230\'c9\par \par And so on. The GM should customize and complete to her taste. Of course, she could set up a 3d6 table instead of a 2d6 table, or even use a 1d6 table listing general gift or fault areas (Social, Physical, Emotional, Mental, Wealth/Status, etc.) and then roll again on an appropriate second table. This would allow 36 equally likely choices.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 1.9  Minimizing Abuse\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Obviously, character creation in Fudge can be abused. There are many ways to avoid this:\par 1) The GM can require that the character take another fault or two to balance the power. (\ldblquote Okay, I\rquote ll allow you to have all that\u8230\'c9 but you need a challenge. Take on another weakness: maybe some secret vice, or be unable to tell a believable lie, or anything that fits the character concept that I can use to test you now and then.\rdblquote )\par 2) She can simply veto any trait (or raised/lowered combination) she feels is abusive. (\ldblquote I see you raised Battle-Axe in exchange for lowering Needlepoint. Hmmm.\rdblquote ) This allows the GM to customize the power level of a game. For high-powered games, allow most anything; for less cinematic campaigns, make them trade equally useful trait for trait.\par 3) She can simply note the character weaknesses and introduce a situation into every adventure where at least one of them is significant to the mission. (\ldblquote You\rquote ll be sent as an emissary to the Wanduzi tribe \emdash  they value fine Needlepoint work above all other skills, by the way\u8230\'c9\rdblquote )\par 4) She can use the \ldblquote disturbance in the force\rdblquote  technique of making sure that more powerful characters attract more serious problems. (\ldblquote The bruiser enters the bar with a maniacal look in his eye. He scans the room for a few seconds, then begins to stare intently at you.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Chapter 2: Supernormal Powers\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If your game doesn\rquote t have any supernormal powers, you don\rquote t need to read Chapter 2 at all. Genres such as modern espionage, WWII French resistance, gunslingers of the Old West, or swashbuckling Musketeers are frequently played without supernormal powers. Feel free to skip ahead directly to Chapter 3, Action Resolution.\par However, those who play in games with non-human races, magic, psi, superpowers, etc., will need to read this chapter before character creation is complete.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.1 Supernormal Power Terms\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Supernormal power: that which is beyond the capability of human beings as we know them. Supernormal powers are treated as powerful gifts. Some may have associated skills (which are taken separately, using the normal skill rules).\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Power:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  a supernormal power.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Mana:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  magical energy. Mana is an invisible substance that magicians can detect (or even create) and manipulate to alter matter, time and space.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magic: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 the art of influencing events through manipulation of mana, or through compelling beings from another dimension, or channeling power from some other source. Magic may be studied by humans, but it is inherent in some races, such as natives of Faerie.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Miracle: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 magic performed by a deity. Miracles are often subtle. Holy persons can attempt to work miracles by invoking their deity. Some religions call any non- or semi-material being greater than human a deity. Others believe there is only one Deity, and that these other beings are simply angels, demons, djinni, efriti, etc. In the former belief, magical results wrought by these superhuman beings are miracles; in the latter belief, they are not miracles, but merely a display of more psychic power than humans are capable of.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Psi:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  any power that involves mind over matter, time or space.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Superpower:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  any supernormal power that is an inherent ability, whether because of mutation, exposure to radiation, a gift of space aliens, etc., or granted by a device, such as an alien-science belt. Examples of superpowers can be found in many comic books, and include super strength, the ability to fly, see through walls, cling to ceilings, become invisible, etc.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Cybernetic Enhancement:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  any mechanical or electronic enhancement to a normal body that gives the character supernormal powers.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Non-human Races:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  certain fantasy and science fiction races (actually species) have abilities beyond the human norm, such as being much stronger, or able to fly, etc. Most of these abilities could also be classified as Psi or Superpowers, so they are not treated separately, except for Mass and Strength. Androids and robots are considered races for rules purposes.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Scale: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 characters may have certain attributes that are well beyond the human norm, one way or the other, but that need to be related to the human norm. Prime examples include Strength, Mass, and Speed. Such attributes are rated in Scale. Human Scale is 0. A race (or individual) of greater than human average strength, for example, would be Scale 1 Strength or more, while a race of lesser average strength than humans would be Scale \endash 1 Strength or less. Individuals can then be of Fair strength, or Good strength, etc., relative to those of their own Scale.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Genetic Enhancement:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  a genetic enhancement may or may not give a character supernormal powers. If it does, then it must be treated like any other supernormal power listed above.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.2  Powers at Character Creation\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Supernormal powers may or may not be available in a given game. They are not appropriate to all genres.\par The best way to design a supernormal character is through close discussion with the GM. A player should describe what he wants the character to be able to do, and the GM will decide if that\rquote s within the limits she has in mind for the game. If not, she\rquote ll make suggestions about how to change the character to fit her campaign.\par Supernormal powers are treated as powerful gifts, with availability set by the GM. The GM may decide that each player can take two Powers for free, for example, or five, or more. The player may make a case for further Powers, but may need to take faults to balance them.\par Some Powers are so effective that they are worth more than other Powers. In the Objective Character Creation system, the GM may set the cost of a certain supernormal power equal to two or three \ldblquote average\rdblquote  supernormal powers. In some cases, the GM may veto player suggestions outright: omniscience and omnipotence are good examples!\par The GM may decide that supernormal powers may be pooled with other traits for trading purposes. In this case, one average Power is worth two gifts. For example, a player who wishes to play a magician in a fantasy setting will need to trade some skill, attribute, or gift levels to buy magical Powers.\par Undefined Powers have a default of non-existent \emdash  that is, they do not have a default value of Fair, like attributes, or Poor, like skills. If a supernormal power is not defined for a character, he doesn\rquote t have it.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.21  Powers Available\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The GM needs to design the type, number allowed, and drawbacks of Powers in her game. Some examples:\par Types of Powers: a given campaign may allow magic, psi, superpowers, etc., or some combination of the above. The GM also needs to decide how finely a supernormal power is subdivided. Is ESP a generic Power, or is it split into separate Powers such as Precognition and Clairvoyance? Is magic subdivided into spells, or groups of spells (such as elemental magic) or simply the ability to break the laws of nature in any way that can be imagined? And so on.\par Number of Powers allowed: the GM may set the number of Powers allowed per character. The number may range from one to 20 \emdash  or even more. Multiple Powers per character are especially likely in a fantasy campaign where individual spells are separate Powers.\par Drawbacks of Powers: in some campaigns, using a Power may bear a penalty or have some drawback. Typical drawbacks include mental or physical fatigue, lengthy time requirements, unreliable or uncontrollable results, and undesirable side effects (such as loud noises, bad smells, and the like). Some Powers will only work under certain conditions or with certain materials, or are limited to a certain number of uses per day \emdash  or month. Others may be risky to the character, affecting physical or mental health. The GM may allow drawbacks to count as faults: a number of them can offset the cost of a Power in the Objective Character Creation system.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Scale Table\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\dn6\kerning1 \tab Scale:\tab \tab \tab Multip