curately release such energy comes with the power for free: no roll needed, it automatically hits the target every time unless the target makes a Good Dodge roll (see Chapter 4, Combat, Wounds & Healing).\par This can be especially true with magic: the ability to cast spells at all may be a gift, but to do it right is a skill, or even many different skills.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.23  Combat Powers\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If a supernormal power can be used to attack a foe, the GM must determine the strength of the Power for damage purposes \emdash  preferably during character creation. An offensive Power is usually handled as a propelled weapon, such as a gun, or as being equivalent to a certain melee weapon. This can just be expressed in terms of damage, though, such as Ball of Fire, +6 damage, or large Claws, +3 damage. (See Section 4.54, Sample Wound Factors List.)\par In the case of a magical or superhero attack, the more potent the attack, the greater the power required, or perhaps the greater the strain on the character who uses it. This can be a penalty to the skill level, greater fatigue, and/or some other disadvantage.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.3 Non-humans\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Some campaigns will have characters (or animals, monsters, etc.) with traits beyond the human norm. In particular, characters with Strength and Speed well above or below the human range are common in role-playing games. Examples include giants, superheroes, pixies, aliens, ogres, intelligent rabbits, robots, etc.\par In Fudge, Strength, Mass and Speed are rated by the GM in terms of Scale for different races. Most other traits that may be different for non-humans are handled with a Racial Bonus or Penalty rather than being on a different Scale \emdash  see Section 2.35. Of course, the GM may assign any trait she wishes in terms of Scale.\par Humans are of Scale 0, unless some other race is the game-world norm. (E.g., if all the PCs are playing pixies or giants. In these cases, the PCs\rquote  race is Scale 0, and humans would be a different Scale.) Non-human races can have a positive or negative number for Scale, depending on whether they are stronger (or bigger or faster) or weaker (or smaller or slower) than humans.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.31  Strength and Mass\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The word Scale used alone always means Strength/ Mass Scale in Fudge \emdash  any other Scale, such as Speed, or Strength without Mass, will be defined as such.\par Each level of Strength (from Terrible to Superb) is defined to be 1.5 times stronger than the previous level. A character with Good Strength is thus 1.5 times as strong as a character with Fair Strength. Note that this progression is not necessarily true for any other attribute. There is a wider range of strength in humans than dexterity, for example: Superb Dexterity is only about twice as good as Fair Dexterity.\par Strength Scale increases in the same way: a Scale 1, Fair Strength individual is 1.5 times stronger than a Scale 0, Fair Strength individual. This holds for each increase in Scale: a Scale 10 Superb Strength creature is 1.5 times stronger than a Scale 9 Superb Strength creature, for example.\par At this point, it is tempting to say that a Scale 1 Fair Strength is equal to a Scale 0 Good Strength. This is true for Strength, but not for Mass. Scale really measures Mass, or Density, and Strength just goes along for the ride.\par In Fudge, Mass has a specific meaning: how wounds affect a character. (This may or may not coincide with the scientific definition of Mass.) It takes more human-powered hits to weaken a giant than a human, for example. She may not really be a healthy giant, but her sheer bulk means that human-sized sword strokes don\rquote t do as much damage relative to her as they would to a human \emdash  unless they hit a vital spot, of course. Likewise, a pixie can be healthy and robust, but not survive a single kick from a human. The difference is Mass, and the strength related to it.\par A Scale 1 Fair Strength fighter has an advantage over a Scale 0 Good Strength fighter, even though their Strengths are equal. The Scale 1 fighter is less affected by the other\rquote s damage due to his mass. Therefore, do not blithely equate Scale 0 Good with Scale 1 Fair.\par Of course, the GM may envision a less massive but harder to kill race than humans. This is best handled by a Racial Bonus (Section 2.35), either as a Toughness Gift (Tough Hide, or Density \emdash  either one would subtract from damage), or by a bonus to Damage Capacity.\par The GM may decide that increased Mass does not necessarily mean of greater size \emdash  the race may be of denser material. Dwarves in northern European legend were derived from stone, and are hence denser than humans. Such a dwarf hits harder and shrugs off damage easier than most humans: he is Scale 1, though shorter than a human. (Of course, the GM should define dwarves\rquote  attributes and Scale to her own requirements.)\par Normally, Strength and Mass are handled by a single Scale figure. That is, if a creature is said to be Scale 7, that means Scale 7 Mass and Scale 7 Strength. Strength can vary within each race just as it can for humans. You can have Scale 10 Superb Strength Giants and Scale 10 Terrible Strength Giants. Unlike Strength, though, it is not recommended that Mass vary much within a race. If you do allow Mass to vary for an individual, it should never be worse than Mediocre or better than Good. In fact, it is far better to call Good Mass a Gift, and Mediocre Mass a fault than treat it as an attribute.\par The GM may choose to separate Strength Scale from Mass Scale. This would allow Pixies of Strength Scale \endash 6 and Mass Scale \endash 4, for example. However, combat between two Pixies would not work the same as combat between two humans. In this case, they would have a harder time hurting each other than humans would, since their Strength Scale (ability to give out damage) is lower than their Mass Scale (ability to take damage). This may actually be what she wants: a super-strong superhero who can dish out punishment but can\rquote t take it can be represented by Strength Scale 10, Mass Scale 2, for example.\par See also Section 4.58, Non-human Scale in Combat.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.32  Speed\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Each level of Speed (from Terrible to Superb) is defined to be 1.2 times faster than the previous level. A character with Good Speed is thus 1.2 times as fast as a character with Fair Speed. This is not the same progression as for Strength.\par Speed Scale increases in the same manner: a Scale 1, Fair Speed individual is 1.2 times faster than a Scale 0, Fair Speed individual. This holds for each increase in Scale: a Scale 10 Superb Speed animal is 1.2 times faster than a Scale 9 Superb Speed animal, for example.\par Speed is not a necessary attribute, of course, and can be ignored entirely if desired. It is included primarily for creatures and vehicles significantly faster than humans. For comparison purposes, assume a Fair Speed human can run at about 10 mph (16 kph) over some distance, provided they are in shape, of course. Sprinting short distance is somewhat faster. This comes to about 15 yards (meters) per three-second combat round.\par Note that in short races, you don\rquote t really have to roll the dice to see if someone of Superb Speed can beat someone of Good Speed \emdash  he can, and will, much more often than rolling the dice would reveal.\par The Speed Scale rises too slowly for comparing such things as race cars or space ships to human movement. In these cases, either use a rough human Scale, or simply set the average space ship at Space Ship Speed Scale 0, and rate others relative to it. Thus, the average race car will be roughly human Scale 12 \emdash  or you can simply call it Race Car Scale 0, and compare other race cars to it. A Space Ship might be Human Scale 100, or Space Ship Scale 0.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.33  Scale Correlations\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The Gamemaster should refer to the following table when assigning a Scale to a race. This only has to be done once, at race creation.\par First, the GM should decide how much stronger (or weaker or faster, etc.) the average member of race X is compared to the average human. For example, she decides that Ogres are three times stronger than humans, and pixies are eight times weaker (which equals 0.12 times as strong). She then needs to look up the closest numbers to these strength multipliers on the table below, and look in the corresponding Scale column to find the correct racial Strength/Mass Scales. In this example, Ogres are Scale 3 creatures, while Pixies are Scale \endash 6. (You may envision Ogres and Pixies differently, of course.)\par (See }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Miscellaneous Charts and Tables}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  for a sample Mass Scale Table with examples.)\par The Strength/Mass Scale number is figured into damage in combat, and all weapons and armor are assumed to be of the same Scale as the wielder. (These numbers have been rounded to the nearest useful number. They are only roughly 1.5 times the previous number, but close enough for game purposes.)\par Other examples: a GM reads in a Medieval text that a dragon is \ldblquote as strong as 20 warriors.\rdblquote  Looking at the table, 20 times the human norm is Scale 8. However, since the average warrior has Good strength, she chooses Scale 9 for the average dragon in her world. Of course, an individual dragon can still have Poor Strength compared to other dragons. This is simply listed as Strength Poor (\endash 2), Scale 9.\par This same GM wants PC leprechauns to be available. While they are small, she decides their magic makes them a bit stronger than their size would otherwise indicate: Scale \endash 4. So a Good Strength leprechaun is as strong as a Terrible Strength human in her world.\par The GM can also use this table to determine relative lifting strength or carrying capacity of characters or beasts if she wishes.\par The GM may require a Strength roll to lift a given object. This will depend on the Scale of the character, of course. Thus, a leprechaun might need a Good Difficulty Level Strength roll to lift a rock that a human could lift without even a roll. (See Chapter 3, Action Resolution.)\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.34  Cost of Scale\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If you are using the Objective Character Creation system, each step of increased Strength/Mass Scale for a player character should cost one attribute level and one gift. This is because each level of Scale includes +1 Strength and extra Mass, which is the equivalent of the Tough Hide gift. However, a generous GM may charge less.\par In a superhero game, this gets very expensive, very quickly. An alternative method: let one supernormal power equal a certain Scale. For example, the GM allows one Power to equal Scale 4 (five times as strong as the average human). A character buys three Powers of super strength and has Scale 12 Strength. Another GM allows Scale 13 (200 times as strong as the average human) to equal one Power. Since a character with two Powers in super strength would have Scale 26 Strength (!), the GM decides to limit the amount of super strength available to one Power.\par A player then raises or lowers his character\rquote s Strength attribute to show how he compares to the average super-strong superhero. Strength can then be raised to Scale 13 Good, for example, at the cost of one attribute level.\par The GM may also allow separate Mass and Strength for superheroes (or even races). For example, the superhero mentioned in Section 2.31 with Strength Scale 10 and Mass Scale 2 would only have to pay for two gifts and ten attribute levels. Or, with a generous GM, a single supernormal power covers the entire cost.\par Other supernormal powers may have levels. Examples include Telekinesis (increased power allows greater weight to be lifted), Telepathy (increased power equals greater range), Wind Control (increased power allows such things as a jet of wind, whirlwind, or tornado), etc.\par In these cases, each level can be bought as a separate supernormal power, which is expensive. Or you could use the option given above for Scale: one supernormal power buys the supernormal ability at a middling power range, and a simple attribute (or even skill) level raises or lowers it from there.\par For Scales below the human norm, each step of Mass Scale includes a fault equivalent to Easily Wounded, and the GM may allow this to be used to balance other traits like any other fault \emdash  see Section 1.64, Trading Traits.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 2.35  Racial Bonuses and Penalties\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 There is rarely any need to use Scale for traits other than Strength, Mass and Speed. It\rquote s easy to imagine someone wanting to play a race that is slightly more intelligent than humans, but a race ten times smarter than the smartest human is so alien that it would be impossible to play. This is true for most traits \emdash  we just can\rquote t grasp such extreme differences from our world view.\par Actually, there is a way to use intelligence in Scale: in a non-quantified manner. For example, when creating a dog character, you can list:\par \par Intelligence:   Great (Scale: Dog)\par \par Since no one is able to quantify inter-species intelligence accurately, do not expect to use it comparatively. It gives an indication that, relative to other dogs, this dog has Great intelligence. The word \ldblquote Scale\rdblquote  isn\rquote t necessary \emdash  \ldblquote Great canine intelligence\rdblquote  works just as well.\par The GM should usually use Racial Bonuses or Penalties for traits other than Strength, Mass and Speed. If the GM envisions halflings as being particularly hardy, she can give them a +1 bonus to Constitution: halfling Fair Constitution equals human Good Constitution. As another example, an alien race, Cludds, have a racial penalty of \endash 1 to Intelligence.\par It is best to use trait levels relative to humans on the character sheets, though you should put the racial-relative term in brackets. (Example: Grahkesh, Intelligence Poor [Cludd Fair].) However, always list Strength relative to the character\rquote s own race, with the Scale (if other than 0), so the Mass will be accurate. See the sample character, Brogo the Halfling (Section 6.311), for an example of both racial bonus and different Scale.\par Racial bonuses and penalties can be used for any type of trait: attributes, skills, gifts, supernormal powers, or faults.\par If using the Objective Character Creation system, each level of a Racial Bonus or Penalty is usually equal to one level of the specific trait raised or lowered normally. That is, if you are granting a +1 to Agility or +1 to Perception for a race, it should cost one attribute level. If a race has a bonus of a Perfect Sense of Direction, it should cost one gift. The innate ability to fly or cast magic spells should cost one supernormal power, etc.\par If a race is at \endash 1 to all Social skills, however, this should only be worth \endash 1 skill level if you have a single skill called Social Skills. If you have many social individual social skills, it should be worth one fault. The converse is true for Bonuses that affect many skills: it should cost one or more gifts.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.4  Legendary Heroes\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Some genres allow human characters to develop beyond the realm of the humanly possible. Such campaigns eventually involve planes of existence beyond the mundane as the PCs require greater and greater challenges.\par This style of gaming can be represented in Fudge by Legendary Levels. Section 1.2, Levels, introduced the concept of Legendary traits as a goal for PCs to work toward. This section expands that concept infinitely.\par If the GM and players prefer this type of gaming, any skill can be raised beyond Legendary. Instead of renaming each level, simply use a numbering system: Legendary 2nd Level Swordsman, Legendary 3rd Level Archer, etc. Attributes can also be raised, but (except for Strength) this is much rarer.\par Each level of Legendary gives a +1 bonus to any action resolution. The character Hugh Quickfinger, for example, has a Longbow skill of Legendary 2nd Level. This gives him a total bonus of +5 (+3 for Superb, and +2 for two levels of Legendary). In any contest against a Fair Longbowman (+0), Hugh should easily triumph.\par The Objective Character Development system, Section 5.2, lists suggested experience point costs for attaining these levels.\par These levels do not automatically exist in any given game: these are strictly optional levels for specific, non-realistic genres.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.5  Magic\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If the Gamemaster wishes to include magic in the campaign, it may be easiest to translate whatever magic system she is familiar with into Fudge. If she wishes to craft her own Fudge magic rules, she should consider what she wants magic to be like in her game world.\par Questions to ask include: What is the source of magic? Is it a natural process, such as mana manipulation? If it does use mana, does the mage create the mana, or is it inherent in a locale? Or does the mage summon other-world entities to do his bidding? Or must the mage find a source of Power and channel it to his own ends? Or is the source of magic something altogether different?\par Can anyone learn to work magic, or is it an inherent talent (that is, does it require a supernormal power)? Are there levels of Power available, and what would having more levels mean? Is a skill also required? Of course, even if a magician must have a Power to cast spells, there may also be magic items that anyone can use \emdash  these are common in tales and legends.\par If beings are summoned, are they evil, good, neutral, confused? How do they feel about being commanded to work for the magician? Can they adversely affect the magician if he fails a spell roll? If Power is being channeled from an external source, is that source in the physical plane or astral? Is it from a living being, or contained in an inanimate object as inert energy, like a piece of coal before going into a fire?\par What is the process of using magic? Does it involve memorized spells? Physical components? Meditation? Complex and time-consuming ritual? How long does it take to cast a spell? Can a spell be read out of a book? Improvised on the spot?\par How reliable is magic? Are there any drawbacks? Any societal attitudes toward magicians? Is it common knowledge that magicians exist, or are they a secret cabal, whose doings are only whispered about in ever-changing rumors?\par Once these issues have been resolved, and the degree of magic in the game decided on, the magic system can be created using Fudge mechanics. A sample magic system, Fudge Magic, is included in Chapter 7, The Addenda.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.6  Miracles\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge assumes miracles are powered by a deity. Some miracles may happen at the deity\rquote s instigation (GM whim, or deus ex machina for plot purposes), and some may be petitioned by characters.\par Miracles may take place in a startling fashion or in a mundane way. In fact, many people believe that miracles occur daily, but we don\rquote t notice them because they appear as simple coincidences. The stranger walking down the road who just happens to have the tools you need to fix your wagon might indeed be just a coincidence, or it may have been divinely arranged that he chanced by at that time. If the tools were simply to appear by themselves, or the wagon fix itself, there would be little doubt that a miracle had occurred. This is neither good nor bad \emdash  the GM can choose either method of granting miracles, and need not feel bound to be consistent.\par The GM must decide whether miracles can occur in her world, and whether they can be called by character petition. If the latter, then she has to make many other decisions. Can any character petition a particular deity? Does it matter if the character is actually a member of a religious order? How important is the character\rquote s behavior \emdash  would a deity help a member of a particular religious order even if he had been acting against the deity\rquote s goals? How certain is the miracle to occur? How soon will it become manifest? How broad and how specific can requests be? Are any Ritual or Supplication skills needed to petition a deity, or can anyone simply breathe a prayer for help?\par The answers will vary from GM to GM \emdash  no \ldblquote generic\rdblquote  system of miracles is possible. A sample miracle system, Fudge Miracles, is included in Chapter 7, The Addenda.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.7  Psi\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Again, it is probably easiest for the GM to translate whatever psionics rules she knows to Fudge. As a simple system, each psionic ability can be a separate supernormal power. The ability to read minds, or foresee the future, or telekinetically move an object, etc., each cost one supernormal power (two gifts). Just how powerful the psionic ability is depends on the level of psi the GM wants for the game world. Someone who can telekinetically lift a battleship is obviously more powerful than someone who can\rquote t lift anything heavier than a roulette ball \emdash  though the latter may make more money with his power, if he\rquote s highly skilled!\par If the game world has more than one level of power available, then a character must spend multiple free power levels to get the higher levels. See also Section 2.34, Cost of Scale.\par In general, higher levels of Psi Powers equal greater range, or the ability to affect larger or more subjects at once, or access to a greater number of related skills (a low Telepathy Power lets you send your thoughts to another, for example, but greater Power lets you read minds, send painful waves of energy, sense emotions, and possibly even control others). A higher level might also let you use less fatigue or have a lower risk of burnout, take less time in concentration to use, or allow more uses per day, or be used in a broader range of conditions (a low ESP Power can only be accessed in a darkened room, for example, while a high Power level can be used at any time), and so on.\par The GM may also require skills to use these powers. Having the psionic ability to use telekinesis just allows you to pick an object up with your mental powers, and move it crudely about. Fine manipulation, such as picking a pocket, requires a successful roll against a telekinetic skill.\par A sample psi system, Fudge Psi, is included in Chapter 7, The Addenda.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.8  Superpowers\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If the campaign allows superpowers similar to those found in comic books, there will probably be a wide variety of powers available. How many an individual character can have depends on the power level of the campaign. A common treatment of superheroes involves faults related to Powers, which makes more Powers available to the character. For example, a super hero is able to fly, but only while intangible. The accompanying fault lowers the cost of the Power to that of a gift.\par There are far too many powers to list in Fudge \emdash  browsing through a comic store\rquote s wares will give you a good idea of what\rquote s available. As with psionics, each power costs one of the free supernormal powers available, and some can be taken in different levels. Potent ones cost two or more of the \ldblquote average\rdblquote  superpowers.\par Super strength is treated as a separate scale \emdash  see Section 2.3, Non-humans. Other superpowers that come in levels are discussed in Section 2.34, Cost of Scale.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 2.9  Cybernetic Enhancements\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Artificial limbs, organs, implants and neural connections to computers are common in some science fiction settings. If these grant powers beyond the human norm, they must be bought with supernormal power levels if using the Objective Character Creation system, or with the GM\rquote s approval in any case.\par If an implant grants a bonus to an attribute, it should cost as much as the attribute bonus, which is not necessarily as much as a supernormal power. Since an artificial implant may occasionally fail, however, the GM can give a slight cost break by also allowing a free skill level elsewhere on the character sheet.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Chapter 3: Action Resolution\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 This chapter covers how to determine whether or not a character succeeds at an attempted action. In the previous chapters, traits were defined in terms of levels: Superb, Great, Good, etc. This chapter explains how those levels affect a character\rquote s chances of success at an action, whether fighting a giant or tracking down a clue. Sometimes a Fair result is sufficient to complete a task, and sometimes a Good or better result is needed. The better your skill, the better your chances of getting these higher results.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 3.1  Action Resolution Terms\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Dice: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Various options for dice are given: players may use either three or four six-sided dice (3d6 or 4d6), or two ten-sided dice as percentile dice (d%), or four Fudge dice (4dF), described in the text. It is also possible to play Fudge diceless.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Unopposed Action: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 some actions are Unopposed, as when a character is trying to perform an action which isn\rquote t influenced by anyone else. Examples include jumping a wide chasm, climbing a cliff, performing a chemistry experiment, etc. The player simply rolls the dice and reads the result.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Rolled Degree:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  this refers to how well a character does at a particular task. If someone is Good at Climbing in general, but the die-roll shows a Great result on a particular attempt, then the rolled degree is Great.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Difficulty Level:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  the GM will set a Difficulty Level when a character tries an Unopposed Action. Usually it will be Fair, but some tasks are easier or harder. Example: climbing an average vertical cliff face, even one with lots of handholds, is a fairly difficult obstacle (Fair Difficulty Level). For a very hard cliff, the GM may set the Difficulty Level at Great: the player must make a rolled degree of Great or higher to climb the cliff successfully.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Opposed Action: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 actions are Opposed when other people (or animals, etc.) may have an effect on the outcome of the action. In this case, each contestant rolls a set of dice, and the results are compared to determine the outcome. Examples include combat, seduction attempts, haggling, tug-of-war, etc.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Relative Degree:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  this refers to how well a character did compared to another participant in an Opposed Action. Unlike a rolled degree, relative degree is expressed as a number of levels. For example, if a PC gets a rolled degree result of Good in a fight, and his NPC foe gets a rolled degree result of Mediocre, he beat her by two levels \emdash  the relative degree is +2 from his perspective, \endash 2 from hers.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Situational Roll:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  the GM may occasionally want a die roll that is not based on a character\rquote s trait, but on the overall situation or outside circumstances. This Situational roll is simply a normal Fudge die roll, but not based on any trait. That is, a result of 0 is a Fair result, +1 a Good result, \endash 1 a Mediocre result, and so on. This is most commonly used with Reaction and damage rolls, but can be used elsewhere as needed. For example, the players ask the GM if there are any passersby on the street at the moment \emdash  they\rquote re worried about witnesses. The GM decides there are none if a Situational roll gives a Good or better result, and rolls the dice. (A close approximation to 50% is an even/odd result: an even result on 4dF occurs 50.6% of the time. Of course, 1d6 or a coin returns an exact 50% probability.)\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Beyond Superb: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 it is possible to achieve a level of rolled degree that is beyond Superb. Rolled degrees from Superb +1 to Superb +4 are possible. These levels are only reachable on rare occasions by human beings. No trait may be taken at (or raised to) a level beyond Superb (unless the GM is allowing a PC to be at Legendary, which is the same as Superb +1 \emdash  see Section 5.2, Objective Character Development). For example, the American baseball player Willie Mays was a Superb outfielder. His most famous catch, often shown on television, is a Superb +4 rolled degree. It isn\rquote t possible for a human to have that level of excellence as a routine skill level, however: even Willie was \ldblquote just\rdblquote  a Superb outfielder, who could sometimes do even better. A GM may set a Difficulty Level beyond Superb for nearly impossible actions.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Below Terrible:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  likewise, there are rolled degrees from Terrible \endash 1 down to Terrible \endash 4. No Difficulty Level should be set this low, however: anything requiring a Terrible Difficulty Level or worse should be automatic for most characters \emdash  no roll needed.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 3.2  Rolling the Dice\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 There is no need to roll the dice when a character performs an action that is so easy as to be automatic. Likewise, an action so difficult that it has no chance to succeed requires no roll, either \emdash  it simply can\rquote t be done. Dice are used solely in the middle ground, where the outcome of an action is uncertain.\par The GM is encouraged to keep die-rolling to a minimum. Do not make the players roll the dice when their characters do mundane things. There is no need to make a roll to see if someone can cook lunch properly, or pick an item from a shelf, or climb a ladder, etc. Don\rquote t even make them roll to climb a cliff unless it\rquote s a difficult cliff or the situation is stressful, such as a chase. (And possibly a Superb climber wouldn\rquote t need a roll for a difficult cliff. He should get up it automatically unless it\rquote s a very difficult cliff.)\par For any action the player character wishes to perform, the Gamemaster must determine which trait is tested. (This will usually be a skill or an attribute.) If the action is Unopposed, the GM also determines the Difficulty Level \emdash  usually Fair. (See also Section 3.5, Opposed Actions.)\par For running Fudge Diceless, see the Addenda, Section 7.42.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 3.21  Reading the Dice: Fudge Dice\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Of the four dice techniques presented in Fudge, this one is recommended. It gives results from \endash 4 to +4 quickly and easily, without intruding into role-playing or requiring complex math or a table.\par Fudge dice are six-sided dice with two sides marked +1, two sides marked \endash 1, and two sides marked 0. They are commercially available from Grey Ghost Press, Inc. \emdash  see http://www.fudgerpg.com.\par You can make your own Fudge dice easily enough. Simply get four normal white d6s. Using a permanent marker, color two sides of each die green, two sides red, and leave the other two sides white. When the ink has dried, spray the dice lightly with clear matte finish to prevent the ink from staining your hands. You now have 4dF: the green sides = +1, the red sides = \endash 1, and the white sides = 0.\par (While you can try to play with normal d6s \emdash  reading: 1,2 = \endash 1;  3,4 =  0; 5,6 = +1 \emdash  this is not recommended. It takes too much effort, and intrudes into role-playing. 4dF is functionally equivalent to 4d3\endash 8, but this is also not recommended for the same reason, even if you have d6s labeled 1-3 twice.)\par To use Fudge dice, simply roll four of them, and total the amount. Since a +1 and a \endash 1 cancel each other, remove a +1 and \endash 1 from the table, and the remaining two dice are easy to read no matter what they are. (Example: if you roll +1, +1, 0, \endash 1, remove the \endash 1 and one of the +1s, as together they equal 0. The remaining two dice, +1 and 0, are easily added to +1.) If there is no opposing pair of +1 and \endash 1 dice, remove any zeros and the remaining dice are again easy to read.\par The result of a die roll is a number between \endash 4 and +4. At the top of the character sheet, there should be a simple chart of the attribute levels, such as:\par \par Superb\par Great\par Good\par Fair\par Mediocre\par Poor\par Terrible\par \par To determine the result of an action, simply put your finger on your trait level, then move it up (for plus results) or down (for minus results).\par Example: Nathaniel, who has a Good Bow Skill, is shooting in an archery contest. The player rolls 4dF, using the procedure described above. If he rolls a 0, he gets a result equal to Nathaniel\rquote s skill: Good, in this case. If he rolls a +1, however, he gets a Great result, since Great is one level higher than his Good Archery skill. If he rolls a \endash 3, unlucky Nathaniel has just made a Poor shot.\par It is not always necessary to figure the exact rolled degree. If you only need to know whether or not a character succeeded at something, it is usually sufficient for the player simply to announce the appropriate trait level and the die roll result. The game goes much faster this way. For example, a player wants his character, Captain Wallop of the Space Patrol, to fly between two asteroids that are fairly close together. The GM says this requires a Great Difficulty Level Piloting roll and asks the player to roll the dice. The player looks up Captain Wallop\rquote s Piloting skill, which is Great, and rolls a +2 result. He simply announces \ldblquote Great +2\rdblquote  as the result. This answer is sufficient \emdash  the GM knows that Captain Wallop not only succeeded at the task, but didn\rquote t even come close to damaging his craft.\par Of course, there are many times when you want to know exactly how well the character did, even if it\rquote s not a matter of being close. If the character is composing a poem, for example, and his Poetry skill is Fair, you will want to figure out what \ldblquote Fair+2\rdblquote  means: he just wrote a Great poem! There are many other instances where degrees of success is more important than merely knowing success/failure.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 3.22  Other Dice Techniques\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For those who don\rquote t want to make or buy Fudge dice, three different options are available:\par 4d6: this method requires 2d6 of one color (or size) and 2d6 of another color or size. First declare which two dice are the positive dice, and which two the negative, then roll all four dice. Do not add the dice in this system. Instead, remove from the table all but the lowest die (or dice, if more than one has the same lowest number showing). If the only dice left on the table are the same color, that is the result: a positive die with a \ldblquote 1\rdblquote  showing is a +1, for example. If there are still dice of both colors showing, the result is \ldblquote 0\rdblquote .\par Examples (p = positive die, n = negative die): you roll p4, p3, n3, n3. The lowest number is a 3, so the p4 is removed, leaving p3, n3 and n3. Since there are both positive and negative dice remaining, the result is 0. On another roll, you get p1, p1, n2, n4. Remove the highest numbers, n2 and n4. This leaves only positive dice, so the result is +1, since a \ldblquote 1\rdblquote  is showing on a positive die, and there are no negative dice on the table.\par 3d6: Roll 3 six-sided dice. Add the numbers and look up the results on the table below. The table is so small that it could easily fit on a character sheet. Example: a roll of 3, 3, 6 is a sum of 12. Looking up 12 on the table yields a result of +1.\par \par Rolled:  3-4\tab 5\tab 6-7\tab 8-9\tab 10-11\tab 12-13\tab 14-15\tab 16\tab 17-18\par Result:   \endash 4\tab \endash 3\tab \endash 2\tab \endash 1\tab +0\tab +1\tab +2\tab +3\tab +4\par \par d%: roll two ten-sided dice, having first declared which will be the \ldblquote tens\rdblquote  digit. Read the tens die and the ones die as a number from 1 to 100 (01 = 1, but 00 = 100), and consult the table below, which should be printed on the character sheet:\par \par Rolled:   1\tab 2-6\tab 7-18\tab 19-38\tab 39-62\tab 63-82\tab 83-94\tab 95-99\tab 00\par Result:  \endash 4\tab \endash 3\tab \endash 2\tab \endash 1\tab +0\tab +1\tab +2\tab +3\tab +4\par \par Of course, the GM may customize this table as she wishes. These numbers were chosen to match 4dF, which the author feels is an ideal spread for Fudge.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 3.23  Success Rates\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The following table is provided so that players can better evaluate their chances of success.\par \tab Chance\tab 4dF\par \tab of achieving\tab or d%\tab 3d6\tab 4d6\par \tab +5 or better:\tab \emdash \tab \emdash \tab 0.2%\par \tab +4 or better:\tab 1%\tab 2%\tab 2%\par \tab +3 or better:\tab 6%\tab 5%\tab 7%\par \tab +2 or better:\tab 18%\tab 16%\tab 18%\par \tab +1 or better:\tab 38%\tab 38%\tab 39%\par \tab   0 or better:\tab 62%\tab 62%\tab 61%\par \tab \endash 1 or better:\tab 82%\tab 84%\tab 82%\par \tab \endash 2 or better:\tab 94%\tab 95%\tab 93%\par \tab \endash 3 or better:\tab 99%\tab 98%\tab 98%\par \tab \endash 4 or better:\tab 100%\tab 100%\tab 99.8%\par \tab \endash 5 or better:\tab \emdash \tab \emdash \tab 100%\par \par Thus, if your trait is Fair, and the GM says you need a Good result or better to succeed, you need to roll +1 or better. You\rquote ll do this about two times out of five, on the average.\par You\rquote ll notice that using 3d6 or 4d6 the results, while slightly different, are close enough for a game called Fudge. The 4d6 results do allow +/\endash 5, however, but this shouldn\rquote t be a problem since they occur so rarely. In fact, you could use 5dF to allow +/\endash 5 if you wanted\u8230\'c9.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 3.3  Action Modifiers\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 There may be modifiers for any given action, which can affect the odds referred to in the preceding section. Modifiers temporarily improve or reduce a character\rquote s traits.\par Examples: Joe, Good with a sword, is Hurt (\endash 1 to all actions). He is thus only Fair with his sword until he\rquote s healed. Jill has Mediocre Lockpicking skills, but an exceptionally fine set of lock picks gives her a Fair Lockpicking skill while she\rquote s using them.\par If a character has a secondary trait that could contribute significantly to a task, the GM may allow a +1 bonus if the trait is Good or better.\par Example: Verne is at the library, researching an obscure South American Indian ritual. He uses his Research skill of Good, but he also has a Good Anthropology skill. The GM decides this is significant enough to give Verne a Great Research skill for this occasion. If his Anthropology skill were Superb, the GM could simply let Verne use that instead of Research: you don\rquote t get to be Superb in Anthropology without having done a lot of research.\par Other conditions may grant a +/\endash 1 to any trait. In Fudge, +/\endash 2 is a large modifier \emdash  +/\endash 3 is the maximum that should ever be granted except under extreme conditions.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 3.4  Unopposed Actions\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For each Unopposed action, the GM sets a Difficulty Level (Fair is the most common) and announces which trait should be rolled against. If no Skill seems relevant, choose the most appropriate Attribute. If there is a relevant Skill, but the character is untrained in it (it\rquote s not listed on his character sheet), then use the default: usually Poor. If a high attribute could logically help an untrained skill, set the default at Mediocre. For example, a character wishes to palm some coins without being observed. The GM says to use Sleight of Hand skill, but the character is untrained in Sleight of Hand. The player points out that the character\rquote s Dexterity attribute is Superb, so the GM allows a default of Mediocre Sleight of Hand for this attempt.\par The player then rolls against the character\rquote s trait level, and tries to match or surpass the Difficulty Level set by the GM. In cases where there are degrees of success, the better the roll, the better the character did; the worse the roll, the worse the character did.\par In setting the Difficulty Level of a task, the GM should remember that Poor is the default for most skills. The average trained climber can climb a Fair cliff most of the time, but the average untrained climber will usually get a Poor result. In the example in Section 3.2 (Nathaniel shooting at an archery target), if the target is large and close, even a Mediocre archer could be expected to hit it: Mediocre Difficulty Level. If it were much smaller and farther away, perhaps only a Great archer could expect to hit it regularly: Great Difficulty Level. And so on.\par Example of setting Difficulty Level: Two PCs (Mickey and Arnold) and an NPC guide (Parri) come to a cliff the guide tells them they have to climb. The GM announces this is a difficult, but not impossible, cliff: a Good Difficulty Level roll is required to scale it with no delays or complications. Checking the character sheets, they find that Parri\rquote s Climbing skill is Great and Mickey\rquote s is Good. Arnold\rquote s character sheet doesn\rquote t list Climbing, so his skill level is at default: Poor. Parri and Mickey decide to climb it, then lower a rope for Arnold.\par Parri rolls a +1 result: a rolled degree of Superb. She gets up the cliff without difficulty, and much more quickly than expected. Mickey rolls a \endash 1, however, for a rolled degree of Fair. Since this is one level lower than the Difficulty Level, he\rquote s having problems. Had Mickey done Poorly or even Mediocre, he would perhaps have fallen \emdash  or not even been able to start. Since his rolled degree is only slightly below the Difficulty Level, though, the GM simply rules he is stuck half way up, and can\rquote t figure out how to go on. Parri ties a rope to a tree at the top of the cliff, and lowers it for Mickey. The GM says it is now Difficulty Level: Poor to climb the cliff with the rope in place, and Mickey makes this easily on another roll.\par Arnold would also need a Poor rolled degree to climb the cliff with the rope, but since his skill is Poor, they decide not to risk it. Mickey and Parri have Arnold loop the rope under his arms, and pull him up as he grabs handholds along the way in case they slip. No roll is needed in this case, unless they are suddenly attacked when Arnold is only half way up the cliff\u8230\'c9.\par (The whole situation was merely described as an example of setting Difficulty levels. In actual game play, the GM should describe the cliff, and ask the players how the characters intend to get up it. If they came up with the idea of Parri climbing the cliff and lowering a rope, no rolls would be needed at all \emdash  unless, possibly, time was a critical factor, or there were hidden difficulties the GM chose not to reveal because they couldn\rquote t have been perceived from the bottom of the cliff.)\par Occasionally, the GM will roll in secret for the PC. There are times when even a failed roll would give the player knowledge he wouldn\rquote t otherwise have. These are usually information rolls. For example, if the GM asks the player to make a roll against Perception attribute (or Find Hidden Things skill), and the player fails, the character doesn\rquote t notice anything out of the ordinary. But the player now knows that there is something out of the ordinary that his character didn\rquote t notice\u8230\'c9. Far better for the GM to make the roll in secret, and only mention it on a successful result.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 3.5  Opposed Actions\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 To resolve an Opposed action between two characters, each side rolls dice (4dF, d%, 3d6, 4d6, or whatever is your chosen dice technique) against the appropriate trait and announces the result. The traits rolled against are not necessarily the same: for example, a seduction attempt would be rolled against a Seduction skill for the active participant (or possibly Appearance attribute) and against Will for the resisting participant. There may be modifiers: someone with a vow of chastity might get a bonus of +2 to his Will, while someone with a Lecherous fault would have a penalty \emdash  or not even try to resist.\par The Gamemaster compares the rolled degrees to determine a relative degree. For example, Lisa is trying to flimflam Joe into thinking she\rquote s from the FBI and rolls a Great result. This is not automatic success, however. If Joe also rolls a Great result on his trait to avoid being flimflammed (Knowledge of Police Procedure, Learning, Intelligence, etc. \emdash  whatever the GM decides is appropriate), then the relative degree is 0: the status quo is maintained. In this case, Joe remains unconvinced that Lisa is legitimate. If Joe rolled a Superb result, Lisa\rquote s Great result would have actually earned her a relative degree of \endash 1: Joe is not going to be fooled this encounter, and will probably even have a bad reaction to Lisa.\par The Opposed action mechanism can be used to resolve almost any conflict between two characters. Are two people both grabbing the same item at the same time? This is an Opposed action based on a Dexterity attribute \emdash  the winner gets the item. Is one character trying to shove another one down? Roll Strength vs. Strength (or Wrestling skill) to see who goes down. Someone trying to hide from a search party? Perception attribute (or Find Hidden skill) vs. Hide skill (or Camouflage, Stealth, etc.). Trying to out-drink a rival? Constitution vs. Constitution (or Drinking skill, Carousing, etc.). And so on.\par Some Opposed actions have a minimum level needed for success. For example, an attempt to control a person\rquote s mind with a Telepathy skill might require at least a Fair result. If the telepath only gets a Mediocre result, it doesn\rquote t matter if the intended victim rolls a Poor resistance: the attempt fails. Most combat falls into this category \emdash  see Chapter 4.\par For an example of Opposed actions involving more than two characters, see Section 4.34, Multiple Combatants in Melee.\par An Opposed action can also be handled as an Unopposed action. When a PC is opposing an NPC, have only the player roll, and simply let the NPC\rquote s trait level be the Difficulty Level. This method assumes the NPC will always roll a 0. This emphasizes the PCs\rquote  performance, and reduces the possibility of an NPC\rquote s lucky roll deciding the game.\par As a slight variation on the above, the GM rolls 1dF or 2dF when rolling for an NPC in an opposed action. This allows some variation in the NPC\rquote s ability, but still puts the emphasis on the PCs\rquote  actions.\par For those without Fudge dice, the GM can simply roll 1d6 for an NPC. On a result of 2-5, the NPC gets the listed trait level as a result. On a result of 1, the NPC did worse than her trait level; on a result of 6 the NPC did better than her trait level. Those who want to know precisely how much better or worse should roll a second d6: \par 1,2,3 = +/\endash 1 (as appropriate)\par  4,5  = +/\endash 2\par   6   = +/\endash 3\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 3.6  Critical Results\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Critical results are an optional Fudge rule for GMs who like the idea. A natural rolled result of +4 can be considered a critical success \emdash  the character has done exceptionally well, and the GM may grant some special bonus to the action. Likewise, a natural result of \endash 4 is a critical failure, and the character has done as poorly as he possibly can in the given situation.\par Note that achieving +/\endash 4 with die modifiers does not count as a critical result, though the character has done exceptionally well or poorly. When a natural critical result is rolled, the GM may ignore what the rolled degree would be, and treat it as an automatic beyond Superb or below Terrible result.\par Optionally, if a character gets a rolled degree four or more levels better than the Difficulty Level, he has gotten a critical success. Likewise, four levels below a Difficulty Level is a critical failure.\par A critical result in combat can mean many things: one fighter falls down, or drops his weapon, or is hurt extra badly, or is stunned for a round and can\rquote t even defend himself, or is temporarily blinded, or knocked out, etc. The GM should be creative, but not kill a character outright.\par The GM may even wish to make a table, such as these sample melee critical results:\par \par Roll 2d6:\par 2\tab Blinded for the next combat round \emdash  no defense or offense!\par 3\tab Fall down: skill at \endash 2 for one round.\par 4\tab Armor badly damaged \emdash  no armor value rest of fight!\par 5\tab Weapon finds chink in armor \emdash  do not subtract for armor.\par 6\tab Off balance \emdash  skill at \endash 1 next turn.\par 7\tab Drop Weapon.\par 8\tab Weapon breaks, but still useful: \endash 1 to damage.\par 9\tab \u8230\'c9\par \par And so on \emdash  finish and customize to your tastes.\par This is an easy way to achieve a lot of detail without complicating Fudge. Those with Internet access are invited to add any interesting critical results tables they create to the Fudge sites.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 3.7  NPC Reactions\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sometimes a non-player character has a set reaction to the PCs. Perhaps she\rquote s automatically their enemy, or perhaps the party has rescued her, and earned her gratitude. But there will be many NPCs that don\rquote t have a set reaction. When the PCs request information or aid, it might go smoothly or it might not go well at all. Negotiation with a stranger is always an unknown quantity to the players \emdash  it may be so for the GM, too.\par When in doubt, the GM should secretly make a Situational roll. If the PC in question has a trait that can affect a stranger\rquote s reaction, this should grant a +/\endash 1 (or more) to the result. Examples include Appearance (which could be an attribute, gift or fault), Charisma, Reputation, Status, and such habits as nose-picking or vulgar language. The Reaction roll can also be modified up or down by circumstances: bribes, suspicious or friendly nature of the NPC, proximity of the NPC\rquote s boss, observed PC behavior, etc.\par The higher the Reaction roll result, the better the reaction. On a Fair result, for example, the NPC will be mildly helpful, but only if it\rquote s not too much effort. She won\rquote t be helpful at all on Mediocre or worse results, but will react well on a Good result or better.\par Example: Nathaniel needs some information about the local duke, who he suspects is corrupt. He has observed that folks are reticent to talk about the duke to strangers. Nathaniel decides to approach a talkative vegetable seller at the open market. Nathaniel has an average appearance (no modifier), but is charismatic: +1 to any Reaction roll. He makes small talk for a while, then slowly brings the duke into the conversation. The GM decides this was done skillfully enough to warrant another +1 on the reaction roll. However, the situation is prickly: \endash 2 in general to elicit any information about the sinister local ruler. This cancels Nathaniel\rquote s bonuses. The GM rolls in secret, and gets a Fair result. The old lady slips out a bit of useful information before realizing what she\rquote s just said. At that point she clams up, but Nathaniel casually changes the subject to the weather, dispelling her suspicions. He wanders off to try his luck elsewhere.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Chapter 4: Combat\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Unless one participant is unaware of an attack or decides to ignore it, combat is an Opposed action in Fudge. The easiest way to handle combat in Fudge is as a series of Opposed actions. This can be done simply or with more complexity. The author of Fudge uses simple and loose combat rules in order to get combat over with quickly and get back to more interesting role-playing. This chapter, largely optional, is for players who prefer combat options spelled out in detail.\par Melee combat and Ranged combat are treated separately.\par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.1  Combat Terms\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Melee:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  any combat that involves striking the opponent with a fist or hand-held weapon. Any attack from further away is a Ranged attack.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Story Element: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 a distinct segment of the storyline in the game. In combat, the interval between story elements can be a practical place for a die roll.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Combat Round: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 an indeterminate length of time set by the GM \emdash  around three seconds seems reasonable to some people, while that seems grossly short or absurdly long to others. A given GM\rquote s combat round may vary in length, depending on the situation. Generally, when each character involved has made an action, a given round is over.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Offensive damage factors:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  those which contribute to damaging an opponent: Strength (if using a Strength-driven weapon), Scale, and deadliness of weapon.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Defensive damage factors:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  those which contribute to reducing the severity of a received blow: Scale, armor, and possibly Damage Capacity.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Total damage factor}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  (or simply damage factor): the attacker\rquote s offensive damage factor minus the defender\rquote s defensive damage factor.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.2  Melee Combat\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge gives three options available for handling the pacing of melee combat: moving from story element to story element, using simultaneous combat rounds, or alternating combat turns. An individual GM may devise others.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.21  Story Elements\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 In the simplest combat system, the GM explains the situation in as much detail as is apparent, then asks the players to describe what their characters are doing. The more complete the description of their characters\rquote  actions, the better the GM knows how to assess the situation. This can be important if she has something that won\rquote t be revealed until the middle of a battle. Die rolls, if any, are required by the GM for each story element.\par A story element is the smallest unit of time in this type of combat resolution. The GM may break the battle down into several story elements, or treat the whole encounter as one element. This depends on the GM\rquote s style, the importance of the battle, the number of participants, whether or not there are unexpected surprises, etc. Each element should be a dramatic unit.\par For example, the PCs are faced with a detachment of guards at the door while the evil mastermind is trying to activate the Doomsday machine at the back of the room. The fight with the guards might be one element while the confrontation with Dr. Doomsday could be a second. Another GM might treat the whole battle as one story element, while a third GM would treat each 5-second segment separately. Whatever the number of elements, keep the battle description as word-oriented as possible.\par The GM may ask for a single die roll from a player occasionally, or require three rolls and take the median roll.\par (The median is the middle value die roll, which may be the same as either the high or low die roll. For example, if the player rolls a Good, a Mediocre, and a Superb result, the median is Good, since it\rquote s the result in between Mediocre and Superb. But a result of Poor, Great, and Great gives a median die roll of Great. Using a median tends to soften the role of extreme luck. Some GMs use a median when a single die result represents many actions.)\par Once the GM has decided which trait (or traits) each PC should use for this combat, she then gives them a modifier, ranging from \endash 3 to +3. Zero should be the most common modifier. The modifier is based partly on how well the PCs\rquote  plan would work, given what the GM knows of the NPCs, and partly on circumstances: fatigue, lighting, footing, surprise, weapon superiority, bravery or cowardice of NPCs, wounds, etc.\par Here is a long example of story element style of combat:\par Gunner, separated from the other PCs, surprises five members of a rival gang in a garage. The player announces that Gunner will shout and charge the rival mob, carrying his Tommy gun as if he\rquote s about to fire \emdash  they don\rquote t know it\rquote s irreparably jammed. He hopes to see them run away, hit the dirt, or freeze in fear. He\rquote ll then use his Tommy gun as a club, starting at the left end of their line. He\rquote ll keep his current opponent in between him and the others as long as possible. He hopes to then roll up their line, one at a time, keeping the wall to his left side as he charges.\par The GM makes a Situational roll for the mob: Mediocre. The mob members don\rquote t recover quickly from their surprise, so she gives Gunner a +1 to his Brawling skill of Good for this plan. She also decides that one mobster will run away and the others won\rquote t draw their guns until Gunner has already engaged the first enemy. His Running skill is Great, so she gives him another +1, since he can cover ground quickly. Total modifier for Gunner is +2, bringing his Brawling skill to Superb for this combat. Since this is a fairly long action and she doesn\rquote t want a single unlucky roll to ruin Gunner\rquote s chances, she asks him for three Brawling skill rolls (at the +2 modifier), and to use the median roll.\par Gunner rolls a Good, Superb, and Great result, in that order. The median roll is Great, and the GM decides this is good enough to have downed the first two mobsters, and describes the battle so far in entertaining detail. Now Gunner is facing the last two thugs, who finally have their pistols out and could probably plug him before he charges that far. The GM asks, \ldblquote What does Gunner do now?\rdblquote \par Gunner hurls the Tommy gun into the face of one gunman while making a low diving tackle for the other, hoping to dodge under any bullets. The GM calls for a single roll against Brawling to cover this whole action: Gunner gets a Fair result. The GM rules that Gunner throws the Tommy gun well enough to distract one gunman, but not harm him. He does, however, manage to tackle and subdue his other foe, whose shots all go wild.\par At this point, the GM rules that the mobster grazed by the thrown Tommy gun now steps over and points his pistol to Gunner\rquote s head while he\rquote s kneeling over the other mobster. Gunner wisely heeds the call to surrender and hopes his friends can rescue him\u8230\'c9.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.22  Simultaneous Combat Rounds\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Those who like their combat broken down into discrete bits can use combat \ldblquote rounds.\rdblquote  In simultaneous action rounds, all offensive and defensive maneuvers happen at the same time. This is realistic: few real combats consist of fighters taking turns whacking at each other.\par The GM determines which traits the combatants should roll against. This depends largely on which weapon they are using, which might simply be a fist. Weapon type also affects damage \emdash  see Section 4.5, Wounds.\par Each combatant makes an Opposed action roll. On a relative degree of zero, the combat round is a stand-off \emdash  the fighters either circled each other looking for an opening, or exchanged blows on each other\rquote s shields, etc. \emdash  nobody is hurt.\par A minimum result of Poor is needed to hit a (roughly) equal-sized opponent. That is, a human needs to score a Poor blow (and still win the Opposed action) in order to hit another human. If both opponents roll worse than Poor, the round is a standoff.\par If one opponent is significantly bigger than the other (of a different Scale, at least), he needs a Mediocre or even Fair result to hit his smaller foe, while even a Terrible result will allow the small fighter to hit the larger. (Of course, such a blow must still win the Opposed action.) Extremely small targets, such as a pixie, may require a Good or even a Great result. Examples include humans fighting giants, or very large or small animals.\par If the result is a relative degree other than zero, and the minimum level needed to score a hit is achieved or surpassed, the winner checks to see if he hit hard enough to damage the loser. In general, the better the hit (the greater the relative degree), the greater the likelihood of damage.\par If one combatant is unable to fight in a given round (possibly because he\rquote s unaware of the attacker, or because of a critical result in the previous round \emdash  see Section 3.6, Critical Results), the combat may become an Unopposed Action for the active fighter, usually with a Poor Difficulty Level. If a character can defend himself in some way, such as using a shield, it is still an Opposed Action, but the defending character cannot hurt the other character even if he wins the combat round.\par Combat often takes more than one combat round. Characters are not limited to attacking each round \emdash  they may attempt to flee, negotiate, try a fancy acrobatic stunt, or any other appropriate action.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.23  Alternating Combat Turns\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Using alternating combat turns, each combat round consists of two actions: the fighter with the higher initiative attacks while the other defends, then the second combatant attacks while the first defends. With multiple characters involved in combat, the side with the initiative makes all their attacks, then the other side makes all their attacks. Or the GM may run the combat in initiative order, even if fighters from both sides are interspersed throughout the combat turn.\par Gaining initiative is an Opposed action. If the characters don\rquote t have an Initiative attribute or skill \emdash  such as Reflexes or Speed \emdash  simply use Opposed Situational rolls. A gift such as Combat Reflexes can grant a +1 to initiative. Surprise may grant a bonus to the roll, or give automatic initiative. Initiative can be rolled once for each battle or once each round. Perhaps a character could trade skill for initiative: attack hastily (+1 to initiative that round) but be slightly off balance because of it (\endash 1 to attack and defend that round).\par Each attack is an Opposed Action: the attacker\rquote s Offensive skill (Sword, Melee Weapon, Martial Art, etc.) against a defender\rquote s Defensive skill (Shield, Parry, Dodge, Duck, etc.). This type of combat take longer than simultaneous rounds, but some players feel it gives a character more control over his own fate.\par Using these rules, a Defensive parry skill may simply equal the weapon skill, or it may be a separate skill that must be bought independently of an Offensive skill. The GM must tell the players at character creation which method she is using \emdash  or allow them extra levels on the fly to adjust their defensive abilities.\par Some weapons, such as an Axe, are poor parrying weapons. Players should ask the GM at character creation if a weapon may be used to parry and still be used to attack without penalty in the next turn \emdash  and give their characters decent Shield or Dodge skills to compensate for poor parrying weapons.\par All-out offensive and defensive tactics can be used. A character forfeits his attack for a round if he chooses All-out defense, and is at \endash 2 on his defense on his opponent\rquote s next turn if choosing All-out offense \emdash  or perhaps gets no defense at all!\par The default defense for animals depends on their type: carnivores will usually have a Defense value one level less than their Offense, while this is reversed for most prey species.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.3  Melee Combat Options\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The various options listed below may be used with any melee system. This is not a comprehensive or \ldblquote official\rdblquote  list of options. The GM should, in fact, consider these options merely as examples to stimulate her imagination. The GM may wish to import complex combat options from other games into Fudge.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.31  Melee Modifiers\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Some situations call for one side or the other\rquote s trait level to be modified. Here are some examples:\par A fighter who is Hurt is at \endash 1, while one who is Very Hurt is at \endash 2.\par If one fighter has a positional advantage over the other, there may be a penalty (\endash 1 or \endash 2) to the fighter in the worse position. Examples include bad footing, lower elevation, light in his eyes, kneeling, etc.\par Subtract the value of a shield from the opponent\rquote s weapon skill. A small shield has a value of +1 in melee combat only, while a medium shield has a value of +1 in melee combat and +1 to defense against ranged attacks (if the shield material is impervious to the weapon). A large shield (+2 in all combat) is cumbersome to lug around. The larger the shield carried, the more the GM should assess penalties for things such as acrobatic and other fancy maneuvers. Shields can also be used offensively to push an opponent back, for example, or knock someone over.\par Compare combatants\rquote  weapon sizes and shields (see Section 4.54, Sample Wound Factors List). If one fighter\rquote s weapon + shield value is +2 (or more) greater than the other fighter\rquote s weapon + shield value, the fighter with the smaller weapon is at \endash 1 to his combat skill. (Example: one fighter has a Two-handed sword: +4 to damage. His opponent has a knife and an average shield: +1 to damage, +1 for shield makes a total of +2. The knife wielder is at \endash 1 to skill in this combat since his weapon modifier is \endash 2 less than the sword fighter\rquote s.)\par Aiming at a specific small body part (such as an eye or hand) will require a minimum result of Good or Great to hit and also have a \endash 1 to the trait level. If a result of Great is needed and the fighter only gets a Good result but still wins the Opposed action, he hits the other fighter \emdash  but not in the part aimed for.\par A fighter may have a magical blessing (+1 or more) or curse (\endash 1 or worse).\par All-out offense, such as a berserk attack, grants a +1 to the combat skill (and an additional +1 for damage, if successful). However, if an all-out attacker ties or loses the Opposed action, the other fighter wins, and gets +2 to damage!\par An All-out defensive stance earns a +2 to the combat skill, but such a combatant cannot harm his foe except with a critical result.\par A successful All-out Defense and a successful Perception or Tactics roll produces a \endash 1 penalty to the opponent on the next round. The fighter takes a few seconds to scope out the area and maneuvers to take advantage of any terrain or conditional irregularity. Similar combat subtleties are possible, and encouraged \emdash  taking a successful All-out defense one round can allow a player to try an acrobatics maneuver the next combat round without risk of being hit, for example.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.32  Offensive/Defensive Tactics\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 This optional rule, used with simultaneous combat rounds, allows more tactical flavor to combat at a small expense of complexity. This option replaces the All-out attack and defense options listed above, and allows for both combatants to be injured in the same combat round.\par Before each round, a fighter may choose to be in a normal posture, an offensive posture or defensive posture. An offensive or defensive stance increases combat skill in one aspect of combat (offense or defense), and decreases the same skill by an equal amount for the other aspect of combat.\par There are five basic options:\par +2 to Offense, \endash 2 to Defense\par +1 to Offense, \endash 1 to Defense\par Normal Offense and Defense\par \endash 1 to Offense, +1 to Defense\par \endash 2 to Offense, +2 to Defense\par Each combat round, a player secretly chooses a combat stance by selecting two Fudge dice and setting them to a result from +2 to \endash 2, which represents an offensive modifier. (The defensive modifier shown above with the offensive modifier is automatically included.) Both sides simultaneously reveal their choices.\par For those without Fudge dice, choose one die placed as follows:\par \tab Die face:\tab Option:\par \tab 1\tab \endash 2 to offense\par \tab 2\tab \endash 1 to offense\par \tab 3,4\tab Normal offense\par \tab 5\tab +1 to offense\par \tab 6\tab +2 to offense\par Each fighter then makes a single Opposed action roll as normal. The result is applied to both offense and defense, however, and will thus have different results for offense and defense if anything other than a normal posture is chosen. The offensive rolled result of each fighter is then compared to the defense of the other fighter.\par For example, a fighter with Good sword skill chooses +1 to offense and \endash 1 to defense for a particular combat round: his offensive sword skill is Great this round, while his defensive sword skill is Fair. His opponent, a Great swordswoman, chooses normal posture. The swordswoman rolls a \endash 1: a Good result for both her offense and defense. The first fighter rolls a 0 result: his offensive rolled result is Great, his defense is Fair.\par His offense result of Great is compared with her Good defense: he wins by +1. However, her offense result of Good is simultaneously compared with his defense of Fair: she also wins the Opposed action by +1. Both sides check for damage, to see if they got through each other\rquote s armor \emdash  see Section 4.5, Wounds.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.33  PCs vs. NPCs\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If a PC is fighting an NPC the GM can treat combat as an Unopposed action by assuming the NPC will always get a result equal to her trait level. In this case, the PC will have to tie the NPC\rquote s trait level to have a stand-off round, and beat the NPC\rquote s trait in order to inflict damage. This option stresses the player characters\rquote  abilities by disallowing fluke rolls by NPCs.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.34  Multiple Combatants in Melee\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When more than one opponent attacks a single fighter, they have, at least, a positional advantage. To reflect this, the lone fighter is at \endash 1 to his skill for each additional foe beyond the first. (For epic-style games, with a few heroes battling hordes of enemies, this penalty can be reduced, or the GM can simply give the hordes Poor skills and low Damage Capacity \emdash  which is not out of character for a horde.)\par The lone fighter rolls once, and the result is compared with each of the opponents\rquote  rolled degrees, one after the other. The solo combatant has to defeat or tie all of the opponents in order to inflict a wound on one of them. If he beats all of his foes, he may hit the foe of his choice. If he ties his best opponent, he can only wound another whose result is at least two levels below his.\par Example: Paco is facing three thugs, who have just rolled a Great, Good, and Mediocre result, respectively. Paco rolls a Great result, tying the best thug. He hits the thug who scored a Mediocre result (at least two levels below his result) and is not hit himself (he tied the best thug).\par The lone fighter takes multiple wounds in a single round if two or more enemies hit him. Usually, he can inflict damage on only one foe in any given round \emdash  his choice of those he bested. It\rquote s also possible to allow a sweeping blow to damage more than one foe at a time. Of course, this slows a slash down: reduce damage done by 1 or 2 for each foe cut through.\par A well-armored fighter facing weak opponents can simply concentrate on one foe and let the others try to get through his armor (that is, not defend himself at all against some of his attackers). In this case, the lone fighter can damage his chosen foe even if he is hit by other, ignored foes. This is historically accurate for knights wading through peasant levies, for example. There may or may not be a penalty for the lone fighter in this case.\par There\rquote s a limit to the number of foes that can simultaneously attack a single opponent. Six is about the maximum under ideal conditions (such as wolves, or spear-wielders), while only three or four can attack if using weapons or martial arts that require a lot of maneuvering space. If the lone fighter is in a doorway, only one or two fighters can reach him.\par When multiple NPCs beset a lone PC, the GM may wish to use the option in Section 4.33, PCs vs. NPCs. This will save a lot of die rolling.\par Alternately, she may wish to roll only once for all the NPCs. The lone fighter is still at \endash 1 per extra opponent. The GM rolls 2dF, and applies the result to each NPC. For example, if the GM gets a +1 result, each attacker scores a +1.\par For those without Fudge dice, the GM could simply use the 1d6 method discussed in Section 3.5, Opposed Actions.\par Example: Three NPC pirates, complete with eye-patches, scars, earrings, sneers and generally bad attitudes, are attacking dashing PC hero Tucker. The pirates (whose names are Molly, Annie, and Maggie) are Fair, Good, and Mediocre, respectively, at combat skills. Tucker is a Superb swordsman, but is at \endash 2 for having two extra fighters attacking him at once: his skill is Good for this combat. The GM wants to roll just once (applying the result to all three pirates) rather than rolling three times each combat round.\par Rolling 2dF, she gets a +1 on the first round. The pirates have just gotten Good, Great, and Fair results, respectively. If Tucker scores a Superb result, he could hit the pirate of his choice and remain unhit. On a Great result, Tucker would be unhit, and could land a blow on Maggie. On a Good result, he doesn\rquote t hit anyone, but Annie hits him. If Tucker rolls a Fair result, both Molly and Annie would hit him. The process is repeated each round.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.35  Hit Location\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A light blow to an eye is very different from a light blow to an armored shoulder, or to a shield. Using a hit location system adds flavor to combat and the description of a character\rquote s equipment, wounds \emdash  and scars! Many games have a hit location system, and a GM can easily translate one she is familiar with to Fudge. Or she can use the simple system given here.\par The simplest system is not to worry about \ldblquote called shots.\rdblquote  Merely say the better the relative degree, the better the location of the blow. Winning a battle by +8 will allow the attacker to pierce an eye, if desired. Hopefully, the players will describe their actions in such detail that the GM will know how close they came to their objective merely by looking at the relative degree.\par A more complicated system: an attacker can announce that he is aiming at a specific body location \emdash  this must be done before rolling to hit. The GM decides the minimum relative degree necessary for such a shot to succeed, usually ranging from 2 to 4, though extreme locations (such as an eyeball) are harder to hit. So if a player wishes his character to hit his opponent\rquote s weapon arm, the GM can respond, \ldblquote You have to win by 2 to do so.\rdblquote  If the player then does win by relative degree 2 or more, the weapon arm is hit, and the wound is specific to that arm.\par If the attacker wins the combat round, but not by the minimum relative degree needed to hit the called target, the defender names which part of the body \emdash  or shield! \emdash  is hit. This will most likely be general body (if there is no shield), but it could be the off-hand, which would carry a lesser combat penalty than a wound to the torso. The GM may have to fudge some here.\par A damaged specific body part can be described as being Scratched (no real game effect), Hurt (a penalty to use, but the body part still functions), and Incapacitated. After battle is the time to decide if an Incapacitated body part can be healed, or is permanently Incapacitated.\par A Hurt body part is generally at \endash 1 to its normal use. A Hurt sword arm gives a \endash 1 penalty to combat, for example, while a Hurt leg is \endash 1 to any running, acrobatics, etc. A Hurt eye is \endash 1 to vision, and so on.\par To determine the exact level of the damage, the GM should consider how well the hit scored, as well as the Strength of the attacker and the weapon being used. Winning by the minimum relative degree necessary to hit the specific body part shouldn\rquote t make the victim Incapacitated unless the attacker is of a much larger Scale than the defender. On the other hand, an arm hit with a battle axe wielded by a large, berserk Viking has a good chance of being cut off even if the Viking just rolled exactly what he needed to hit the arm\u8230\'c9.\par As a guideline, if the attacker surpasses the relative degree necessary to hit the body part at all, the part is Scratched or Hurt, depending on Strength and weapon deadliness. If he surpasses it significantly, the part is Hurt or Incapacitated.\par Species other than humans may have a different list of body parts to hit, and/or different difficulty modifiers.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.36  Fancy Stuff\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A lot of fancy maneuvers are possible in Fudge combat. All require a bit of thought on the GM\rquote s part.\par What if you want a Speed or Reflexes trait to affect how often you can strike in combat? How would you handle someone of Good Speed vs. someone of Fair Speed?\par If someone has a Power that speeds him up beyond the human norm, you can simply have him attack every other round as if his opponent wasn\rquote t aware of the attack. That is, every other round, an Unopposed result of Poor or better hits the foe, with no chance to be hit back in return.\par For more subtle differences, the GM may allow an Opposed action to determine if one fighter gets to land a blow first: after declaring their actions, each fighter makes a roll against a Speed trait. The winner of the Opposed action, if any, adds the difference to his weapon skill.\par How about Fudge\rquote s \ldblquote graininess\rdblquote  getting in the way of interesting combat? That is, since there are only seven levels in Fudge, a Good fighter will often meet another Good fighter, and it doesn\rquote t seem right that you can\rquote t meet someone who\rquote s just a little better or worse than you.\par In this case, the GM can create new levels of combat skills (there\rquote s no point in using this option with other skills). These new levels require full experience points to reach, but function only as \ldblquote half\rdblquote  levels, called \ldblquote plus\rdblquote  levels. Thus, you can have:\par Superb +\par Superb\par Great +\par Great\par Good +\par Good\par And so on. In any combat, someone with a \ldblquote +\rdblquote  has the skill level listed before the \ldblquote +\rdblquote , but gets a +1 every other round, starting with the second round. So in a combat between Gus (skill Great) and Ivan (skill Good +), Gus would have the higher skill on on rounds one, three, five, etc. But on rounds two, four, six, etc., Ivan will roll as if he had a Great skill, thus being Gus\rquote s equal those rounds.\par What about swinging on chandeliers and other swashbuckling moves? Since role-playing games have more to do with movies than real life, this should be encouraged if the genre is at all cinematic.\par In these cases, have the player describe his swashbuckling intentions as fully and dramatically as he can. The better the story, the better the bonus to the die roll \emdash  or no roll needed if the outcome is entertaining enough. You may then request a roll against Dexterity, or Acrobatics (or even Chutzpah!) and let that determine how well he accomplished his aim. Maybe the swing on the chandelier came off great, but the landing on the banister was a little rough, so the slide down to slam the villain in the back was a tad off, and instead of knocking him out, you merely made him drop his weapon, but then fell on the floor yourself, and now he\rquote s mad, and maybe you should get up before he picks up his pistol, or you could try to yank the carpet while you\rquote re down there, right next to it, and he seems to standing on it a bit off-balance\u8230\'c9 Whatever is fun!\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.4  Ranged Combat\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Ranged combat may or may not be an Opposed action.\par If the target is unaware of the assault, the attacker makes an Unopposed action roll to see if he hits his target. The GM sets the Difficulty Level based on distance, lighting, cover, etc. Do not modify the attacker\rquote s skill for range, partial cover, or other circumstances \emdash  that\rquote s included in the Difficulty Level. Equipment such as a laser sighting scope can modify the attacker\rquote s skill, though.\par If the defender is aware of the attack it is an Opposed action: the attacker\rquote s ranged weapon skill against the defender\rquote s defensive trait. (A Difficulty Level for range, lighting, etc., is still set by the GM, and is the minimum rolled degree needed to hit.) A defensive roll should be made against a Dodge skill, or Agility attribute, or something similar.\par If the ranged weapon is thrown, there is no modifier to the defense roll. However, a propelled weapon, such as a bow, gun, or beam weapon, is much harder to avoid. In this case, reduce the defender\rquote s trait by \endash 2 or \endash 3. Obviously, the defender isn\rquote t trying to dodge a bullet, but dodging the presumed path of a bullet when an attacker points a gun at him.\par Of course, the defender may decline to dodge, but shoot back instead. In this case, the action is Unopposed \emdash  making the Difficulty Level is all that is needed to hit. The GM may make such actions simultaneous.\par Example: Nevada Slim and the El Paso Hombre are facing off in a showdown. Both are in the open, in the sunlight, so there\rquote s no lighting or cover difficulty. The range is obviously the same for both \emdash  the GM rules it\rquote s a Fair task to hit each other. Slim rolls a Poor result, and the Hombre a Mediocre result. The Hombre\rquote s bullet came closer to Nevada Slim than vice versa, but both missed since neither made the Difficulty Level.\par Another Example: Will Scarlet is shooting a longbow from the greenwood at Dicken, the Sheriff\rquote s man, who has a crossbow. Dicken knows Will is there, because the man next to him just keeled over with an arrow through his chest. Dicken is in the open, in good light, so only range is of any concern to Will Scarlet: the GM says even a Mediocre shot will hit since they are fairly close. The range for Dicken to hit Will is of course the same, but Will is partially hidden behind a log (cover), and just inside the foliage, so the lighting makes it hard to see him clearly. The GM decrees Dicken needs a Good roll to hit Will. Dicken rolls a Fair result, missing Will. Will rolls a Mediocre result, which hits Dicken, even though it wasn\rquote t as good a shot as Dicken\rquote s.\par In both examples, the fighters forfeited their Dodges in order to shoot simultaneously. Each combatant needed to make the appropriate Difficulty Level to hit. Under these conditions, it\rquote s possible for both combatants to succeed in the same combat round. Had Dicken\rquote s shot hit, Will and Dicken would have skewered each other.\par Guns and similar weapons that do not rely on muscle power should be rated for damage at the beginning of the game. No detailed list is provided, but as a rough guideline: The average small hand gun might be of +2 to +3 Strength, while a derringer might be +1 or even +0. Powerful two-handed projectile weapons are at +5 and higher, while bazookas and other anti-tank weapons are at +10 and higher. Science fiction small weapons may do as much damage as a modern bazooka \emdash  but some are designed to capture people without injuring them.\par Automatic weapons can be simulated roughly by allowing more bullets to hit with higher relative degrees. That is, blasting away with a weapon that fires 20 bullets in a combat round and hitting with relative degree +1 \emdash  a graze \emdash  means only one or two hit the target. If a relative degree +8 represents maximum amount of ammunition on target (whatever that may be for a given weapon), then hitting with a +4 means about half maximum hit the target, while +2 means only one quarter.\par If there is no effective armor, simply add a big damage number if lots of bullets hit: this is going to Incapacitate anyone, at the very least. If armor is at all likely to slow down a bullet, you can\rquote t just add a bigger and bigger damage number if more bullets hit: the armor has a chance to slow down each bullet. In this case, rather than roll damage for each bullet, or have them all stopped, the GM needs to fudge some medium result: give a slight damage bonus if more projectiles hit the target.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.5  Wounds\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge offers various methods of tracking wounds, with many options. It is impossible to be 100% accurate when simulating damage to such an intricate mechanism as a living being. This is true even for detailed simulations \emdash  for an abstract role-playing game, it is hard to get close to reality at all.\par Consequently, many GMs don\rquote t try to be very accurate, and want a simple system that works and lets the story flow. Others want as much accuracy as they can get. Fudge presents a simple freeform system that works, and suggests some options to make it more mechanical, and encourages each GM to add as much detail as she is happy with.\par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.51  Wound Levels\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Combat damage to a character can be described as being at one of seven stages of severity. The stages are:\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Undamaged:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  no wounds at all. The character is not necessarily healthy \emdash  he may be sick, for example. But he doesn\rquote t have a combat wound that\rquote s recent enough to be bothering him.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Just A Scratch:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  no real game effect, except to create tension. This may eventually lead to being Hurt if the character is hit again. This term comes from the famous movie line, \ldblquote I\rquote m okay, it\rquote s only a scratch.\rdblquote  The actual wound itself may be a graze, bruise, cut, abrasion, etc., and the GM whose game is more serious in tone may choose to use one of these terms instead.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Hurt: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 the character is wounded significantly, enough to slow him down: \endash 1 to all traits which would logically be affected. A Hurt result in combat can also be called a Light Wound.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Very Hurt: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 the character is seriously hurt, possibly stumbling: \endash 2 to all traits which would logically be affected. A Very Hurt result can also be called a Severe Wound.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Incapacitated:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  the character is so badly wounded as to be incapable of any actions, except possibly dragging himself a few feet every now and then or gasping out an important message. A lenient GM can allow an Incapacitated character to perform such elaborate actions as opening a door or grabbing a gem\u8230\'c9.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Near Death:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  the character is not only unconscious, he\rquote ll die in less than an hour \emdash  maybe a lot less \emdash  without medical help. No one recovers from Near Death on their own unless very lucky.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Dead:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  he has no more use for his possessions, unless he belongs to a culture that believes he\rquote ll need them in the afterlife\u8230\'c9.\par The GM may expand or contract these stages. For example, expand Hurt and Very Hurt to Light Wound, Moderate Wound and Severe Wound. In this case, a Severe Wound might be \endash 3 to all actions \emdash  or the GM might leave it at \endash 2, make Moderate Wound = \endash 1, and make Light Wound something in between a Scratch and Moderate Wound. That is, maybe a Light Wound causes no penalty during combat (you don\rquote t notice such a slight wound in the heat of battle), but after combat the character will be at \endash 1 to all skills until it\rquote s healed (such wounds can be annoying later).\par The GM may allow a high Difficulty Level Willpower roll to reduce or even nullify penalties listed at Hurt, Very Hurt, and possibly Incapacitated. A gift of a High Pain Threshold will reduce the penalties by one level, while a fault of a Low Pain Threshold will increase penalties by one.\par Some players delight in describing their characters\rquote  wounds in detail, even writing resulting scars into the character story.\par Automatic Death: sometimes you don\rquote t have to roll the dice. Holding a knife to a helpless character\rquote s throat is a good example \emdash  no roll needed to kill such a character, but the killer\rquote s karma suffers.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.52  Damage Capacity\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 In Fudge, Damage Capacity determines how wounds affect a character. Damage Capacity may be called Hit Points, if desired. It may be tied to a character trait such as Constitution (or Hardiness, Fitness, Health, Body, Strength, etc.), or it may be a separate trait \emdash  see Section 6.3, Character Examples. It can also be treated as a gift/fault.\par The GM decides how to handle the differing abilities of humans to take damage. It really does vary, but how much is open to debate.\par As an extreme example, take the death of the Russian monk Rasputin, the adviser to Czarina Alexandra, in 1916. He was fed enough cyanide to kill three normal people, but showed no signs of it. He was then shot in the chest and pronounced dead by a physician. A minute later he opened his eyes and attacked his assassins! They shot him twice more, including in the head, and beat him severely with a knuckle-duster. He was again pronounced dead, tied in curtains and ropes, and tossed into a river. When his body was retrieved three days later, it was found he had freed an arm from his bindings before finally dying of drowning! Clearly, the man could soak up damage well beyond most peoples\rquote  abilities. He is not unique, however: there are many cases in history of people being hard to kill.\par On the other hand, the phrase \ldblquote glass jaw\rdblquote  is familiar to most English speakers, referring to those who are hurt from the slightest blow.\par So there is undoubtedly some room for variation in damage capacity in characters.\par If the GM is handling wounds in a freeform matter, make Damage Capacity an attribute and let players rate their characters in it like any other attribute. Or have a gift (Damage Resistant, perhaps) and a fault (Fragile, maybe), and let everyone without either the gift or the fault be normal in this regard. The GM can assess the character\rquote s ability to take damage based on that information and the situation at hand.\par If the GM wants a more numerical approach to wound determination, it requires some forethought. If Damage Capacity is an attribute, the easiest way to rate it numerically in Fudge is the standard:\par +3 for Superb Damage Capacity\par +2 for Great Damage Capacity\par +1 for Good Damage Capacity\par +0 for Fair Damage Capacity\par \endash 1 for Mediocre Damage Capacity\par \endash 2 for Poor Damage Capacity\par \endash 3 for Terrible Damage Capacity\par However, since light metal armor, as listed in Section 4.54, Sample Wound Factors List, only grants a +2 to defense against being wounded, it is easily seen that a Great Damage Capacity is equal to light metal armor. Some GMs will find this absurd: a naked person of Great Damage Capacity can turn a sword as well as an armored person of Fair Damage Capacity. Others will remember Rasputin, and consider it within the bounds of reason \emdash  it could be part body size (vital organs harder to reach) and part healthiness (muscle tissue more resistant to being cut).\par For simplicity, any equation-driven approach to wounds in Fudge assumes the GM will use a Damage Capacity attribute, and it is rated from +3 to \endash 3, as listed above. If you are not happy with this, please make the necessary mental substitution.\par Here are some other possible ways to handle Damage Capacity numerically:\par 1) Make Damage Capacity an attribute, as above, but instead of automatically granting a bonus, require a Damage Capacity die roll every time a character is hit for at least a Light Wound (Hurt result). On a result of:\par Great or better: reduce the severity of the wound by one.\par Mediocre to Good: no adjustment to the severity of the wound.\par Poor or worse: increase the severity of the wound by one.\par This adjustment can either be one wound level, or simply one damage point, as the GM sees fit.\par For certain types of damage \emdash  perhaps from a stun ray or a quarterstaff across the ribs \emdash  the GM can use the values from +3 to \endash 3 without requiring a roll.\par 2) Do not use a Damage Capacity attribute; instead allow the players to take a gift of Damage Resistant (reduces wound severity by one) or a fault of Fragile (increases wound severity by one). Again, this adjustment can be one wound level, or one damage point.\par 3) Use a Damage Capacity attribute, as outlined as the first suggestion under Section 4.57, Recording Wounds. Each hit temporarily reduces your Damage Capacity attribute one or more levels.\par 4) Use a Willpower attribute instead of Damage Capacity. GMs who believe that Rasputin was able to overcome so much damage because his will was focused on overcoming his enemies may use this method. Grant an adjustment to the wound level based on the result of a Willpower die roll. This can be temporary \emdash  until the battle is over \emdash  or actually have a permanent affect on reducing wound severity.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.53  Wound Factors\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When determining how wounded a character is when hit in combat, take into consideration all of the following factors:\par 1) The relative degree the attack succeeded by \emdash  the better the hit, the greater likelihood of damage. Winning a combat round with a relative degree of +1 means you probably hit where the opponent is most heavily armored. Scoring a hit with a +3 finds a chink in the armor.\par 2) The strength of the blow. For muscle-powered weapons, such as melee weapons, unarmed attacks, bows, slings, etc., this is determined by the attacker\rquote s Strength attribute: stronger folks tend to hit harder. The relative Scale modifier is also figured in here. For things like guns, beam weapons, etc., it is relative to the nature of the weapon: a .38 usually does more damage than a .22. The technological level of the weapon can be important.\par 3) The deadliness of the attacker\rquote s weapon. Big weapons tend to do more damage than little weapons; sharp weapons rip tissue more than dull ones, but blunt weapons can cause concussive damage through armor thick enough to stop a sharp weapon. People trained in Karate tend to do more damage than those untrained in any martial art.\par 4) The defender\rquote s armor. People wearing thicker armor, and more of it, tend to get hurt less than those wearing no armor. Armor can be finely differentiated, or simply said to be Light, Medium, or Heavy armor. Science fiction scenarios will have Extra-Heavy armor, and even further levels. Fantasy campaigns may include magic armor that offers even greater protection, sometimes specific against certain types of damage.\par 5) The amount of damage the victim can soak up (Robustness, Damage Capacity, or Mass). Big, healthy guys can take more damage before collapsing than little, sickly guys. But it\rquote s your call if it\rquote s a big, sickly fighter against a little, healthy fellow.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.54  Sample Wound Factors List\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For those who prefer numerical values, here are some suggested numbers to attach to the factors listed in the previous section. These may be customized to taste, of course, and are only offered as a starting point. If used, they should be written down on the character sheet at character creation (probably with the weapons and armor), so as to be readily available during combat.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Offensive factors:\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Character\rquote s Strength (muscle-powered weapons only):\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 +3 for Superb Strength\par +2 for Great Strength\par +1 for Good Strength\par +0 for Fair Strength\par \endash 1 for Mediocre Strength\par \endash 2 for Poor Strength\par \endash 3 for Terrible Strength\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Attacker\rquote s Scale:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Plus the attacker\rquote s Strength Scale(see Section 4.68, Non-human Scale in Combat).\par Note: the attacker\rquote s Strength Scale is relevant only for muscle-powered weapons and for those projectile weapons scaled to the attacker\rquote s size, such as miniature bazookas or giant-sized handguns. A superhero of Scale 10 using an ordinary pistol would not figure his Scale into the Offensive Damage Modifier.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Weapon\rquote s Strength(Guns, Crossbows, Beam weapons, etc.):\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 +/\endash  Strength of weapon(see Section 4.4, Ranged Combat).\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Muscle-Powered Weapon:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \endash 1 for no weapon, not using a Martial Art skill.\par +0 Martial Art skill, or for small weapons(blackjack, knife, brass knuckles,sling, thick boots if kicking, etc.).\par +1 for medium-weight one-handed weapons(billy club, machete, shortsword,epee, hatchet, rock, etc.).\par +2 for large one-handed weapons(broadsword, axe, large club, etc.),or for light two-handed weapons(spear, bow, etc.).\par +3 for most two-handed weapons(polearm, two-handed sword, battleaxe, etc.).\par +1 for sharpness(add to other weapon damageknife becomes +1, shortsword +2,broadsword +3, greatsword +4, etc.).\par Note: For a less lethal game, subtract 1 from each type of weapon except sharpness. (This will lengthen combats.)\par Note: the value of a shield may be subtracted from the opponent\rquote s skill \emdash  see Section 4.31, Melee Modifiers.\par Optional note, as an example of the detail you can achieve in Fudge: for heavy blunt metal weapons, such as maces and flails, halve any protection from the defender\rquote s armor, round down. The concussive damage from such weapons is slowed, but not totally stopped, by most armor. Example: if using a large mace (+2 weapon) against plate armor (+4 armor), the armor only counts as +2 armor.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Defensive factors:\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Character\rquote s Damage Capacity Attribute:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Note: this is optional \emdash  see Section 4.52, Damage Capacity, for a complete discussion.\par +3 for Superb Damage Capacity\par +2 for Great Damage Capacity\par +1 for Good Damage Capacity\par +0 for Fair Damage Capacity\par \endash 1 for Mediocre Damage Capacity\par \endash 2 for Poor Damage Capacity\par \endash 3 for Terrible Damage Capacity\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Armor:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 +1 for light, pliable non-metal armor.\par +2 for heavy, rigid non-metal armor\par +2 for light metal armor.\par +3 for medium metal armor.\par +4 for heavy metal armor.\par +5 or more for science fiction advanced armor.\par Note: magical armor may add anywhere from +1 to whatever the GM will allow to any given armor type above.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Defender\rquote s Mass Scale:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Plus the defender\rquote s Mass Scale(see Section 4.58, Non-human Scale in Combat).\par (If the defender has Mass other than Fair, or a gift of Tough Hide, it should also be figured in.)\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.55  Determining Wound Level\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A given blow will cause a certain level of wounding. In the simplest wound determination system, the GM assesses all of the Wound Factors (Section 4.53) and announces how bad the wound is. (In some cases, however, the PCs won\rquote t know the precise degree of damage. In those cases, the GM can simply say, \ldblquote You think you wounded her, but she\rquote s still on her feet,\rdblquote  or, \ldblquote You don\rquote t notice any effect.\rdblquote )\par As an example, the GM thinks to herself, \ldblquote Okay, the fighter with Good Strength just scored a Great hit with a broadsword. The loser rolled a Fair combat roll, has Good Damage Capacity and heavy leather armor. Hmmm \emdash  I\rquote ll say the Strength and Damage Capacity cancel each other, while the sharp sword should be able to penetrate the leather armor if the blow is good enough. A Great hit against a Fair defense is enough, but not really massive: I\rquote d say the loser is Hurt.\rdblquote  This result would then be announced to the loser of the combat round.\par The GM can also use a Situational roll to help her. Roll the dice behind a GM screen, and let the result guide you. A roll of \endash 1 to +1 isn\rquote t significant \emdash  no change from what you decided. But a roll of +3 or +4 adds a wound level or two to the damage.\par See Section 4.57, Recording Wounds, for details on how to keep track of wounds received.\par That system, while simple and satisfying to a certain type of GM, doesn\rquote t do much for those who prefer the system detailed in Section 4.54, Sample Wound Factors List. There\rquote s no point in figuring out the offensive and defensive factors if you don\rquote t do something with the numbers.\par One system that uses the offensive and defensive factors requires finding the total damage factor. This is derived by adding up all the attacker\rquote s offensive factors and then subtracting all the defender\rquote s factors.\par Example, first Leroy attacking Theodora, then vice versa:\par \par Leroy:\par Good Strength (+1)\par Scale 0\par Broadsword (+2 for size, +1 for sharpness = +3 weapon).\par Offensive damage factors = 1+0+3 = 4\par \par Theodora:\par Fair Damage Capacity (+0)\par Scale 0\par Boiled leather armor (+2)\par Defensive damage factors = 0+0+2 = 2.\par \par Leroy\rquote s total damage factor against Theodora is 4\endash 2 = 2.\par \par Theodora:\par Superb Strength (+3)\par Poleaxe (+4)\par Offensive damage factors = 3+0+4 = 7\par \par Leroy:\par Good Damage Capacity (+1)\par Scale mail armor (+3)\par Defensive damage factors = 1+0+3 = 4.\par Theodora\rquote s total damage factor against Leroy is 7\endash 4 = 3.\par Since Theodora\rquote s damage factor is larger, if she hits him, she\rquote ll do more damage to him than he would to her for an equally well-placed blow.\par Once these numbers are determined, jot them down so you don\rquote t have to refigure them each combat round.\par This system requires each character sheet to have a wound record track which looks like:\par \par \tab \tab 1,2\tab \tab 3,4\tab \tab 5,6\tab \tab 7,8\tab \tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \par The numbers above the wound levels represent the amount of damage needed in a single blow to inflict the wound listed under the number. For example, a blow of 3 or 4 points Hurts the character, while a blow of 5 or 6 points inflicts a Very Hurt wound.\par These numbers can be customized by the GM to fit her conception of how damage affects people. Raising the numbers makes it harder to wound someone, while lowering them makes combat more deadly.\par Note that there is no number given for Dead. This is left up to the GM, and deliberately not included to prevent accidental PC death.\par However, you can\rquote t simply use the damage factor you determined above \emdash  relative degree is also important.\par A relative degree of +1 is treated as a graze \emdash  see Section 4.56, Grazing.\par Otherwise, simply add the relative degree to the damage factor. (You may also wish to include a damage roll \emdash  see Section 4.61, Damage Die Roll.)\par The result is a number that may or may not be a positive number. If it\rquote s zero or less, no damage is scored.\par If the number is positive, look up the result across the top of the wound levels, and figure the wound as described above. If Leroy hits Theodora with a relative degree of +2, he adds that to his damage potential of +2 to produce a damage number of 4. Looking down, we see that a result of 4 is a Hurt result (Light Wound). Theodora is Hurt, and at \endash 1 until she is healed.\par For more detail, see Section 4.7, Combat and Wounding Example.\par There are other ways to figure damage. A GM who believes the relative degree is more important than the damage factor would double it before adding it to the damage factor. The numbers above the wound levels should be adjusted in this case:\par \par \tab \tab 1-3\tab \tab 4-6\tab \tab 7-9\tab \tab 10-12\tab \tab 13+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \par This is a satisfying system that is recommended for those who don\rquote t mind doubling relative degree.\par Others feel Strength is more important, and so on. A totally different wounding system is given in Section 4.63, Min-Mid-Max Die Roll. Many others have been proposed for Fudge over the years, and it would be easy to import one from another game system. Use what you feel comfortable with.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.56  Grazing\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Any relative degree of +1 can do at most a GM-set Wound level (plus any Scale difference). It may do no damage at all, depending on the opponent\rquote s defensive factors: a fist hitting plate mail won\rquote t hurt the armored knight in the slightest \emdash  unless it\rquote s a giant\rquote s fist.\par Sample graze severity table:\par \tab Damage\par \tab Factor\tab Result\par \tab <0\tab Undamaged\par \tab 0-4\tab Scratch\par \tab  5+\tab Hurt\par \par A GM may or may not allow a damage die roll on a graze, even if using the die rolls for other hits. If allowed, a damage roll shouldn\rquote t change the result of a graze by more than one level.\par Scale difference is a little trickier to figure, but it should be minimized for such a narrow victory: a giant\rquote s club could give a human a glancing blow that might inflict a Very Hurt result, but not necessarily Incapacitate.\par On the other hand, a tiger biting a mouse with a relative degree of +1 grazes the mouse as a cow grazes grass\u8230\'c9.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.57  Recording Wounds\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Once the final damage is determined, it is recorded on the wounded fighter\rquote s character sheet. Each individual wound is described as a Scratch, Hurt (Light Wound), etc., as introduced in Section 4.51, Wound Levels.\par Use a Damage Capacity attribute as an easy way to record wounds. (In this case, Damage Capacity is not figured into determining wound severity.) Each hit that is greater than a Scratch reduces a character\rquote s Damage Capacity attribute one level \emdash  or more, if the GM deems the hit to be severe enough. (Scratches can accumulate as the GM desires \emdash  perhaps three Scratches equal one hit.)\par When someone is reduced to Mediocre Damage Capacity, he is Hurt: \endash 1 to all actions. When he is at Poor Damage Capacity, he is Very Hurt: \endash 2 to all actions. When he drops to Terrible, he is at \endash 3 to all actions \emdash  or Incapacitated, if a GM wishes to play it that way. Damage Capacity below Terrible is Incapacitated, at least \emdash  possibly worse.\par (For characters of Mediocre or worse Damage Capacity, these levels only affect them when damaged. That is, an undamaged character of Mediocre Damage Capacity is not at \endash 1 to all actions. However, if he takes even one hit, he drops to Poor Damage Capacity, and is at \endash 2 to all actions.)\par Healing in such a system cannot raise Damage Capacity above a character\rquote s undamaged level \emdash  that can only be raised through Character Development (see Chapter 5).\par A more detailed method requires a space on the character sheet to record wounds. This would look like:\par \par \tab \tab 1,2\tab \tab 3,4\tab \tab 5,6\tab \tab 7,8\tab \tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \tab \tab [   ]  [   ]  [   ]\tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\par \par The numbers above the wound levels are discussed in Section 4.55, Determining Wound Level.\par The boxes below the wound levels represent how many of each wound type a fighter can take.\par When a wound is received, mark off the appropriate box. A character takes a Very Hurt result in the first round of combat. The character sheet would then look like:\par \par \tab \tab 1,2\tab \tab 3,4\tab \tab 5,6\tab \tab 7,8\tab \tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \tab \tab [   ]  [   ]  [   ]\tab [   ]\tab \tab [X]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\par \par This character is at \endash 2 to all skills since he\rquote s Very Hurt.\par If he then received a Hurt result, he would check it off like so:\par \par \tab \tab 1,2\tab \tab 3,4\tab \tab 5,6\tab \tab 7,8\tab \tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \tab \tab [   ]  [   ]  [   ]\tab [X]\tab \tab [X]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\par \par This character is still at \endash 2 to all skills. The Hurt result is not cumulative with the Very Hurt result; only the penalty for the highest recorded wound level counts.\par If there is no open box for a given wound result, the character takes the next highest wound for which there is an open box. If the character above, for example, takes another Hurt result, we see that there is no open box in either Hurt or Very Hurt, so we have to go to Incapacitated: the character is now incapacitated, and the sheet would look like:\par \par \tab \tab 1,2\tab \tab 3,4\tab \tab 5,6\tab \tab 7,8\tab \tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \tab \tab [   ]  [   ]  [   ]\tab [X]\tab \tab [X]\tab \tab [H]\tab \tab [   ]\par \par Note that an \ldblquote H\rdblquote  is recorded under the Incapacitated label. The character is indeed Incapacitated \emdash  he can\rquote t fight any more \emdash  but for healing (and scarring) purposes, he has only received two Hurt wounds and one Very Hurt wound \emdash  never an Incapacitating wound in one blow. Since Incapacitating blows are harder to heal from, this is important.\par As another example, a character that takes two Very Hurt results without taking any other hits is Incapacitated, since that is the next highest wound level.\par Note that three boxes are provided under Scratch. This can be customized by each GM, of course. A Scratch wound will not make a fighter Hurt until he receives his fourth Scratch. Optionally, a Scratch will never raise a character\rquote s wound level beyond Very Hurt, no matter how many he takes. The GM should not to use this rule when the PCs fight a monster of huge Scale. Otherwise, they\rquote d never be able to kill such a creature when the worst wound they can inflict is a Scratch.\par The wound progression above makes for a fairly realistic campaign. For a more cinematic campaign (especially those without magic or science fiction healing), add an extra box for Scratch, Hurt, and possibly Very Hurt: lesser blows won\rquote t accumulate so quickly to hinder the character. A moderately cinematic character sheet looks like:\par \par \tab \tab 1,2\tab \tab 3,4\tab \tab 5,6\tab \tab 7,8\tab \tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \tab \tab [   ]  [   ]  [   ]\tab [   ]  [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\par \par It wouldn\rquote t be out of line, for an epic scale game, to add up to two more boxes to Hurt and Very Hurt.\par Be warned that adding boxes can lengthen combat significantly.\par Never add boxes for cannon-fodder NPCs, though you may wish to do so for major NPCs. In fact, NPC pawns don\rquote t even need the system above. A simple three-stage system of Undamaged, Hurt, Out of the Battle is good enough for most of them. Simply make a mark under an NPC\rquote s name for Hurt, and cross out the name for Out of the Battle.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.58  Non-human Scale in Combat\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The attacker\rquote s Strength Scale is added to his offensive damage factors, and the defender\rquote s Mass Scale is added to her defensive damage factors. If you have combat with beings weaker than humans, remember what you learned in school about adding and subtracting negative numbers\u8230\'c9.\par Armor and weapons affect the damage done normally, since they are scaled to the folks using them. Hits become Scratches, Hurt, etc., as usual \endash  see Section 4.55, Determining Wound Level.\par However, an extremely small character is not likely to be able to wound a large one in the numerical value wounding system. The GM may allow a point or two of damage to penetrate if the small character gets a critical success. Poison-tipped arrows and lances are also a possibility: the small character can aim for joints in the armor and merely has to break the skin to inject the poison.\par Also, this system treats Mass Scale like armor, which isn\rquote t quite accurate. In reality, a small opponent may be slowly carving the larger fighter up, but each wound is too petty, relative to the large scale, to do much damage by itself. To reflect a lot of small wounds gradually inflicting a hit on a large-scale foe, allow a damage roll when Scale prevents a hit from doing any damage \endash  that is, when Scale is the only difference between getting a Scratch and no damage at all. See Section 4.61, Damage Die Roll.\par There are also \ldblquote scale piercing\rdblquote  weapons, such as whale harpoons and elephant guns. These don\rquote t have massive damage numbers: instead, if they hit well, simply halve the Scale value, or ignore it all together. Of course, if such a weapon is used on a human, it would indeed have a massive damage modifier\u8230\'c9.\par Combat Examples: In the following examples, each fighter\rquote s Strength Scale equals his own Mass Scale, but not his opponent\rquote s. (E.g., Wilbur\rquote s Strength is Scale 0 and his Mass is Scale 0.) Also, it is assumed the GM is not using the optional damage roll, which could vary damage in all three combats discussed.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 First example:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sheba, a human warrior, has just kicked McMurtree, a wee leprechaun. Sheba\rquote s offensive damage factor = +1:\par Fair Strength: +0\par Unarmed Combat Skill, with thick boots: +1\par Scale: +0\par (Sheba\rquote s martial art skill normally earns her a +0 to damage, and boots normally earns a +0. The GM rules that using both together allows a +1, however.)\par \par McMurtree\rquote s defensive damage factor is \endash 3:\par Light Leather Armor: +1\par Fair Damage Capacity: +0\par Scale: \endash 4.\par \par Sheba\rquote s damage factor against McMurtree is 1\endash (\endash 3) = +4. (Subtracting a negative number means you add an equal but positive amount.)\par If Sheba wins the first combat round with a relative degree of +2 she scores a total of 4+2 = 6 points. McMurtree\rquote s player looks up 6 on the wound table on his character sheet: Very Hurt \endash  he\rquote s at \endash 2 for the next combat round, and in grave danger if she hits again.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Second example:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 McMurtree\rquote s friend, Fionn, now swings his shillelagh (oak root club) at Sheba\rquote s knee. Fionn\rquote s offensive damage factor is \endash 1:\par Good Strength: +1\par Shillelagh: +2\par (medium sized relative to Fionn, not sharp)\par Scale: \endash 4\par \par Sheba\rquote s defensive damage factor is +2:\par Heavy Leather Armor: +2\par Scale: +0\par Fionn\rquote s damage factor against Sheba is \endash 1\endash 2 = \endash 3.\par \par If Fionn wins by +3, a solid blow, he adds \endash 3+3 = 0. Unfortunately for Fionn, she takes no damage from an excellently placed hit.\par Fionn had better think of some other strategy, quickly. Fortunately for Fionn, he knows some magic, and if he can dodge just one kick from Sheba, she\rquote ll learn the hard way why it\rquote s best not to antagonize the Wee folk\u8230\'c9.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Third example:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Wilbur, a human knight with a sword, is attacking a dragon. Wilbur\rquote s offensive damage factor is a respectable +6:\par Great Strength: +2\par Two-handed sword: +4 (+3 for size, +1 for sharpness)\par Scale: +0\par \par The dragon\rquote s defensive damage factor is +8:\par Fair Damage Capacity: +0\par Tough hide: +2\par Scale: +6\par \par Wilbur\rquote s damage factor against the dragon is therefore 6\endash 8 = \endash 2.\par If Wilbur hits the dragon with a relative degree of +3, he does 3\endash 2 = 1 point of damage. Given his Strength, weapon, and the amount he won by, this would be a severe blow to a human, even one wearing armor. But this is no human opponent. Only one point get through the dragon\rquote s Scale and tough hide. The GM checks off a Scratch for the dragon, and the fight continues. Since there are three Scratch boxes for a major NPC, Wilbur will have to do this thrice more before he finally Hurts the dragon. He may need help, or have to go back for his magic sword.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.6  Wound Options\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 This section introduces some of the simpler options for determining wounds. Many others are possible in Fudge, and this list should not be considered official or exhaustive. They are included for possible use, but also to inspire the GM to create her own.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.61  Damage Die Roll\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Although the damage roll is optional, it is recommended if you are using numerical damage factors. This is because the damage factors are generally fixed for the entire fight, and things tend to get stagnant. It also allows a tiny fighter to have a chance against a larger foe \emdash  a satisfying result.\par There are many possible ways to use a damage die roll.\par One could roll a single Fudge die for a result of \endash 1, 0, or +1. This can be added to the damage factor, or, more broadly, to the actual wound level.\par For example, if a fighter inflicts 4 points of damage, that is normally a Hurt result. If a +1 on 1dF is rolled, however, that can make the result +5 (if adding to the damage factor), which brings it up to Very Hurt result. However, a \endash 1 wouldn\rquote t change the wound: it would lower the result to 3, which is still a Hurt result. But if the GM is using 1dF to alter the wound level, then a \endash 1 changes the result to a Scratch, since that\rquote s one wound level below Hurt.\par Instead of a separate damage roll, one could simply use the die rolls used to resolve the Opposed action. If the attacker wins with an even roll (\endash 4, \endash 2, 0, +2, +4), add one to his offensive factor. If he wins with an odd result (\endash 3, \endash 1, +1, +3), his offensive factor is unchanged. Do the same for the defender, except it affects his defensive factor. This system will help the defender 25% of the time, the attacker 25% of the time, and won\rquote t affect the damage results at all 50% of the time.\par Example: the defender loses the combat round, but rolls his trait level exactly (die roll of 0): he adds one to his defensive damage factor. The attacker wins with a die roll of +3: his offensive damage factor is unchanged. The final damage number is reduced by one \emdash  the defender, although losing the round, managed to dodge left as the attacker thrust a bit to the right, perhaps. He may still be wounded, but he got his vital organs out of the way of the blow.\par This system could also be applied to the wound level instead of the damage factor.\par A more complicated system uses a Situational roll (result from \endash 4 to +4, not based on any trait), and adds it to the calculated damage number (the number over the wound level), as found in Section 4.55, Determining Wound Level. Negative final damage is treated as zero damage.\par The GM may wish to apply some limitations to the damage roll, to restrict too wild a result. For example:\par 1) If the calculated damage is positive, the damage roll cannot exceed the calculated damage. That is, if the calculated damage is +2, any damage roll of +3 or +4 is treated as +2, for a total of 4 points of damage.\par 2) If the calculated damage is positive, the final damage cannot be less than +1.\par 3) If the calculated damage is negative or zero, the final damage may be raised to a maximum of +1 by a damage roll.\par First Example: The calculated damage is found to be \endash 2 due to armor and Scale. It would take a +3 or +4 die roll to inflict a wound on the defender in this case, and then only 1 point of calculated damage: a Scratch.\par Second Example: The calculated damage is +2 (a Scratch). A damage roll of +2 to +4 results in final damage of four points, since calculated damage cannot be more than doubled by a damage roll. A damage roll of +1 results in final damage of three points, while a damage roll of 0 results in two points of final damage. Any negative die roll results in one point of final damage, since a positive calculated damage cannot be reduced below one by a damage roll.\par For simplicity, of course, the GM can simply ignore the limitations, and allow the damage roll to be anywhere from \endash 4 to +4, let the chips fall where they may\u8230\'c9.\par Many other damage die rolls are possible \emdash  these are only given as examples to the GM.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.62  Stun, Knockout, and Pulling Punches\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A player can announce that his character is trying to stun or knock his opponent out rather than damage her. Using the flat of a blade instead of the edge, for example, can accomplish this. Damage is figured normally, but any damage inflicted doesn\rquote t wound the opponent: it stuns her instead.\par In this case, a Hurt result is called a \ldblquote Stun\rdblquote  \emdash  a stunned character cannot attack or all-out defend, and is at \endash 1 to defend for one combat turn only. However, the Stun result stays on the character sheet: that is, a second Stun result, even if delivered more than one combat round after the first, will cause the character to become Very Stunned. (Stun results heal like Scratches: after combat is over.)\par A Very Hurt result in a stunning attack is called a Very Stunned result instead: no attacks and \endash 2 to all actions for two combat rounds.\par A result of Incapacitated or worse when going for stun damage results in a knockout. A knocked-out character doesn\rquote t need healing to recuperate to full health \emdash  just time. (Only a harsh GM would roll for the possibility of brain damage \emdash  this is fiction, not reality.)\par The GM may simply decide that a successful Good blow (or better) to the head knocks someone out automatically. In an Opposed action, the Good blow would also have to win the combat, of course.\par Likewise, a player may choose to have his character do reduced damage in any given attack. This is known as \ldblquote pulling your punch,\rdblquote  even if you are using a sword. This commonly occurs in duels of honor, where it is only necessary to draw \ldblquote first blood\rdblquote  to win, and killing your opponent can get you charged with murder. A Scratch will win a \ldblquote first blood\rdblquote  duel \emdash  it is not necessary to Hurt someone.\par To pull your punch, simply announce the maximum wound level you will do if you are successful. A fencer can say he is going for a Scratch, for example. In this case, even if he wins the Opposed action by +8, and adds in +3 for his sword, the worst he can do is nick his foe. He was just trying for a Scratch \emdash  but the Scratch is probably in the shape of the letter \ldblquote Z\rdblquote  with such a result!\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.63  Min-Mid-Max Die Roll\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 This system of wound determination does not pretend to be a realistic method, and can produce some wildly varying results. But it\rquote s quick, easy, and lots of fun, and so works well in a certain style of gaming.\par This system requires 3d6 for a damage roll, even if using 4dF for action resolution.\par Overview: roll 3d6 when a damage roll is called for. You will probably only read one of the dice, however: either the lowest value (Min), median value (Mid) or highest value (Max), depending on damage factor and relative degree. The greater the damage factor and/or relative degree, the greater the d6 you read for result.\par If using the Min-Mid-Max system, use the wound track on the character sheet listed in Section 4.57, Recording Wounds:\par \par \tab \tab 1,2\tab \tab 3,4\tab \tab 5,6\tab \tab 7,8\tab \tab 9+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \tab \tab [   ]  [   ]  [   ]\tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\par \par The offensive and defensive damage factors listed in Section 4.54, Sample Wound Factors List, are used.  However, they are not added to the relative degree. Instead, simply derive the total damage factor as normal: (attacker\rquote s Strength + Scale + weapon) minus (defender\rquote s Damage Capacity + Scale + armor). Each player should jot down this number once it is known for the combat.\par Before the game begins, the GM decides how important the damage factor and relative degree are in determining wound severity. The following table is recommended as a starting point; the GM can adjust it as she sees fit:\par \par \tab Damage\tab \tab Bonus\tab \tab Relative Degree\par \tab  Factor\par \tab < 0\tab \tab \endash 1\tab \tab \emdash \par \tab 0,1,2\tab \tab 0\tab \tab 2,3\par \tab 3,4,5\tab \tab +1\tab \tab 4,5\par \tab 6+\tab \tab +2\tab \tab 6+\par \par A damage factor of 3, for example, has a die-reading bonus of +1, while a relative degree of 3 has a die-reading bonus of 0. The GM may charge a \endash 2 penalty if the damage factor is well below zero (\endash 5 or worse).\par Since the graze rules are used unchanged with this system, there is no listing for relative degree less than 2.\par Add the bonus for damage factor with the bonus for relative degree to get a final bonus. Example: a character has a damage factor of +3 (bonus: +1) and a relative degree of +5 (bonus: +1).  His total bonus for that round of combat is +2.\par What do these bonuses represent?\par A total \ldblquote bonus\rdblquote  of less than zero means no damage is possible \emdash  don\rquote t even roll the dice. Otherwise, locate the total bonus on the following table:\par \par \tab \par \tab Total Bonus\tab Die to Read\par \tab 0\tab \tab Min\par \tab 1\tab \tab Mid\par \tab 2\tab \tab Max\par \tab 3\tab \tab Add Max + Min\par \tab 4\tab \tab Add all three\par Min = lowest die.\par Mid = median die.\par Max = highest die.\par \par The median is the value in the middle. This may be the same as the highest or lowest, as in a roll of 2, 4, 4: the Min = 2, the Mid = 4, and the Max = 4. A roll of triples means Min = Mid = Max. (Please read the median value \emdash  not necessarily the die that is physically between the other two on the table.)\par Once you have determined which die to read, compare it with the numbers above the wound levels. With a roll of 1, 3, 5, for example, the Min die = 1 (a Scratch result), the Mid die = 3 (a Hurt result), and the Max die = 5 (a Very Hurt result). You would only read one of these results, however \emdash  not all three.\par With three or more bonuses, add the appropriate dice as listed on the table. For results beyond 9, the GM is free to kill the recipient outright, or merely keep it as a Near Death result, as called for by the situation.\par The tables are not meant to be intrusive, merely guidelines. The basic intent is to read the Mid if the attacker has either a decent damage factor or a decent relative degree; to read the Min if he has neither; and to read the Max if he has both. All other values are derived from that simple idea. So the GM can ignore all the tables, and with that idea in mind, just fudge which die to read.\par For example, a GM might say, \ldblquote Whoa! You just hit him across the forehead as he backed into a bucket left by the hastily fleeing janitor. Nice shot \emdash  he topples over onto his back. For damage, roll 3d6 and read the Max!\rdblquote \par This would have come out of a descriptive game, in which the players describe their characters\rquote  actions in great detail.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Example of the Min-Mid-Max system:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Valorous Rachel is fighting the villainous Archie. Both are Scale 0, so Scale won\rquote t be mentioned.\par \par Rachel:\par \tab Quarterstaff: +2\par \tab Strength Fair: +0\par \tab \tab Offensive damage factor: +2\par \tab Light Leather Armor: +1\par \tab Damage Capacity Good: +1\par \tab \tab Defensive damage factor: +2\par Archie:\par \tab Greatsword: +4\par \tab Strength Great: +2\par \tab \tab Offensive damage factor: +6\par \tab Heavy Leather Armor: +2\par \tab Damage Capacity Fair: +0\par \tab \tab Defensive damage factor: +2\par \par So Rachel\rquote s damage factor is 2\endash 2 = 0. She gets no bonus.\par Archie\rquote s damage factor is 6\endash 2 = 4.  He gets +1 bonus, according to the table above.\par On the first round, Rachel wins by +2, whacking Archie across the ribs. Relative degree +2 doesn\rquote t get any bonus (and she has none from her damage factor), so Rachel will read the Min. She rolls 3d6 and gets lucky: a 3, 5, and 6. The Min is a 3: she Hurts Archie, who is now at \endash 1 and checks off his Hurt box.\par On the second round, Archie manages to win with a graze: +1 relative degree. Do not even calculate a bonus in this case \emdash  use the graze rule unchanged from Section 4.56, Grazing. His damage factor is only 4, so he scores a Scratch on Rachel.\par On the third round, Archie does very well: he wins by +4 as Rachel backs into a chair! He now gets two bonuses, one from his damage factor and one from his relative degree: he will read the Max die. But Archie\rquote s karma is in serious need of overhaul: he rolls a 1, 2, and 3. Rachel is only Hurt, and the GM checks off the Hurt box.\par Rachel all-out attacks in the following round, and with the +1 to hit she scores an awesome +6 over Archie! She gets two bonuses for such a high relative degree \emdash  she\rquote ll read the Max die \emdash  and gets +1 to the die roll for all-out attacking. (Note that this is +1 to the die result, not a +1 to the die-reading bonus.) The GM rolls a 1, 4, 6. She reads the Max and adds 1 for a total of 7. Reading the wound table on the character sheet, she sees that this is Incapacitated, and declares that Rachel\rquote s staff just smashed across the bridge of Archie\rquote s nose, probably doing serious damage, and at least knocking him out of this battle\u8230\'c9.\par For a more epic game, where it\rquote s important to be able to Incapacitate in one blow, use the following wound track on the character sheet:\par \par \tab \tab 1\tab \tab 2,3\tab \tab 4,5\tab \tab 6\tab \tab 7+\par Wounds:\tab Scratch\tab \tab Hurt\tab \tab Very Hurt\tab Incapac.\tab \tab Nr. Death\par \tab \tab [   ]  [   ]  [   ]\tab [   ]  [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\tab \tab [   ]\par \par The extra wound boxes are in keeping with an epic style game, but are optional.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.64  PC Death\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sometimes the dice try to kill a PC. In most campaigns, PC death shouldn\rquote t occur through a bad die roll, but only if the character\rquote s actions were truly self-sacrificing \endash  or stupid \endash  enough to warrant death. Three methods of preventing accidental PC death are presented. They may be used separately or together or not at all.\par These should not be used for run-of-the-mill NPCs, but could be used for major ones.\par The \ldblquote automatic death\rdblquote  rule in Section 4.51, Wound Levels, takes precedence over these suggestions.\par 1) A character cannot take more than three levels of wounds in one blow. For example, an unwounded character could be Scratched, Hurt, or Very Hurt in one blow, but any excess damage points beyond that would be lost. A Hurt character could go all the way to Near Death in one blow, but not be killed outright.\par 2) A character cannot be rendered Near Death unless he began that combat round Incapacitated. This is simpler to keep track of than the first system, and assumes there is some great difference between a severe wound and mortal wound. There probably isn\rquote t, but the rule isn\rquote t intended to be realistic: it\rquote s to make the PCs more heroic than real life.\par 3) A player may spend a Fudge Point (Section 1.36) to convert a deadly wound to a merely serious one.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 4.65  Technological Levels as Scale\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Technological differences between weapons and armor can be expressed as Scale if the GM desires. Instead of figuring exactly how much mega-damage a transvibrational subneural pulverizer does, the GM can simply say, \ldblquote This is a weapon that is of the same technological level as the armor of the defender \emdash  therefore, it has the same effect on her as a modern pistol would on kevlar.\rdblquote  However, if used against someone who is wearing kevlar, the transvibrational subneural pulverizer does lots and lots of damage \emdash  kevlar wasn\rquote t designed to stop this type of thing.\par Basically, there isn\rquote t much difference between thrusting a sword through a naked man\rquote s kidney, or shooting him with a .38 through the kidney, or using a transvibrational subneural pulverizer on the kidney: naked people don\rquote t resist most weapons well. Plate armor stops the sword well, but won\rquote t slow down the .38 enough to help much \emdash  unless it can deflect it away from the kidney, that is. It probably won\rquote t help at all against the pulverizer, but it may: the GM will have to decide the effect of such a weapon on plate armor.\par The concept of technological levels as Scale only comes into effect when weapons of one technological era are used against armor of another technological era. At that point, the GM can add an arbitrary Scale difference to the weapon \emdash  or armor, whichever is of the higher tech level. No attempt to quantify tech levels is made here. This section is merely food for thought.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.7  Combat and Wounding Example\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 This example uses the numerical offensive and defensive factors in Section 4.54, Sample Wound Factors List. It also uses a damage die roll: the 4dF option, with the three limitations listed.\par The two opponents are Medieval warriors, Snorri and Brynhild. The fight takes place in a barroom, which quickly empties of other occupants once weapons are drawn. No one noticed that the innkeeper\rquote s son had actually left much earlier than this, when the belligerent Snorri was merely exchanging insults with the proud Brynhild. Both fighters are human (Scale 0), so Scale is left out of the discussion.\par \par Snorri:\par Sword skill: Great\par No shield\par Strength: Good (+1)\par Weapon: Magic Sword\par \tab \tab (+2 for size, +1 for Sharp, +1 for Magic = +4)\par \tab Offensive damage factor: +5\par Damage Capacity: Good (+1)\par Armor: Heavy Leather (+2)\par \tab Defensive damage factor: +3\par \par Brynhild:\par Axe skill: Good\par Shield: Medium (\endash 1 to foe\rquote s weapon skill)\par Strength: Great (+2)\par Weapon: Axe (+2 for size, +1 for Sharpness = +3)\par \tab Offensive damage factor: (+5)\par Damage Capacity: Fair (+0)\par Armor: Heavy Leather (+2)\par \tab Defensive damage factor: (+2)\par \par Snorri\rquote s damage factor vs. Brynhild: 5-2 = +3\par Brynhild\rquote s damage factor vs. Snorri: 5-3 = +2\par Snorri\rquote s skill is reduced to Good for this combat by Brynhild\rquote s shield \emdash  see Section 4.31, Melee Modifiers.\par In the first round, Snorri gets a Great result on his weapon skill (die roll = +1), and Brynhild gets a Fair result (die roll = \endash 1). Snorri wins with a relative degree of +2. Snorri\rquote s damage factor of +3 is added in, bringing the damage to +5. Looking at the character sheet, a +5 result equals a Very Hurt wound \emdash  before rolling for damage.\par The GM is requiring damage rolls, so Snorri\rquote s player rolls the dice: a \endash 2 result, too bad. This brings the damage down to 3. Since Brynhild is an NPC, the GM looks at the wound chart on her character sheet, and finds 3: a Hurt Wound. The GM marks off the box under the word \ldblquote Hurt,\rdblquote  and the next round is fought. Brynhild is now at \endash 1 for the rest of the combat.\par In the second round, both combatants get Good results \emdash  a standoff. The GM describes it as a give-and-take of blows that are all parried or blocked as the fighters circle each other. Another five seconds have passed this round, the GM decrees.\par In the third round, Snorri gets a Great result and Brynhild only a Good result \emdash  Snorri has hit again. Since the relative degree is +1, this is a graze. The GM does allow a damage die roll on a graze, but won\rquote t let it change the result by more than one level. Snorri\rquote s damage factor of +3 normally means a Scratch on a graze.\par Snorri rolls a 0 for damage, so the GM marks off a Scratch box on Brynhild\rquote s character sheet.\par In the fourth round, Snorri decides to finish off the Hurt Brynhild in one blow: he all-out attacks, which gives him a +1 modifier to his skill, and a +1 to damage if he wins. Brynhild had decided to try for a situational advantage, though: she\rquote s spending this round in all-out defense, hoping to spot some way to get an advantage over Snorri for the fifth round. Brynhild gets a +2 modifier to her skill this turn, but can\rquote t hurt Snorri if she wins. Snorri gets a Great result, even counting his +1 for all-out attacking, and Brynhild also gets a Great result. Snorri would ordinarily have lost the combat round (all-out attackers lose tie results), but Brynhild\rquote s all-out defense means she doesn\rquote t aim any blows at Snorri, just beats his attack down.\par The GM requires a Good Perception roll from Brynhild in order to spot a situational advantage. Her Perception attribute is Great, so she easily makes it. She notices a drink on the floor, spilled earlier by a customer in full flight. Since she successfully defended that round, the GM rules she maneuvers Snorri into the slippery puddle for one round.\par In the fifth round, the GM gives Snorri a \endash 1 to skill this round (down to Fair) for bad footing. Snorri tries an ordinary attack, and Brynhild, wounded, desperate, and sensing this may be her only chance, now tries an all-out attack: +1 modifier to her skill, bringing her up to an effective skill of Good from her wounded Fair state. Brynhild rolls a Great result, and Snorri only gets a Good result: Brynhild wins this round by +1.\par Since she was doing an all-out attack, she gets a bonus of +1 to damage. This does affect a graze, so her normal Scratch result (for a graze) is increased to Hurt. She rolls a 0 on the damage roll, so Snorri is now Hurt: \endash 1 until healed.\par The combat is interrupted at this point by the town guards, who had been alerted by the innkeeper\rquote s son. Snorri and Brynhild are hauled off to separate cells, probably only too glad to get out of what had become a potentially deadly duel\u8230\'c9.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 4.8  Healing\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Wounds are healed through a medical skill or supernormal power.\par A Scratch is too insignificant to require a roll on a healing skill (although it might require a kiss to make it better\u8230\'c9). Scratches are usually erased after a battle, provided the characters have five or ten minutes to attend to them. An individual GM may rule otherwise, of course: they may linger on for a day or two.\par A Good result on a healing skill heals all wounds one level (Hurt to healed, Very Hurt to Hurt, etc.). (Scratches do not count as a level for healing purposes. That is, a Hurt wound that is healed one level is fully healed.) A Great result heals all wounds two levels, and a Superb result heals three levels.\par Healing with realistic medical skills takes time: the success of the roll merely insures the wounds will heal, given enough rest. How long this takes depends on the technological level of the game setting, and is up to the GM. (A day per treated wound is extremely fast healing, but may be appropriate in an epic-style game. Likewise, one minute per magically healed wound is fast.) Whether or not strenuous activity before the healing period ends reopens a wound is also left up to the GM\u8230\'c9.\par Example: a character with three wounds (two Hurt results and one Very Hurt) is healed with a roll of Good. After the appropriate time, the two Hurt wounds will be fully healed, while the Very Hurt wound will now be a Hurt wound (and carries a \endash 1 modifier as such).\par Otherwise, wounds heal on their own at one wound level per week of rest \emdash  or longer, if the GM is being more realistic. That is, after a week of rest, an Incapacitated character becomes Very Hurt, etc. The GM may also require a successful roll against a Constitution attribute: Fair Difficulty Level for Hurt, Good Difficulty Level for Very Hurt, and Great Difficulty Level for Incapacitated. Failing this roll slows the healing process. Someone Near Death should take a long time to heal, even with magical or high tech healing.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Chapter 5: Character Development\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 After playing a bit, perhaps each session, a player will want the character to grow in abilities. At this point, a developing character can exceed the initial GM-set skill limits (such as one Superb, three Greats). There are two ways to handle character development, or \ldblquote experience,\rdblquote  as it\rquote s often called.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 5.1  Subjective Character Development\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When the player feels the character has accomplished enough to warrant improving in some trait (and he feels he\rquote s been role-playing well), he petitions the GM for permission to raise it. A trait can only be raised one level at a time. A trait must be used more to raise it from Good to Great than Fair to Good, and so on. It should be easier to raise a Skill than an attribute.\par Or the GM can simply award an improvement in a trait she feels deserves to be raised. In these cases, there is never a corresponding reduction of another trait \emdash  this is character development, not creation.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 5.2  Objective Character Development\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 In the Objective Character Development system, the GM can award experience points (EP), which the player can trade in any way he wants at the following rates:\par \par Raising a skill\par \tab From:\tab \tab To:\tab Costs:\par \tab Terrible\tab \tab Poor \tab 1 EP\par \tab Poor\tab \tab Mediocre\tab 1 EP\par \tab Mediocre\tab Fair\tab 1 EP\par \tab Fair\tab \tab Good\tab 2 EP\par \tab Good\tab \tab Great\tab 4 EP\par \tab Great\tab \tab Superb\tab 8 EP\par \tab Superb\tab \tab Legendary\tab 16 EP\par \tab \tab \tab + GM permission\par \tab Legendary\tab Legendary 2nd\tab 30 EP\par \tab \tab \tab + GM permission\par \tab Each add\rquote l level of Legendary:\tab 50 EP\par \tab \tab \tab + GM permission\par \par Raising an attribute:\par Triple the cost for skills of the same level.\par \par Adding a gift:\par 6 EP (or more) + GM approval.\par \par Adding a supernormal power:\par 12 EP (or more) + GM approval.\par \par A trait can only be raised one level at a time.\par The GM may adjust these point levels as she sees fit and should require that the player may only raise traits that were used significantly during an adventure. If a long campaign is planned, these EP costs could be doubled to allow room for character growth.\par Defining skills narrowly will also ensure characters don\rquote t become too powerful too quickly.\par As a guideline, good role-playing should be rewarded with 1 to 3 EP per gaming session, with a suggested upper limit of 4 EP for flawless role-playing. Players may save EP as long as they wish.\par Attribute levels may or may not affect EPs put into skills. For simplicity, you can ignore attribute levels entirely when raising skill levels. For greater realism, however, the GM can add a surcharge of +2 EP (or more) when a skill is raised above an appropriate attribute.\par Example: Violet the Herbalist has Good Intelligence.  EP costs for raising Herb Lore skill are normal until she tries to raise it to Great, which is higher than her natural Intelligence. At that point, she must pay +2 EP beyond what the table calls for: 6 EP to raise Herb Lore to Great, and another 10 EP to raise it to Superb.\par This proposal is recommended only for character development \emdash  not for character creation. The GM should inform the players at character creation if this option is in force so they can plan their characters\rquote  attributes accordingly.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 5.3  Development through Training\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Improving skills through EP is not always realistic, to be honest. A gaming session might only cover a few hours of campaign time. Allowing a character to improve one or two different skills from Fair to Good in that time is far-fetched. But it\rquote s fun for the players, and psychologically satisfying, and so recommended.\par As an alternative, or in addition to the methods described above, the GM may allow traits to be raised through appropriate amounts of training time. This would require finding a teacher (which would cost money) or taking an appropriate job (which may not be totally dedicated the skill you wish to learn, and so take longer). It\rquote s also possible to learn something on your own, but the GM should double the time required. If using the Objective Character Development system, the GM may (or may not) require that EPs be spent in this manner \emdash  that is, you can\rquote t spend EPs unless you also take the time to train.\par The GM sets training time and costs, and difficulty of finding a teacher. The teacher has two skills that must be considered: Teaching skill, and the appropriate skill being taught. The player may need to roll the dice to see how diligently the character studied the skill. The die roll should be on an attribute such as Willpower, Drive, Zeal, Wisdom, Self Discipline, Self Motivation, Psyche, Intelligence, etc. If the player can give a valid reason why the character is extremely motivated to learn this skill, the GM may grant up to +2 to the trait tested. The GM may request a single die roll, or a roll per week, month, etc. If multiple rolls are called for, at least half of them should succeed to earn the skill improvement.\par Example: Billy Blaster, space cadet, is back at the Academy after his first tour of duty. He considers his Fair Laser Pistol skill to be substandard. He takes a six-week training course in Laser pistol use, taught by an instructor of Superb Laser skill and Great Teaching skill. (Since Billy has Gift: Employed by Space Patrol, this is free training for him.) The GM decides that Billy\rquote s player needs to make a Willpower roll for each two-week period to see how dedicated he is to studying. If at least two of the three rolls are Mediocre or better, Billy can raise his Laser pistol skill from Fair to Good, given the length of training and quality of the instructor. Had the training been shorter, or the instructor worse, he would have needed a preponderance of Fair or even Good rolls to have successfully raised his Laser pistol skill.\par Remember that it is much easier to improve a skill from Poor to Mediocre than from Great to Superb. Require more time, or higher Difficulty Levels on the Will rolls to raise an already high skill.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 5.4 Alternative Experience System\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Note: The following was taken from the author\rquote s \ldblquote Thoughts on Fudge\rdblquote  (online at http://www.io.com/~sos/rpg/fudlatest.html).\par After a convention game one time, Ann Dupuis and I were discussing how well the game went, especially with the one newcomer to gaming at the table. The woman was not only at her first convention, but was playing her first RPGs that weekend. Fudge was the last game in her schedule that con, and she was blown away by how easy it was compared to the other games. She said she understood the character sheet without having to have anything explained to her \endash  and that the single mechanic to resolve all actions was the best she\rquote d seen in the five different games she\rquote d tried.\par So we were congratulating ourselves, when I mentioned to Ann (President and Dictator for Life of Grey Ghost Games) that Fudge did have its drawbacks \endash  experience being the most glaring. Yes, it\rquote s great for one-shot con games, but it seems to allow characters to develop too quickly or not at all in long-term games.\par Ann came up with an idea which we batted around a bit, and it looks something like this:\par Instead of awarding Experience Points, the GM awards Fudge Points at the end of a gaming session. These can be turned in for Experience Points, but the ratio in Section 1.36 (suggested 3 EP = 1 Fudge Point) is reversed. That is, you may turn in three Fudge Points for one EP.\par Raising traits is unchanged from Chapter 5.\par What this does is force the player to consider whether he needs to save his Fudge Points to get out of a jam the next session, or convert them to EP to raise a trait. He can save Fudge Points from session to session, so he can eventually swap 12 Fudge Points for 4 EP to raise a trait or two \endash  but he may have to use some of those Fudge Points along the way to survive!\par The net effect is that character development is left totally in the hands of the player, but is slowed down from the rate suggested in the book. This means a long-term campaign becomes more viable in Fudge.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Chapter 6: Tips and Examples\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 6.1  GM Tips and Conversion\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Always remember the main point of the game is to have fun\u8230\'c9.\par The GM should translate at least one of her favorite characters into Fudge from whatever system she is used to. This will give her a good idea of what traits to choose, and how many.\par Fudge is incredibly flexible, possibly more so than any system you\rquote ve played before. Once you\rquote ve translated a favorite character, fiddle with her a bit. Can you tweak her to be exactly what you want, possibly in ways your previous system wouldn\rquote t allow? What if you split that attribute into two or three effects \endash  ah! See, she can be smart in some ways, but dumb in others; knowledgeable of some things, ignorant of others. Hmmm \endash  too many attributes? Make some of them gifts, then \emdash  that might be easier to deal with. And so on \endash  have fun!\par It is easy to create NPCs to challenge the player characters by counting levels. Figure roughly how many levels have been spent on combat skills by the average player character. This figure, put into combat skills in an NPC, should give a fair fight. For example, if the PCs are built on 40 skill levels and four free attribute levels, the average character might have ten levels in combat skills directly. In that case, a gang of thugs with ten levels each of combat skills and two attribute levels put into physical attributes should challenge the player characters pretty closely.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 6.11  Conversion Hints\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 It is not practical to give guidelines for converting every game system to and from Fudge. However, two systems of trait measurement are in widespread use: a 3-18 scale, and a percentile system. While these are not used uniformly (and there are many games that don\rquote t use either system), it is still useful to discuss translating between such systems and Fudge.\par Standard 3-18 scale traits are converted as follows:\par \par \tab Fudge Level\tab 3-18 Level\par \tab Superb\tab \tab 18+\par \tab Great\tab \tab 16-17\par \tab Good\tab \tab 13-15\par \tab Fair\tab \tab 9-12\par \tab Mediocre\tab 6-8\par \tab Poor\tab \tab 4-5\par \tab Terrible\tab \tab 3 or less\par \par Percentile traits are converted roughly as follows:\par \par \tab Fudge Level\tab Percentile Level\par \tab Superb\tab \tab 98-100\par \tab Great\tab \tab