ak skills down into finer divisions. Each skill must be raised separately if the GM decides to break the broad groups into finer distinctions. If the GM likes keeping the skills together as groups, then raising an entire skill group level should cost more experience points than in a system with narrowly-defined skills \emdash  perhaps as much as ten times the cost.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 6.43  Cercopes (Fantasy Race)\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Cercopes (or Kerkopes) were originally a pair of brothers in early Greek mythology. By the first century BC, however, mythological writers had expanded them into their own race. It is in this later definition that they are used here.\par Cercopes (singular: cercop) are a small, apish race that love to play tricks and pranks on anyone they can. Born thieves, some of them even dared to steal Heracles\rquote  weapons! When he caught them and tied them to a pole for punishment, they amused him so with their jokes and banter that he let them go. Players should not attempt to play a cercop unless they have a roguish sense of humor.\par Cercopes are small humanoids with ugly, apelike faces and a prehensile tail. A cercop stands about four feet high (120 cm), but generally stoops a bit. The face is not hairy, but both sexes tend to have long sideburns that often meet under the chin \emdash  this hair does not continue to grow, but stays the same length, as monkeys\rquote  hair does. The bodies have some scant hair on the back, and the tail is furred except for the final six inches (15 cm). Arms, legs and chests have no more hair than the average human male does, and they wear clothing \emdash  with a tail hole. Their feet resemble monkeys\rquote  feet, but they cannot manipulate things well with them. They are not fond of shoes, only wearing them when attempting to disguise themselves as another race. \par Cercopes stand upright most of the time, but lean forward to run, with the tail acting as a counterbalance. Their tails are strong enough to be used in combat and to aid in climbing. However, a cercop cannot do fine manipulation (such as pick a lock) with its tail. Cercopes speak their own language, and need to learn another to speak with the rest of the party.\par The average cercop has a Mediocre Strength and Damage Capacity, but a Good Dexterity. Their intelligence runs the same range as humans.\par Cercopes have the racial gifts of Exceptional Balance (+2 to any action requiring balance, even in difficult situations), the Ability to Land on their Feet with no harm from twice the distance a human could, and Prehensile Tail.\par Their racial faults are Impulsiveness (act first, think later), Compulsive Jokers (practical and otherwise), Kleptomania, Unattractive Appearance to other races, and Bad Reputations as Thieves and Tricksters.\par They have a bonus of +1 to the following skills: Acrobatics, Move Quietly, Climbing and Fast Talk. They have a \endash 1 penalty to use any weapon of Medium size or bigger.\par The net result is that it counts as a fault to be a Cercop. Since anyone playing such a character actually gets some useful bonuses if playing a thief, the GM should be sure to enforce the faults \emdash  especially the Bad Reputation. NPCs will have a hard time trusting a cercop, usually with good reason.\par This racial template gives a strong incentive to creating a thief character. However, it is possible to make a cercop warrior or even cleric if desired. Certain faults can be \ldblquote bought off.\rdblquote  That is, a character may have a gift of Not a Kleptomaniac \emdash  but it costs one gift, which would nullify the free fault level. However, the Unattractive Appearance and Bad Reputation cannot be bought off \emdash  these are inherent prejudices in others, not in one\rquote s self.\par A cercop character could take a fault: No Tail \emdash  perhaps he lost it in battle. This would give extra levels to overcome the \endash 1 penalty to all medium and large weapons if a character wished to be a warrior cercop, for example.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 6.5  Animal & Creature Examples\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Non-PC animals need not be built using level limits. Just define what traits are essential to the animal, and let it go at that. The Strength Scale refers to Section 2.3, Non-humans. Damage may include a \ldblquote weapon deadliness\rdblquote  factor for teeth, claws, and, in some cases, body optimized for combat (usually carnivores).\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Dog\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Perception: \tab Great to Superb\par \tab (Smell should be Scale: Dog)\par Strength/Mass Scale: \tab \endash 7 to 0\par Skills: \tab Mediocre to Superb\par \tab (tailor to specific training received; examples include attack, guard, guide, track, hunt, and tricks)\par Melee Combat: \tab Fair to Superb\par Damage Capacity: \tab Good to Great\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Cat\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Agility: \tab Great to Superb\par Scale: \tab \endash 6 or \endash 7\par Skills: Survival, Hunting, Playing\par Gifts: Night Vision, Nine Lives (e.g., each time a cat receives damage that would kill it in one blow, check off one life and don\rquote t count the damage. There are other ways to play this, of course, such as a Legendary Dodge ability.)\par Faults: Independent-minded, Curious, Lazy, Vain\par Damage Capacity: \tab Fair to Superb\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Horse\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Strength: \tab Scale 3 Good to Great\par Endurance: \tab Good\par Speed: \tab Scale 4 Good to Great\par Skills: \tab Mediocre to Superb