ar Damage Capacity: \tab Fair to Superb\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Grizzly Bear\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Perception: \tab Good\par Melee Combat: \tab Good\par Dodge: \tab Fair\par Strength: \tab Scale 3 Fair to Great\par Fault: \tab Berserker\par Damage Capacity: \tab Fair to Great\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Cobra\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Perception: \tab Good\par Melee Combat: \tab Great\par Dodge: \tab Good\par Supernormal Power: \tab Poison, +4 damage bonus\par Fault: \tab Bad temper\par Damage Capacity: \tab Poor\par Skunk\par Melee Combat: \tab Poor\par Ranged Combat: \tab Good, short range\par Dodge: \tab Poor\par Supernormal Power: \tab Noxious Fluid\par \tab (blinds, incapacitates, renders foul)\par Damage Capacity: \tab Terrible\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Giant Spider\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Melee Combat: \tab Good\par Dodge: \tab Poor\par Supernormal Powers: \tab Poison (paralyzes)\par \tab \tab Web\par \tab (Good Difficulty Level Strength roll to break)\par Damage Capacity: \tab Good\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Griffin\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Perception: \tab Great\par Melee Combat: \tab Great\par Dodge: \tab Good\par Supernormal Powers: \tab Flight\par \tab \tab Tough Hide (light armor)\par Strength: \tab Mediocre to Great, Scale 4\par Damage Capacity: \tab Good to Superb\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Dragon (customize to taste)\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Melee Combat: \tab Good to Great\par Ranged Combat: \tab Good, short range\par Dodge: \tab Mediocre\par Supernormal Powers: \tab Fire Breath (+2 damage)\par \tab \tab Flight\par \tab \tab Tough Hide (\endash 1 to \endash 3)\par \tab \tab Charm with Eyes\par \tab \tab Magic Potential\par \tab \tab (some of them)\par Fault: \tab Greedy\par Strength: \tab Scale 3 to Scale 9\par \tab \tab Fair to Great\par Damage Capacity: \tab Fair to Great\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 6.6  Equipment Examples\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 It\rquote s possible to define equipment in Fudge character terms. This is probably unnecessary, but can be done if desired.\par Equipment from any technological level, stone age to science fiction, can be detailed this way. A piece of equipment can be defined by as many Fudge traits as are needed: attributes, skills, gifts or faults.\par For example, an old, battered sword found in a damp dungeon has:\par \par Attributes:\par Sharpness: \tab Terrible\par Durability: \tab Poor\par \par Fault:\par Looks Shabby.\par \par Such a weapon is treated as a club for damage, rather than a sword (no Sharpness bonus). The GM may require a Situational roll every few combat rounds: the sword breaks on a Mediocre or worse result from parrying or being parried. And finally, some people will make fun of anyone carrying such a shoddy-looking weapon.\par When the sword was new, however, it had:\par \par Attributes:\par Sharpness: \tab Good\par Sturdiness: \tab Great\par \par Gift:\par Beautifully Made\par \par In that case, it would indeed merit the +1 for Sharpness (perhaps any Sharpness level of Mediocre to Good gets the +1 Sharpness bonus, while duller blades get no bonus, and better blades might get an additional +1 bonus). It also would never break under ordinary circumstances, and its appearance probably earns its owner a positive reaction from many people.\par A bejewelled magic sword found in a dragon\rquote s hoard might have:\par \par Attribute:\par Appearance: \tab Superb\par (+3 to impress those who value wealth)\par \par Gift:\par Troll-slaying (+3 to hit when fighting Trolls; such wounds will never heal)\par Fault:\par Dedicated Purpose (it tries to control the wielder to hunt trolls)\par \par Skill:\par Dominate Wielder: Fair (Opposed action against a Will attribute)\par \par A different magic sword:\par \par Supernormal Power:\par Flame Creation (+2 damage)\par \par Skill:\par Flame Shooting: \tab Great\par \tab (Range: 3 yards or meters)\par \par Fault:\par Flame Creation only works on a Good or better Situational roll\par \par \par Of course, even if the flaming missile fails, it can still be used as a regular sword, so it\rquote s not exactly worthless in such cases.\par As a final example, consider a science fiction double-seat fighter spaceship:\par \par Attributes:\par Acceleration: \tab Great\par Handling: \tab Superb\par Speed: \tab Good (Scale 15)\par Size: \tab Fair (Scale 8)\par \par Skills:\par Navigation: \tab Good\par Targeting: \tab Superb\par Auto-pilot: \tab Fair\par Food Preparation: \tab Poor\par Entertainment: \tab Mediocre\par \par Gifts:\par Turret-mounted Laser Rifles, above and below\par Bucket Seats in the bridge\par Hyperdrive\par Can be used in an atmosphere or in deep space\par \par Faults:\par Non-standard parts (expensive to repair)\par Unattractive exterior\par Cramped sleeping quarters\par Airlock squeaks annoyingly\par \par Ordinary, every-day equipment should not be detailed out in this manner. There is no need to define a canteen, for example, as anything other than \ldblquote metal, 1 quart (liter) capacity.\rdblquote  Even for equipment that may have an impact on the game, such as weapons or thieves\rquote  tools, you do not need to have any more information than \ldblquote +2 offensive damage factor\rdblquote  or \ldblquote adds 1 to Pick Locks skill.\rdblquote \par It\rquote s best to restrict defining equipment in Fudge character terms to the truly extraordinary (such as magic items). Another use is when the equipment\rquote s powers may be used in an opposed action: in a car race, for instance, you need to know the relative speeds and handling capabilities of the vehicles as well as the skills of the drivers. A battle between spaceships is another good example.\par Equipment with personality, such as sentient magic items or advanced robots, may be treated as full-fledged Fudge characters if desired.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Chapter 7: The Addenda\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par The Addenda consist of a variety of supplementary material for Fudge.\par Chapters 1 through 5 represent plain, vanilla Fudge \emdash  here you can find and create fancier fare. If you pass Fudge around, please add any customization to this chapter (quoting Section number and name, such as 1.33, Gifts), rather than change the original. Suggestions for a specific genre also go in the Addenda. Examples: a list of sample superpowers, or a list of guns and their damage.\par Please include a date and credit (your name) for the change, and, if possible, notify Grey Ghost Press, the publisher of Fudge, via the Internet (ghostgames@fudgerpg.com) or via the Post Office (P.O. Box 838, Randolph, MA 02368).\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 7.1  Sample Magic System: Fudge Magic\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Date: November, 1992 to November, 1993\par By: Steffan O\rquote Sullivan\par Here is a sample magic system, based on the following premises mentioned in Section 2.5, Magic:\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Who can cast: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magicians only (supernormal power needed).\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Levels of Power:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  yes. There are two game effects: the greater the power, the easier it is to cast more powerful spells; and power levels act as a reserve in case of severe failure, which temporarily drains Power. Voluntarily draining a level of Power can also guarantee success for one spell.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Source of Power: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 manipulation of local area mana.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Reliability: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fair.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Time to cast spells:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  depends on potency of spell (one minute to days). This can be speeded up by taking a penalty to the roll.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Spells: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 improvised. Exact wording isn\rquote t important, so magic books tend to be collections of effects, not formulae.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Material Components:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  none needed, but good use can give a +1 bonus to skill.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Drawbacks:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  casting non-trivial spells is fatiguing; severe failure causes distress.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Societal constraints: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 none \emdash  magic is rare, but not unheard of.\par This system is based on the conviction that a player using magic should never be blas\u233\'8e: there should always be some tension and excitement when a character casts a spell, or the magic has gone out of the game. Too often in a role-playing game, the player running a magician uses tried-and-true spells so regularly that spell-casting becomes mundane. Since \ldblquote mundane magic\rdblquote  seems a contradiction in terms, Fudge Magic attempts to instill a little excitement into spell-casting.\par There are many ways to achieve this. Fudge Magic has chosen the following limitations:\par 1) The mana available for a specific spell result gradually becomes depleted in a given area. That is, casting two fireballs in a row is harder than casting one fireball and one lightning blast, for example.\par 2) Magic is an untamable force; there is a skill cap for casting spells.\par 3) Magic is somewhat risky to use \emdash  there are penalties for severe failure.\par Options are provided to alter these limitations for GMs who dislike them. In fact, Section 7.193, Spell-Casting Skill Alternatives, is essential for Faerie races and demigods, who have much more dependable magic powers than humans. (Unless the GM is generous, such characters would have to buy higher skill levels normally if using the Objective Character Creation system. Taking some faults to balance such Powers is in keeping with the nature of demigods and Faerie races.)\par See Section 6.31 for sample characters using Fudge Magic.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.11  Magic Potential\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magic Potential is a Supernormal Power. (A suggested cost in the Objective Character Creation system is two gifts for each level of Magic Potential. This can be reduced in a magic-rich campaign.) A character with at least one level of Magic Potential (usually abbreviated to Potential, sometimes simply called Power) is referred to as a \ldblquote magician\rdblquote  in these rules \emdash  substitute your favorite word. Only magicians may cast spells. (However, see Section 7.192, Magicians & Non-Magicians, for other options.) Magic Potential may be taken more than once, but each level counts as a separate supernormal power.\par Each level of Magic Potential must be bought as a specialization. Specializations can be suggested by the player or set by the GM. (In the latter case, she should make a list of acceptable magic specializations.) The categories can be as broad or as narrow as the GM wishes \emdash  the broader the terms, the more powerful the magicians.\par Examples of specialized Potential: Alter Inanimate Material, Augury, Combat Magic, Communication Magic, Defensive Magic, Elemental Magic, Flying Magic, Healing Magic, Illusion, Information-Gathering Magic, Mind Control, Necromancy, Only Affects Living Beings, Only Affects Sentient Beings, Only Affects Technological Items, Shapeshifting, White Magic (cannot harm anyone, even indirectly), etc.\par A character may have Power levels in more than one specialization, unless the GM disallows it for some reason. Certain disciplines may have societal constraints: in most cultures, studying Necromancy is offensive and probably illegal. Mind Control, Invisibility, Teleportation, Illusion Magic, etc., might all be limited to government-approved magicians, at best. It\rquote s even possible that such magicians will be outlaws. Anything that can be used easily to commit a crime (especially assassination or thievery) will be difficult, if not impossible, to learn openly in most cultures. If a given culture allows such magic openly, it is sure to have powerful defenses against being damaged by it.\par Narrow specializations should probably cost less than one supernormal power: perhaps each specialized Potential is worth one gift.\par In order to cast a spell of a given result, the magician must have at least +1 Potential specialized in that type of magic (on the character sheet, that is: he may be temporarily reduced to 0 Potential). Someone with +1 Potential: Combat Magic and +2 Potential: Information-Gathering Magic could not cast a spell to create food in the wilderness, for example.\par Failing a spell miserably causes the temporary loss of a level of Magic Potential (see Section 7.15, Resolution). When this happens, the magician faints for at least one combat round. He needs a Good Constitution roll to wake up (roll each round). When he comes to, the magician may function normally, even attempting to cast the same spell again \emdash  if he hasn\rquote t dropped below 0 Potential.\par If a magician has two or more types of Potential that are appropriate for the spell being cast, and a loss of Potential is called for, the GM decides which type of Potential is reduced. For example, a magician has one level of Combat Magic and two levels of Fire Magic, and fails miserably on a fireball spell. The GM could say that he has lost either his one level of Combat Magic or one of his Fire Magic levels, but not one of each.\par If a magician drops to \endash 1 Potential in any given specialty, he immediately falls into a coma, lasting anywhere from an hour to a day (GM\rquote s decision). When he wakes, he must roll against his Constitution: on a Mediocre or worse roll, he takes a point of damage. He checks Constitution again at the end of every day he is active \endash  a failed result means another point of damage. These wounds cannot be healed until he recharges his Magic Potential back up to level 0.\par A magician with 0 Potential may still cast spells; a magician at \endash 1 Magic Potential, however, cannot attempt any magic spells that would involve that specialty. He may still cast spells of another specialty. For example, a magician who falls to \endash 1 Encyclopedic Magic can no longer cast a spell that allows him to open his blank book and read a magically-appearing encyclopedia entry on a specified topic. But he can still cast spells using his Animal Empathy Magic, allowing him to call and converse with wild animals, provided that Potential is still 0 or greater. He must still make a Constitution check for every day he his active, however, to see if his \endash 1 Encyclopedic Magic Potential is causing him wounds.\par Magic Potential may be recharged only by resting for one week per level. (GMs may alter this time to taste, of course: resting for one day is sufficient for more epic campaigns.) For example, a magician falls to \endash 1 Potential. Resting one week will bring him up to 0 Potential (and cure any wounds incurred by being active while at \endash 1 Potential). A second week of rest will bring him up to +1 Potential.\par No character may gain Magic Potential levels beyond his starting level except through Character Development \emdash  see Chapter 5.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.12  Spells\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When a magician wishes to cast a spell, he describes the result he has in mind. The GM assesses how powerful such an effect would be, based on how prevalent magic is in her campaign. In a low-magic campaign, even a simple spell such as levitating the jail keys to an imprisoned character would be taxing. In a high-magic campaign, however, that would be a trivial spell, and even shooting forth a flash of lightning from a fingertip wouldn\rquote t be out of the ordinary.\par The potency of the spell can be modified by the magician\rquote s appropriate Power level. An \ldblquote average\rdblquote  magician has three levels of appropriate Power when casting a given spell. (Modify this number up or down for harder or easier magic.) That is, a spell is more difficult for a magician with less than three levels of an appropriate Power. Likewise, a magician with four or more appropriate Power levels treats a spell as more trivial than it would be for an average magician.\par \ldblquote Appropriate\rdblquote  Power does not have to be all of the same specialization so long as each Power governs the spell in question. For example, a spell to make a sword fly up and attack a foe could be governed by Flying Magic, Combat Magic, and Control Inanimate Material. If a magician had one level of each of those types of magic, the spell would be of average potency for him.\par A spell is then Trivial, Average, or Potent. (It may also be Very Trivial, or Very Potent, if the GM wishes. In fact, the players will undoubtedly propose truly awesome spells, which should be labeled as Extraordinarily Potent, or with some other impressive adjective.) The GM tells the player what the potency of a proposed spell is \emdash  any magician character would have a fairly good idea of a spell\rquote s potency.\par The spell\rquote s potency determines the Difficulty level. A spell of average potency has a Fair Difficulty level, while a Potent spell has a Difficulty level of at least Good. Likewise, a Trivial spell has a Difficulty level of Mediocre or Poor.\par The GM also decides the duration of the spell if it succeeds \emdash  seconds, minutes, hours, days, etc. The character may try to adjust this, subject to GM approval. For example, the magician can voluntarily take more fatigue or reduce the scope of the effect \emdash  or accept some other penalty \emdash  to lengthen the spell\rquote s duration. Rolling a higher relative degree can also mean the spell lasts longer. Some spells have permanent effects: healing (until wounded again), busting a hole in a wall (until repaired manually or by magic), teleporting to a distant place (until you come back), and so on. Of course, even these spell effects may be temporary in a given GM\rquote s world: healing only lasts a day and the wound reappears, or a hole in the wall fixes itself after a few minutes, or a teleported person automatically returns after an hour in the other location\u8230\'c9.\par The GM also needs to determine if there are any drawbacks to casting a spell. Fudge Magic assumes that spells are tiring to cast, and a magician reduces his Fatigue attribute when casting. The more potent the spell, the more the fatigue. (Fatigue is regained by resting, of course. If Fatigue goes below Terrible, the character passes out. The GM may have separate Fatigue attribute, or base it on Endurance, Constitution, Strength, etc.)\par A GM who dislikes the idea of keeping track of fatigue can change the drawback to something else. Perhaps a magician has a limited number of spells he can cast in a day (or in an hour). In this case, he may have a Spell Point attribute, which is drained by spell casting and regained simply by the passage of time. (A trivial spell won\rquote t drain any Spell Point levels, while an average spell drops a magician from Good Spell Points to Fair, for example, and more potent spells drain two or more levels at a time.) Draining spell points would not necessarily make the magician tired in this case, and Spell Points would regenerate whether the magician was resting or not \emdash  or they might only regenerate with sleep.\par Or maybe each spell affects a magician\rquote s Sanity attribute, and he needs to convalesce to restore it. Or, equally entertaining, a spell might affect the sanity of anyone who witnesses magic! Reduced sanity can manifest in many amusing ways\u8230\'c9.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.13  Mana\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Mana is an energy source capable of manipulating matter, time and space. It can be tapped only by those with Magic Potential.\par The GM determines the availability and density of mana in a given game world, just as she does the average potency of a spell. Mana density can affect two things: how large an area is needed to fuel a given spell effect, and (optionally), how easy or hard it is to cast a spell.\par When a spell of a particular effect is cast, the magician draws a specific type of mana to him to create the effect. The next time this same effect is desired, it will be harder to do: he has drained some of that mana type in the local area.\par The size of the area is defined by the GM. For most fantasy worlds, assume it\rquote s about 50 yards or meters in diameter. In a low-level magic campaign, the area is the size of a town or even city. (This would give meaning to the old line, \ldblquote This town ain\rquote t big enough for both of us\rdblquote  \emdash  dueling wizards!) On the other hand, a high-level magic campaign is so mana-rich that the magician can simply take a step or two and be in a new area. Note that the area governs which spells can be cast without penalty: if one magician casts a healing spell, a second magician will be at \endash 1 to cast a healing spell in the same area within the next 24 hours. (Mana may recharge at a different rate in a given game world, of course.) Note also that a magician may be unaware of what spells were cast in an area before he arrived\u8230\'c9.\par In a mana-rich area, spells may also be easier to cast: +1 or +2 to skill level. Likewise, in a mana-poor area, spells can be harder to cast: \endash 1 or more. The GM decides if this rule is in effect.\par Mana is dispersed and weak in a world such as modern Earth. The average fantasy game world will have much stronger mana, and some high-magic campaigns will simply reek of mana. In any given world, it is possible to vary the amount of mana. Some lands may be mana-rich, while neighboring areas are mana-poor. Mana may flow in currents, or in tides with the phases of the moon. There may be \ldblquote rogue\rdblquote  mana streams that change course and invade new areas, or a mana drought may afflict a given locale. Astrological alignments can affect mana, too \emdash  thus even here on mana-poor Earth there will be places and times of the year when cultists gather to call forth unseen powers\u8230\'c9.\par A PC magician would know the general mana level for at least his home area. He may or may not know whether it fluctuates periodically, or if far lands have different mana levels. In order to determine the mana level of the local area at a given time, a magician must cast a spell specifically to that end.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.14  Skill\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Spell-casting is a skill that must be learned. The default is Non-Existent, and, due to the element of uncertainty in Fudge Magic (mentioned in Section 7.1, Fudge Magic), the maximum base skill level is Fair. This cannot be raised permanently \emdash  but see Section 7.193, Spell-Casting Skill Alternatives.\par One generic Spell-Casting skill is assumed, but the GM may require more if she breaks magic down into different types. It should cost one level just to get a Spell-Casting skill at Terrible.\par Spell-casting skill may be modified (to a maximum of Great) by the following:\par Taking an average time to cast a spell: +0. (Note: the GM assesses the average time for any given spell proposed. Potent spells might take all day, or even longer, while Trivial ones might take one to five minutes.)\par Taking a long time to cast a spell carefully: +1. (Relative to each spell, of course. For a Trivial spell: taking a half an hour or more.)\par Casting a spell much more quickly than normal: \endash 1. (For a Trivial spell: one combat round of concentration.)\par Using normal effort to cast a spell: +0.\par Using extra effort to cast a spell (more fatigue than normal, or counts as two spells cast if there is a limit per day, or reduces Sanity more than normal, etc.): +1 or +2.\par Using less effort than normal to cast a spell: \endash 1 or more. (Reduced fatigue, or it only counts as half a spell against a daily limit, etc.)\par First spell-casting of a particular effect in a given area within 24 hours: +0. (See Section 7.13, Mana, for the size of an area.)\par Additional spell-castings of a particular effect in a given area within 24 hours: \endash 1 per casting.\par For using authentic magic formulae: +1. (The Law of Contagion or the Law of Similarity, for example \emdash  see James Frazer\rquote s classic anthropological study, The Golden Bough. Both Laws require some physical component: a feather to cast a flight spell, a piece of the subject\rquote s hair to heal or hurt her, a drop of water that becomes a water jet, a stick that becomes a staff, a bearskin to change the magician into a bear, etc. Drafting the spell in poetical form earns an additional +1, if the GM is willing.)\par Multiple magicians casting a spell that they have all tried before: +1 (for 2 to X magicians) or +2 (for more than X magicians). (X is set by the GM, anywhere from two to ten, or even more for low-magic campaigns. One magician is assumed to be the primary caster: roll only once against his skill.)\par Mana-rich area: +1 or +2 (optional).\par Normal mana area: +0\par Mana-poor area: \endash 1 or more (optional).\par Other modifiers may also apply, such as in a spell to search the mountains magically for someone you love (+1) or searching for someone you\rquote ve never met (\endash 1).\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.15  Resolution\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Each spell is then resolved as an Unopposed action: the Difficulty level is dependent on the spell potency. Spells of average potency have a Difficulty level of Fair, while more trivial spells have difficulty levels of Mediocre or Poor. (No spell has a Difficulty level of Terrible \emdash  magic just doesn\rquote t work at that level.) More potent spells have Difficulty levels of Good to Superb, or even beyond Superb if a truly powerful effect is desired.\par If the magician surpasses the Difficulty level, the spell occurs as he described it. The better the relative degree, the better the result. The magician suffers \endash 1 (or more) to his Fatigue attribute if the GM deems the spell is fatiguing. (If the GM has chosen some other drawback, of course, apply that instead.)\par Sometimes a skill roll is then needed to do something with the end result of a spell. For example, a fireball needs to be thrown accurately: use the Throwing Skill and Ranged Weapon rules in Chapter 4.\par If the magician equals the Difficulty level, then a watered-down version of the spell occurs. Either it will have a short duration, or reduced potency, or there is a time lag before the spell takes effect, etc. There may be an unexpected side effect, though it won\rquote t be harmful to the magician. There is no penalty for the magician beyond a possible \endash 1 or \endash 2 to Fatigue, at worst.\par If the magician rolls below the Difficulty level, however, he is adversely affected. The energy inherent in mana lashes out at the magician\rquote s psyche instead of being focused as desired. There may (or may not) be some visible magical effect, but it will not be the desired effect, and, if he rolled poorly enough, it may even be inimical to the magician\rquote s goals \emdash  or health\u8230\'c9.\par On a failed roll, the magician is stunned for one combat round (no actions or defense) and takes at least \endash 1 Fatigue. A Terrible result always fails.\par If he rolls a result of \endash 4, the spell automatically fails (no matter what the resulting level) and he also temporarily drains one level of his Magic Potential \emdash  see Section 7.11, Magic Potential, for effects. (This is the \ldblquote riskiness\rdblquote  of magic mentioned in Section 7.1, Fudge Magic.)\par Examples: Barney casts a spell, Create Pizza, of Average potency in a normal mana area and gets \endash 3: a Terrible result. The spell fails and Barney is stunned for a combat round, but he does not drain a level of Magic Potential because he did not roll a \endash 4. Later, in a mana-rich area (+1 to cast), Barney takes a long time (+1) to cast Detect Food, a very Trivial spell (Poor result or better needed for success). He has temporarily raised his skill to Great, the maximum allowed. He rolls a \endash 4 result, which is a Poor rolled result. Although the rolled degree is good enough to cast the spell, Barney still fails because he rolled a \endash 4 result. Barney not only doesn\rquote t detect any food, he also exhausts one level of Magic Potential \emdash  ouch!\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.16  Personal Magic Resistance\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 If the spell is one which attempts to Control another being \emdash  either mentally, physically or spiritually \emdash  Opposed action rolls are also called for. First, the magician casts the spell (as above); then he has to overcome the Personal Magic Resistance of the subject. Magic Resistance may be an attribute or gift (Willpower is a good choice, if there is no specific anti-magic trait), as the GM desires. Magic Resistance may even be a different attribute for different types of spells (a mental attribute for attempts to control the mind, etc.). Note that this second roll is Opposed \emdash  the subject of the spell gets a chance to resist it, and so can influence the result.\par If the GM is willing, the magician may use the result he just rolled as his skill level for the Opposed action. That is, if he rolled a Great result on the spell, he rolls the Opposed action as if his skill were Great. Otherwise, he uses the same level he rolled initially against.\par \ldblquote Control\rdblquote  can mean many things to different GMs. Personal Magic Resistance would resist an attempt to read someone\rquote s mind to one GM, but not to another. However, Magic Resistance does not resist any spell that calls or creates physical energy to lash out at another being. If the magician successfully creates lightning to blast the subject, it is not resisted by Personal Resistance; it is treated as a physical weapon.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.17  Certain Spell-Casting\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sometimes a magician desperately needs a certain result. In this case, he may opt not to roll the dice at all, and simply drain one level of Magic Potential for a guaranteed success. He takes the usual penalties for losing a level of Potential \emdash  see Section 7.11, Magic Potential. This means he\rquote ll faint \emdash   be unconscious \emdash  after casting the spell, which limits the utility for certain spells. You can\rquote t control someone\rquote s mind when you are unconscious, for example\u8230\'c9.\par The GM may restrict this to Trivial spells, or non-Potent spells, or have no restrictions at all, beyond requiring the normal fatigue (or other) penalties. If the spell is one that could logically be resisted by the subject, however, the subject still gets a Resistance roll. In this case, the magician rolls as if his skill were Great.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.18  Enchanting Items\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Items may be permanently enchanted in this system. The magician works for a number of weeks or months (as required by the GM), depending on the number and potency of the spells desired, and the general availability of magic items in the campaign. At the end of each month (or week), the magician rolls against two skills: Spell-casting, and the appropriate Craft skill for the material being worked. The usual penalties apply on failing a spell roll. If he surpasses the Difficulty level on each roll, the spell is slowly being set into the item, one stage at a time. On a roll that only matches the Difficulty level, the work counts as only half a time period, but does progress the enchantment.\par Obviously, a mana-rich area will attract magicians, especially enchanters.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.19  Fudge Magic Options\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 These options offer ways to make Fudge Magic more sweeping, more reliable, less risky, and even make it available to non-magicians.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.191  Generalized Magic Potential\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Some GMs may want the players to have sweeping powers. In this case, each level of Magic Potential allows a character to try any magic effect desired. This is in keeping with certain fictional settings in which learning magic involves general principles rather than specific spell effects. This makes for a very free and open game, which may or may not be to your tastes.\par This system still allows specializations. Simply use faults to limit a magician\rquote s ability to cast certain spells. See Section 6.311, Character Examples, Brogo the Scout.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.192  Magicians & Non-Magicians\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The GM may allow non-magicians to cast spells. In this case, it is risky, as there is no Magic Potential \ldblquote cushion\rdblquote  \emdash  one severe failure is enough to devastate the character. Still, in an emergency, it may be worth the risk. Such a character would still need to have some Spell-casting skill, however. (But see Section 7.193, Spell-casting Skill Alternatives).\par As a substitute for Magic Potential specialization, the GM looks over the character sheet (checking traits, personality, and character background) and decides if a proposed spell would be appropriate for the character. The character must have some aptitude in the proposed spell subject, or he may not cast such a spell. For example, a trained fighter with no knowledge of book learning or foreign languages could conceivably try a combat spell, but not a spell to translate a book written in an unknown script.\par Of course, the same spell is of greater potency for a non-magician than for a magician. This probably means that a non-magician will only have a chance of casting a spell that a magician would consider trivial.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.193  Spell-Casting Skill Alternatives\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Since tastes differ, and Fudge Magic tends to be undependable (see Section 7.1, Fudge Magic), three options are provided for more reliable spell-casting:\par 1) Use the basic Fudge Magic system, but allow a magician to improve his chances of casting a spell beyond Fair. At a cost of one gift (or even supernormal power), this may be raised to Good. At a cost of two more gifts (or supernormal powers), casting skill may be raised from Good to Great, the maximum.\par 2) GMs who want magic to be a lot more reliable can simply treat Spell-casting as any other skill. That is, it costs the usual skill costs to raise it to Good or even Great. Superb Spell-casting is not recommended for any but inherently magical races, even in high-level magic campaigns.\par 3) Spell-Casting is equal to the Willpower attribute, or perhaps Willpower\endash 2. (There may still be a ceiling of Great, Good, or even Fair for Spell-Casting, regardless of the level of Willpower.) This is especially appropriate for games in which non-magicians can cast spells \endash  see Section 7.192, Magicians & Non-Magicians. This is a potent option because the player doesn\rquote t have to buy Spell-casting skill for his character.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.194  Less Risky Spell-Casting\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 To make spell-casting less risky (not necessarily a good thing \emdash  see Section 7.1, Fudge Magic), make it harder to drain a level of Potential.\par Examples (apply as many or as few as desired):\par 1) A magician cannot deplete a level of Magic Potential if he is attempting a Trivial spell. That is, if he rolls a \endash 4 on a Trivial spell, he fails the spellcasting, but doesn\rquote t lose a level of Magic Potential.\par 2) A magician cannot exhaust a level of Magic Potential if he is attempting a Trivial or Average spell.\par 3) A magician cannot deplete a level of Magic Potential if he takes enough time to get a +1 bonus for slow and careful spell-casting.\par 4) A level of Magic Potential can only be depleted on a hurried spell-casting attempt that fails badly.\par 5) A magician cannot drain a level of Magic Potential on the first spell cast each day, or when the moon is full, or if the mana level is low (not enough mana to backlash potently), etc.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 7.2  Sample Miracle System: Fudge Miracles\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Date: December, 1992\par By: Steffan O\rquote Sullivan\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Here is a sample miracle system (not generic), based on the following premises mentioned in Section 2.6, Miracles:\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Can miracles occur by petition: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Yes.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Who can petition: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Anyone. Holy persons have an advantage. (A holy person is one with the supernormal power: Divine Favor, and whose behavior is in synch with the deity\rquote s goals \endash  GM decision on how the player is role-playing.) Religious Investiture \endash  a social title that may or may not coincide with Divine Favor \endash  is not required, and, in fact, does no good if behavior is inappropriate.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Certainty of petitioned miracles: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Mediocre.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Broad or specific requests:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  Specific requests are more likely to be granted.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.21  Divine Favor\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Divine Favor is a supernormal power that can be taken more than once. Each time Divine Favor is taken, it is dedicated to a single deity. It is possible to have Divine Favor from more than one deity in a polytheistic world, or you can have multiple steps of Divine Favor from a single deity. Each step of Divine Favor counts as two supernormal powers (recommended).\par Divine Favor can be temporarily lost if the character does not act in accordance with the deity\rquote s desires. Usually a period of atonement is required to regain Divine Favor. This may be instantaneous for a merciful deity, or it may take up to a month for stricter deities. All steps are lost and regained as a unit when this happens.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.22  Petitioning a Miracle\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A character may petition a miracle at any time. However, some deities do not like to be disturbed for trivial matters, and may ignore requests when it is obvious the character hasn\rquote t even tried to help himself.\par In Fudge Miracles, the petition should be fairly precisely worded. Rather than a simple, \ldblquote Please help me,\rdblquote  the character should focus the plea: \ldblquote We are starving, please feed us,\rdblquote  or, \ldblquote My friend is dying, please heal him.\rdblquote  A holy character can petition for any miraculous result desired, however \emdash  there is no established list of miracles.\par Characters without Divine Favor have a Petitioning skill of Poor (or Mediocre in a more deity-active game). Those with one or more steps of Divine Favor have a Petitioning skill of Fair. Petitioning skill cannot be raised. (In a high-level deity-active campaign, Petitioning skill can be raised to Good at the cost of one supernormal power.) Petitioning skill can be modified, however \emdash  see the next section.\par To resolve a petition, make an Unopposed action roll against Petitioning skill. Each step of Divine Favor grants the holy character one extra chance to roll the dice in a petition to his deity.\par On a Fair or worse result, the roll is a failure. If the character has any steps of Divine Favor from the same deity, he may roll again for each step (this does not count as a separate petition). He can stop at any point \emdash  only the last result rolled counts. This means a character with two steps of Divine Favor can try one, two, or three rolls. If he gets Good, Fair, and Mediocre results, in that order, the result of the petition is Mediocre.\par On a Fair or Mediocre result, the petition isn\rquote t answered by the deity, but the deity isn\rquote t annoyed by the petitioner. On Poor or worse result, however, the deity is angry with the character, and there will be a \endash 1 on the next petition attempt. If the deity is evil, a miracle may actually occur, but not one the petitioner is likely to enjoy\u8230\'c9.\par On a Good or better result, the petition is granted. The better the rolled result, the better the answer to the prayer. For example, a Good result heals one wound or wound level, while a Superb result totally heals the character. A Good result could call a wolf to defend the petitioner, while three lions might answer a Superb result. And so on.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.23  Modifiers to the Petitioning Skill Level\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The GM decides if any modifiers are applicable. Suggested modifiers:\par The petitioner\rquote s behavior has been strictly in accordance with the deity\rquote s desires: +1\par The petitioner\rquote s behavior has not been in accordance with the deity\rquote s desires: \endash 1 or more\par The petition will further the deity\rquote s desires: +1\par The petition goes against the deity\rquote s desires: \endash 1 or more\par The petition involves the deity\rquote s sphere of influence: +1  (Calling for a fireball from a fire god, for example. This is not appropriate for a Supreme God, whose sphere encompasses all things.)\par The petition involves an element antagonistic to the deity: \endash 1 or more (asking the Fire deity to use water, for example.)\par The petition is phrased too generally: \endash 1 or more\par The petitioner has not tried to help himself first: \endash 1 or more.\par The petition is too trivial to bother the deity with: \endash 1 or more\par The petition is a simple, but important, request: +1, provided the petitioner has exhausted his own abilities to accomplish this task. (Example: requesting a piece of chalk, which is trifling, but simply cannot be found anywhere near the character. In this case, chalk would have to be essential to the character\rquote s state of body, mind or soul.)\par The last petition was a Poor or worse result: \endash 1\par The deity feels the petitioner is calling for help too frequently: \endash 1 or more (Optional \emdash  may be invoked by a GM annoyed at constant requests for miracles\u8230\'c9)\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 7.3  Sample Psionic System:Fudge Psi\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Date: February, 1993 & December, 1993\par By: Shawn Garbett and Steffan O\rquote Sullivan\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 There are three types of Psi traits in this system: Powers, skills, and Psychic Reservoir. Only psionicists have Powers and the skills to activate them, but everyone has a Psychic Reservoir to resist psionic attacks.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 7.31  Psionic Powers\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The GM must decide how precisely to define Psi Powers. Since each Power must be bought separately, defining them broadly makes for more powerful characters.\par The following chart (see right) shows some broad groups that include more narrowly defined Psi power groups listed with them. These in turn contain even more narrowly defined powers, which a GM may use as individual Powers if desired. This list may be regrouped, expanded, some powers disallowed, a narrowly defined group made into a broad group that includes other powers, etc. The list is not intended to be comprehensive, but merely a sample.\par The GM should let the players know what depth of Psi skills she is using. Each Power costs one Supernormal Power (two gifts).\par Putting one level in a Power gets it at Terrible. Powers may then be raised at the cost of two skill levels per level, if using the Objective Character Creation system. For example, raising Telekinesis Power to Poor requires two skill levels, and raising it to Mediocre would cost two more skill levels.\par If a GM envisions a psi-rich campaign, of course, the costs should be much cheaper. Allowing many free levels of Supernormal Powers is a good way to do this, but be cautious about trading them for mundane traits.\par Power levels define range, quantity or size of subject affected, etc. \emdash  see Section 2.7, Psi. A Fair Power can do whatever the default average is for the campaign world.\par Some tasks require a minimum Power level, as set by the GM. If the character has the Power, but not at the minimum level required, he may not attempt the action unless he uses Desperation Psionics (Section 7.35). If the psi has the appropriate Power at three or more levels above the minimum required, he is at +1 for that use.\par No psionic ability can be used unless the character has the Power listed on his character sheet.\par A character may take a latent psi Power at the cost of one gift. He can\rquote t use the Power (may not take any related psi skills), but later in the campaign he may spend EP equal to another gift to awaken the Power. He would then have to learn the skills to control the Power.\par It is also possible to take some interesting faults that will limit the nature (and reduce the cost) of any Power. \ldblquote Usable only in emergencies\rdblquote  is a common theme in fiction, for example.\par \tab \par Very Broad\tab Mildly Broad\tab \tab Narrow\par Groups\tab \tab Groups\tab \tab \tab Groups\par Antipsi\tab \tab Distort\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab Nullify\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab Resist\par ESP\tab \tab Astral Projection\par \tab \tab Telesense\tab \tab Clairaudience\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \