make fireballs or direct the fire to spread in a given direction.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fortune Telling: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 you can see a possible future, as through a glass, darkly. This only works on others, and never on events which are important to you \emdash  your own future is always obscured.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Green Thumb: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 plants respond extraordinarily well to you, with increased growth, health, and production.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Healing Hands:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  you can heal one level of wounds with a touch. This takes one minute and is fatiguing (see Hedge Magic, below, for fatigue effects).\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Second Sight:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  you can see through illusions and \ldblquote read\rdblquote  general personalities. You can\rquote t read minds or know any details of personality, but you\rquote ll know who to trust if you concentrate.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Shapeshifter:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  you can change into one GM-approved animal or plant form. It takes three combat rounds to change fully, during which you are defenseless. [Costs two Gifts]\par You don\rquote t need to spend any points on skills to have Innate Magic \endash  you only have to buy the Gift. No skill roll is usually required \endash  the talent is automatic, although it may take time. Should it ever be an issue, each talent is known at a Great level.\par You may add to this list any innate magic abilities for non-human races in your campaign world.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Hedge Magic\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Note: Hedge Magic is based on the Hedge Magic system created for GURPS\u174\'a8 by S. John Ross. (GURPS is a registered trademark of Steve Jackson Games.) \par GURPS Hedge Magic can be found at:\par http://www.io.com/~sjohn/hedge.htm\par Hedge Magic is the \ldblquote peasant\rdblquote  version of magic: hedgerow witches and village wizards concocting herbal potions, creating charms, nullifying (or, alas, casting) curses, etc.\par You may spend up to four points in the Hedge Magic group, but only as many points as you have levels of the Magic Talent: Hedge Magic Gift. That is, if you take only one level of Magic Talent: Hedge Magic Gift, you may only spend one point on Hedge Magic skills.\par The skill list for Hedge Magic follows, and is treated like any other skill group. That is, one point spent in Hedge Magic allows you to choose 3 skills at Fair and 1 at Mediocre, etc. Each skill is a mundane skill found in other skill groups \emdash  if you learn it in the Hedge Magic group, there is no need to learn it from another group.\par You may use a mundane skill from this group without applying Hedge Magic. But if you use Hedge Magic, you can accomplish more than you could otherwise. Hedge Magic is not flashy magic \emdash  you\rquote ll never see major magical effects from it. It\rquote s nonetheless effective in what it tries to do.\par Hedge Magic is fatiguing, however \emdash  your Health attribute drops one level, temporarily, for each use. If your Health level falls below Terrible, you are exhausted and collapse \emdash  treat as the fatigue equivalent of \ldblquote Incapacitated.\rdblquote  A level of fatigued Health is regained simply by resting 15 minutes.\par Another possible downside to Hedge Magic is that the results may be perceived as magical, which, depending on the situation, may get the caster in trouble.\par The following mundane skills are the only ones which may be enhanced by Hedge Magic, unless the GM permits otherwise. Those without descriptions are simply assumed to provide enhanced results.\par Animal Handling\par Astrology: fortune telling for other folk \emdash  grants no inkling of your own future.\par Camouflage: if you don\rquote t want to be seen, you\rquote re very hard to spot.\par Cooking: tasty, nourishing, mildly healing.\par Counseling: your sympathetic ear and wise advise can soothe troubled souls.\par Craft: most of the craft skills, such as Pottery, Smithy, Tailor, etc., allow you to make superior quality items more quickly. These items are of exceptional quality, but are not really magic items\u8230\'c9 or are they?\par Detect Lies\par Farming: a very common use of hedge magic, you can bless or curse crops: increased yield, faster growth, etc. \emdash  or the opposite.\par First aid: you can stop bleeding with a touch, and enable the severely injured to survive until appropriate care is available.\par Herb Lore: the archetypal hedge magic skill: preparation of magical concoctions. While not as potent as alchemical elixirs, they are quicker to make. Common potions include healing, sleep, love, charisma, strength, endurance, etc. \emdash  ask the GM what\rquote s possible. Use Poisons for harmful potions.\par Medicine: expeditious and efficacious healing.\par Move Quietly\par Poisons: your poisons are more potent, faster acting, and harder to detect. Shame on you.\par Storytelling: you can enthrall an audience, and even sway their mood to your purposes.\par Tracking\par Veterinarian: expeditious and efficacious healing. For evil hedge witches, this is also the skill used to sicken animals, a common complaint in former days.\par Weather Sense: you\rquote re remarkably accurate.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Scholarly Magic\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Scholarly Magic is the \ldblquote upper class\rdblquote  version of magic: sorcerers in towers poring over ancient tomes, wizards roaming the world seeking out spell-crafters and new sources of power, colleges of magicians teaching apprentices while debating amongst themselves the merits of this spell or that, etc.\par A sample Scholarly Magic system is presented below. It\rquote s a flexible magic system, with no preset spell list, and thus leaves a lot of decisions up to the GM. Gamemasters are welcome to substitute any other magic system of choice. The sourcebook }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A Magical Medley}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  from Grey Ghost Games contains a chapter on creating Fudge magic systems, as well as six sample systems. The Gramarye is particularly recommended; you can also find it online at http://fudge.phoenyx.net/gramarye/. Also recommended: Fudge Magic (see section 7.1 of the core Fudge rules), GURPS\u174\'a8 Magic, and Four-by-Five Magic (http://www.io.com/~sos/rpg/4by5.html).\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magical Talent: Scholarly Magic\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Characters wishing to learn Scholarly Magic must have the Magical Talent: Scholarly Magic Gift. You may spend up to four points in the Scholarly Magic group, but only as many points as you have levels of the Magic Talent: Scholarly Magic Gift. If you spend only one Gift on Magic Talent: Scholarly Magic, you may only spend one point on Scholarly Magic skills. Note that Scholarly Magic skills cost more; see below.\par Characters without Magical Talent may learn the Thaumatology Knowledge Skill instead. This will allow them to recognize magic spells, skills, and possibly magic items and talismans (especially if powerful or well known), but not cast magic themselves.\par \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Skill Points and the Scholarly Magic Skill Group\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The Scholarly Magic skills are difficult areas of study, covering magical incantations, rituals, arcane knowledge, and more. There is no default for these skills, so a character learning Scholarly Magic in-game (as opposed to pre-game character creation) would learn the skill at Terrible. They cost more at character creation, as well.\par Note that you may trade 1 Scholarly Magic skill for 2 skills at one level lower. And remember that you can spend only a