nes required, hence the more time required in applying the runes. \par Restrictions: Each rune or symbol has a different purpose, and the mage must know the appropriate rune for a given magical feat. The Gamemaster may create a list of runes or other symbols the mage knows, with brief descriptions of how they may be used in the game. \par Note: When used in conjunction with other Scholarly Magic skills, the player may roll against the Rune skill even if Runes is not the lowest skill level involved \endash  but only if the runes involved are directly related to the magical feat.\par \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Shamanism:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  Spirit Magic. Shamans interact with spirits of varying powers. Spirits include ancestral spirits, anima (spirits that imbue every object; some anima are more powerful than others), and \ldblquote guardian spirits.\rdblquote  \par }\pard \li720\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magical Feats: A Shaman can cause any magical effect the spirits he deals with are capable of creating. Shamans can also exorcise troublesome spirits and ghosts, and even creatures (or constructs or demons) called through Conjuration, Necromancy, or Sorcery.\par In-Game Requirements: Shamans don\rquote t typically need to expend much mana, as any magical feat beyond the initial contact with a spirit is performed by the spirit itself. Once contacted, a spirit may require a bribe, or bargain, or some other method of persuasion to actually perform the requested feat. Spirits must be honored, with each spirit requiring a different ritual. Dancing, sacrificing (of goods, animals, or even sentient creatures), and singing are often essential features of Shamanistic rituals.\par Restrictions: The Shamanism roll made when a Shaman character wishes to perform a magic feat determines whether or not the Shaman successfully contacts the desired spirit.  An additional skill, such as Flatter, Intimidate, Parley/Negotiate or other persuasive means may be needed to convince the spirit to actually perform the magic feat requested of it. Shamans who fail to uphold their part of any spirit bargain tend not to be able to practice Shamanism well for long. The Gamemaster may require a Shaman to use the Extra Sensory Perception skill for communicating with the spirits through trances and out-of-body experiences. Artificing is required to create shamanistic objects (charms, talismans, and the like) imbued with spirits that perform magic for the wielder. \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sorcery:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  The \ldblquote Black Arts.\rdblquote  Sorcery relies on summoning demons and other powerful, evil beings to trick or bribe or force them into doing the sorcerer\rquote s bidding.\par }\pard \li720\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magical Feats: Anything that can be done by a demon, devil, or evil spirit can be accomplished with Sorcery \endash  provided the sorcerer is powerful enough to summon the required entity and crafty enough to convince it to do his bidding. Sorcerers may gain innate magical gifts and other magical powers, either permanently or temporarily, through their dealings with powerful evil beings.\par In-Game Requirements: There are three facets to sorcerous dealings \endash  summoning the evil being; controlling the evil being (by holding it within a circle of power, for example); and persuading it to do the summoner\rquote s bidding. The summoned being  will seek to twist or distort or otherwise alter any deal struck with the sorcerer, so sorcerers must take care to protect themselves and negotiate their deals carefully.\par Restrictions: Penalties of failure are severe, and often gruesome. Evil beings do not take kindly to being summoned against their will, and even less kindly to forced servitude.  Should a sorcerer\rquote s control slip, even for an instant, the demon or spirit will do its best to harm its captor. Few cultures welcome sorcerers, so the Secret Fault may be required. The Gamemaster may (and probably should) restrict Sorcery to non-player characters, or to PCs with specifically crafted backgrounds (such as a sorcerer-hunter who was once a practicing sorcerer himself).\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Transmutation:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  Turning things into other things. Living creatures may oppose such transformations with Willpower.\par }\pard \li720\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magical Feats: The more unalike the original object and the transmutated object are, the harder the feat. Turning living objects into inanimate objects (such as statues) or vice versa is especially difficult. Turning water to wine, or a glutton into a hog, are easier. Such transformations are usually of short duration; it takes much skill and power to affect a permanent transformation.\par In-Game Requirements: Transmutation is a difficult art, often requiring much mana. Affecting a permanent transformation usually requires the use of a powerful enchanted item, such as a staff of transmutation or wand of frog princes.\par Restrictions: If the magician\rquote s target has a Willpower attribute, it may resist the magical change. Resolve as an Opposed Action, the mage\rquote s Transmutation skill versus the target\rquote s Willpower attribute, plus or minus any modifiers the GM sets.\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Wizardry: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The \ldblquote Wise Arts.\rdblquote  The most scholarly of scholarly magic, Wizardry concerns itself with the laws of magic, the flow of mana, and the underlying structures of spells, incantations, and enchantments. Wizards know many ways to gather mana, and how to use it efficiently.\par }\pard \li720\sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magical Feats: Wizardry can detect or analyze magic and magic items, dispel magic, alter mana flows, and perform similar feats that directly affect the forces that make magic possible. Wizardry can also lower the cost in power points of a given feat (see Mana, below).\par In-Game Requirements: When applying Wizardry, the Wizard must take time to consider applicable magical laws, mana flows in the area, and any circumstances present at the time of casting that could affect the outcome.\par Restrictions: The GM may require the player to refer to \ldblquote laws of magic\rdblquote  (Similarity, Contagion, or whatever \ldblquote laws\rdblquote  are appropriate for the game world) , create rhyming \ldblquote incantations,\rdblquote  or otherwise embellish the description of what the mage is doing when using Wizardry in a magical feat.\par Note: When used in conjunction with other Scholarly Magic skills, Wizardry may provide a +1 bonus to the character\rquote s skill roll. This occurs only if the character\rquote s Wizardry skill is higher than one or more of the other Scholarly Magic skills involved (see below).\par \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Magical Power (Mana)\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Casting scholarly magic requires mana, or power points. Truly trivial magic (with effects similar to those attainable with Hedge Magic) uses negligible amounts of mana, but most scholarly magic requires one or more power points.\par Each level of the Magical Talent: Scholarly Gift grants the character 5 power points to use in performing magic.\par The number of Gifts used to purchase Magical Talent also affects how much mana the character can channel and control. One Magical Talent Gift allows the character to perform trivial magic, and magical feats costing 1 power point. Two Magical Talent Gifts increase that to 2 power points, and so on.\par Attempting to channel more power than the character can normally handle requires a Willpower roll, Difficulty Level equal to Fair plus 1 per power point over the character\rquote s usual limit. Thus, a character with 2 Magical Talent Gifts attempting to channel 4 power points to perform a magical feat must roll Willpower against a Difficulty Level of Great (Fair +2). Failure results in the loss of one level of Health by each level the Difficulty Level is missed. (A Mediocre result with a Great Difficulty Level would result in the loss of 3 Health levels; see Fatigue, below.)\par Power points may be regained at the rate of 1 point per 2 hours of sleep or 1 hour of undisturbed meditation, up to the number allowed by the magician\rquote s Magical Talent Gifts.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fatigue\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 In addition to requiring mana, Scholarly Magic is fatiguing (much like Hedge Magic). The character\rquote s Health attribute drops one level for each use. If Health level falls below Terrible, the character is exhausted and collapses \emdash  treat as the fatigue equivalent of \ldblquote Incapacitated.\rdblquote  A level of fatigued Health is regained simply by resting 15 minutes.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Performing Magical Feats\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When a character wishes to perform magic, the player should describe to the Gamemaster the magical results the character wishes to achieve. The more detail included in the description, the better. Scholarly magic depends heavily on the magician\rquote s concentration and clarity of thought, and if the player isn\rquote t paying much attention to what the character wishes to accomplish, the GM may assume the character isn\rquote t, either.\par The player may also describe the magician character\rquote s actions, and aspects of the ritual being used to perform the magic feat, if desired. Including poetic incantations (especially if it\rquote s good poetry) and other \ldblquote flavor\rdblquote  in the description of the ritual may be worth bonuses to the character\rquote s skill.\par There are several aspects that should be considered for each magical feat:\par \bullet  Skill required (Difficulty Level)\par \bullet  Mana required (power points that will be used)\par \bullet  Time to perform (from an instant to years)\par \bullet  Materials required (if any)\par \bullet  Optional modifying circumstances (lots possible)\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Skill: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The more complex the desired results, the higher the Difficulty Level the GM should set for a magical feat. Difficulty Levels start at Fair for simple magic, such as creating \endash  but not controlling \endash  fire, or speaking with a spirit that\rquote s already \ldblquote awake\rdblquote  and interested in communicating. Difficulty can range up to Legendary or even beyond, for god-like magical feats. Some \ldblquote trivial\rdblquote magic may have Difficulty Levels of Mediocre, but any magic requiring power points should be of at least Fair Difficulty.\par Once the Difficulty Level is set, the player rolls against the magician\rquote s Scholarly Magic skill. Use the lowest skill if the feat requires more than one Scholarly Magic skill.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Example:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  Enchanting a Staff of Dragon Summoning and Control requires skill in Artificing, Conjuration, and Mesmerism. An enchanter with Artificing: Mediocre, Conjuration: Fair, and Mesmerism: Good would roll on a skill level of Mediocre.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Mana:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  The more powerful or all-encompassing the desired results, the more power points will be required. \ldblquote Trivial\rdblquote  magic may require so little mana that power point use isn\rquote t even tracked. This doesn\rquote t mean a mage can go around popping off trivial spells all day, though, since even trivial spells requiring no power points will fatigue the mage.\par Note that the Difficulty Level and the mana required are not related; one measures complexity, the other power. Creating a small colored flame that dances in a pattern that recreates an ancient battle between wizards may be of Legendary Difficulty, but require only one power point.\par Note also that some magical feats require more power points than any but the most Legendary Wizards have access to. Such feats are possible, either through pooling the power points of more than one magician, or drawing on \ldblquote mana vessels\rdblquote  containing stored power points (see Artificing, above). Some rare materials are natural \ldblquote mana vessels.\rdblquote  \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Time: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Generally speaking, the more complex the magical feat desired, the greater the time required in preparing. This is usually true of powerful spells as well. Complex, powerful spells should take a lot of time to prepare. You can trade Time for Difficulty Level, if you wish. The less time you take in preparing the magical incantation, enchantment, or other feat, the greater the Difficulty Level. Likewise, increasing the preparation and casting time may, at the GM\rquote s option, lower the Difficulty Level.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Materials:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1  If the GM wishes, magical feats may require the use of materials related to the effects desired; sulphur or coal for fire, a feather for a flying spell, and so on. Some magical feats may be performed with nothing more than the magician\rquote s concentration or some words of power; others may require rare and precious materials.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Modifiers: }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The GM may apply any modifiers desired. Examples include bonuses for using special materials (or using materials at all if not normally required); for performing magic in naturally magical surroundings; for applying any \ldblquote laws of magic\rdblquote  the GM allows (if they have the Wizardry skill). Penalties may be applied for distracting circumstances, or the GM may require a Willpower roll for the mage to avoid becoming distracted and possibly losing control of the magic he\rquote s wielding.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Determining Results\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The GM judges whether a feat is within the character\rquote s capabilities \endash  if not, she should warn the player that attempting greater magics than the character is ready for is dangerous. The GM also determines what the actual result will be. Magic in Fantasy Fudge is an art, not a science; and the same \ldblquote spell\rdblquote  cast in the same way may have varying results.\par In general, the greater the success in performing a magical feat, the closer to the desired effects the results will be. Spectacular successes may carry unexpected benefits, such as less time required to cast, lower power point cost, and the like. Abysmal failures should be spectacular, as well. Use your imagination, but don\rquote t allow the results to outright kill the character (unless he\rquote s a sorcerer)! Less abysmal failures will produce unexpected and possibly unwanted results, including greater power point cost with little or nothing to show for it.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Spell Lists\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 It\rquote s a good idea to take some time before play to work out some \ldblquote standard\rdblquote  spells a scholarly mage is likely to use. Ask the player what spells the character is likely to have sought out, and work out some sample Difficulty Levels, Mana costs,  and required time and materials for those spells. Feel free to \ldblquote steal\rdblquote  spells from other games to help build a spell list. Consider the spell\rquote s desired affect rather than the actual game mechanics used in the game it was designed for, and base the difficulty and power levels on that.\par Spell descriptions should be considered guidelines rather than strict definitions of spell effects and costs. Magical feats and their results are meant to be improvised by the Gamemaster as well as by the character.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sample Spells\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \ldblquote Skinwalker.\rdblquote  Skill: Transmutation.  Feat: Temporarily shapechanges caster into a wolf. Difficulty Level: Good. Power Points: 2. Time: 20 minutes. Materials: Ritually prepared wolfskin (may be reused).\par \ldblquote Targeted Fireball.\rdblquote  Skills: Conjuration, Elementalism, Kineticism. Feat: Fireball moves to target and explodes. Difficulty Level: Fair. Power Points: 1 (more for larger fireball). Time: 1 combat round. Materials: Red garnet (destroyed).\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Clerical Magic\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 5-Point Fudge uses Fudge Miracles (section 7.2) as a basis for Clerical Magic.\par The Gift Divine Favor is required to use Clerical Magic. It\rquote s possible to play a priest without Divine Favor \endash  simply choose the Professional skill Counseling/Priest and assemble an appropriate set of skills. But such a priest has no ability to use Clerical Magic. Note also that you don\rquote t have to be an ordained priest in any religion to have Divine Favor or to use Clerical Magic.\par Skills available to a character with Divine Favor include the mundane and the supernatural. The supernatural are cast strictly through the power of the God or gods served by the cleric. If the cleric\rquote s behavior is inconsistent with the God\rquote s desires, this ability is withdrawn, at least temporarily.\par Supernatural skills in the following list are detailed \endash  any other skill is mundane and uses the description in the Skill list. This list assumes a benign deity who grants free will and supernatural aid to its followers in times of crisis. Other skills may be appropriate for other types of clerics \endash  plant magic for Druids, for example, and more spirit magic for shamans. Evil clerics have a different skill list \endash  your characters should pray they never meet them\u8230\'c9.\par Aid Task: by touching someone who is trying to accomplish a task that is in the deity\rquote s interest, you can grant a +1 to their skill.\par Arcane Lore\par Banish Spirits: you can force spirits and demons from another plane to return to their proper plane.\par Bless: you can grant a +1 (or more, if the GM is willing) defensive bonus to someone, which lasts until the next combat ends.\par Counseling/Priest\par Detect Lies: your ability at this is enhanced.\par Exorcism: you can force a spirit or demon which has invaded a body or dwelling to leave.\par First Aid\par Healing: you can channel healing from the deity you serve.\par Medicine\par Oratory\par Parley/Negotiate\par Persuade\par Remove Fatigue: you can restore endurance to the weary.\par Repel Undead: you can ward off zombies, vampires, ghosts, etc., from your presence.\par Teaching\par Theology/Rituals\par True Sight: you can see through illusions.\par Ward: you can protect a person or all within a room-sized area from supernatural evil, either spells, spirits, undead, demons, etc.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Calling on Divine Favor\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When a cleric with Divine Favor calls on his deity, make an Unopposed action roll against the specific Clerical Magic skill (see Action Resolution, above).  On a Good or better result, the cleric\rquote s petition for divine favor is answered. For clerical skills where exact results aren\rquote t quantified (such as Healing), the better the rolled result, the better the answer to the prayer. For example, a Good result may reduce one wound by one wound level, while a Superb result could heal an injured character entirely.\par On a Fair or Mediocre result, the favor simply isn\rquote t granted. On a Poor or worse result, the deity may be angry with the cleric. The GM should consider the character\rquote s recent actions, especially in regard to the cleric\rquote s religious beliefs. If there are any reasons for the cleric\rquote s deity to be less than satisfied with service rendered, this is the time for that to become abundantly clear. If the cleric\rquote s behavior has been exemplary (so far as the deity is concerned), a failure simply means the deity was busy with other things, or considered the favor unimportant (or counter to its own desires) for some reason.\par Modifiers: The GM can apply any modifiers she thinks applicable. Suggestions may be found in Section 7.2 of the core Fudge rules, and include +1 or more if the cleric has recently been furthering the deity\rquote s cause, or \endash 1 if the most recent petition for Divine Favor ended in a Poor or worse result.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Non-Human Races\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For each non-human race in the game world, create a \ldblquote racial package\rdblquote  that includes such things as racial gifts, faults, any special powers (see Chapter 2: Supernormal Powers in the basic Fudge rules) and modifiers, including Scale and Attribute and Skill modifiers.\par Determine how many \ldblquote Gifts\rdblquote  the racial package is worth, and require that many Gifts be spent (or attribute levels reduced, or extra Faults incurred). Some racial packages will balance out, not requiring the use of a Gift slot. Some racial packages may actually qualify as Faults, allowing the character to compensate with higher Attributes or additional Gifts.\par Some Skills, Gifts, Faults, Supernormal Powers, etc. may be unique to members of particular races.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sample Racial Package: Elves\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attribute Modifiers: +1 Agility, +1 Perception. Gifts: Magical Talent: Innate Gifts, Eagle Eyes; Very Long Lifespan. Faults: Elven Code of Honor; Honesty; Truthfulness. Cost: 1 Gift.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sample Racial Package: Halflings\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attribute Modifiers: Scale \endash 2, Health +1. Faults: Social Stigma in non-halfling lands. Cost: 2 Faults.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Equipping Characters\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The Gamemaster may wish to define a \ldblquote starting equipment\rdblquote  package that all characters will have (unless they took the Poor Fault or Wealthy Gift). This may include such things as clothing (perhaps one good set and an everyday set), footgear, and weapons appropriate to their Combat skills. They may also have travel or camping gear (such as wineskins or canteens, a messkit, a tinderbox, and other items common in the campaign world).\par Players should be allowed to customize their characters\rquote  equipment list a bit, adding things that make sense given their skills. Characters with Climbing skill may have rope, a grappling hook, iron spikes, or similar equipment that can aid in climbing.\par Characters should also be allowed to purchase equipment \endash  spending their hard-earned wealth for the privilege, of course. The GM may want to prepare an \ldblquote equipment list\rdblquote  with average prices for common items available in the campaign world. Appropriate equipment lists may also be borrowed or adapted from other roleplaying games. \par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Damage Factors and Equipment\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For weapons, armor, and other equipment likely to be used in combat situations, the player or GM should determine Offensive and Defensive Damage Factors.\par Damage Factors are simply the sum of damage-related modifiers for each weapon or armor type. These factors will be used to determine damage points and wound levels in combat (see Wounds, section ).\par Sample \ldblquote Wound Factors\rdblquote  are detailed on in section 4.53. Use these to determine the \ldblquote Offensive Damage Factor\rdblquote  for each character/weapon combination.\par For example, a character with Good Strength wielding a longsword would have an Offensive Damage Factor of +4 (+1 for Strength; +2 for a large one-handed weapon; +1 for sharpness). A character with Fair Strength wielding the same weapon would have an ODF of +3 (no Strength bonus). Remember to include any bonuses or penalties due to Scale when dealing with non-human combatants.\par Then determine the character\rquote s \ldblquote Defensive Damage Factor\rdblquote  for both \ldblquote unarmored\rdblquote  and \ldblquote armored\rdblquote  (if the character possesses armor). Modifiers range from +0 for no armor to +4 or more for heavy or magical armor. Scale and Gifts such as Tough Hide can also affect a character\rquote s Defensive Damage Factor.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Character Development\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 After each game session, award Fudge Points (see section 1.36) to the characters. Fantasy Fudge suggests 1-3 Fudge Points per gaming session. The GM may reward really good roleplaying and problem solving with more Fudge Points. Fudge Points may be used to \ldblquote fudge\rdblquote  a game result, or they may be saved up and traded for Experience Points at a rate of 3 Fudge Points = 1 EP. The EPs may then be spent to raise skills or attributes, or acquire additional Gifts, etc., as outlined in Chapter 5: Character Development.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Settings for Fantasy Fudge\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Where would a fantasy roleplaying game be without a setting? Wherever you want it to be!\par Use Fantasy Fudge with your favorite fantasy world, whether that\rquote s one of your own creation, a fictional world brought to life by your favorite fantasy author, a published fantasy game world, or any of a number of game worlds created by other gamers. The Grey Ghost website (http://www.fudgerpg.com) has links to many game settings created for Fudge.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Action Resolution\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 There are two types of actions in Fantasy Fudge \endash  Opposed Actions, and Unopposed Actions.\par A fight between two creatures will most often be resolved as a series of Opposed Actions. \par An attempt to climb a cliff will most often be resolved as an Unopposed Action. The Gamemaster sets the \ldblquote Difficulty Level\rdblquote  that must be met or surpassed for the action to succeed.\par Note that very easy actions should be automatic; no need to roll. Likewise with impossible actions; the character just can\rquote t do it, and will fail in the attempt no matter how lucky the player is with dice.\par If the character doesn\rquote t have an appropriate skill to attempt a task, the GM may allow the player to roll on the default level for that skill (usually Poor). The GM may call for a roll against an attribute instead of a skill whenever it seems appropriate (asking for an Agility check rather than a Climbing check, for example), although an unskilled character should get a negative modifier to the dice roll.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Rolling the Dice \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When a character attempts an action, roll percentiles (or use 100ths of a second on a stopwatch) and consult this table:\par \par Rolled:   1\tab 2-6\tab 7-18\tab 19-38\tab 39-62\tab 63-82\tab 83-94\tab 95-99\tab 00\par Result:  \endash 4\tab \endash 3\tab \endash 2\tab \endash 1\tab +0\tab +1\tab +2\tab +3\tab +4\par \par If you have Fudge dice, roll four of them instead.\par The result (from \endash 4 to +4) is used as a modifier to a skill or character trait.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Unopposed Actions\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 The Gamemaster sets a Difficulty Level for any unopposed action. This includes most ranged weapon combat \emdash  it\rquote s difficult for a character to actually hinder someone\rquote s attempt to fire at him, although if he has Quick Reflexes he could attempt to dodge out of the line of fire.\par The Difficulty Level should take into account everything but the character\rquote s skill (and modifiers to that skill provided by equipment or character condition, including injuries). A task with a Difficulty Level of Poor is very easy, while something with a Difficulty Level of Superb is very hard. For legendary feats, set the Difficulty Level even higher (Superb +2, for example). When in doubt, set the Difficulty Level to Fair. That will give a character with a Fair skill a 62% chance of succeeding.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Opposed Actions\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When characters engage in opposed actions (including hand-to-hand combat), the players of each contestant roll the dice, add the indicated modifiers to the appropriate skill level, and compare the results. The GM rolls for all NPCs.\par Relative Degree measures the difference between the results. If one character has a Good success in an Opposed Action, and the second character has a Mediocre success, the Relative Degree is +2 from the winner\rquote s perspective, and \endash 2 from the loser\rquote s perspective. In combat, the winner adds the Relative Degree to his Offensive Damage Factor to determine the number of damage points inflicted.\par If it helps, you can convert the characters\rquote  combat skills to their numerical equivalents before adding all modifiers (including the random dice roll). Alternatively, put your finger on the Terrible - Superb Trait Scale list, and move up one line for every +1 or down one line for every \endash 1.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Combat\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 In Fudge, a combat \ldblquote round\rdblquote  can be defined as the Gamemaster wishes. Fantasy Fudge assumes one \ldblquote round\rdblquote  (roll of the dice) equals about 3 seconds of combat action. Actions occur simultaneously.\par Combat can be resolved as an Unopposed action if it involves ranged combat, a combatant being caught unawares (giving a \ldblquote free attack\rdblquote  to the opponent), or a \ldblquote cannon-fodder\rdblquote  type of NPC (see Special Circumstances, below). Otherwise, treat combat as a series of Opposed Actions.\par The players of characters engaged in opposed actions will roll the dice once each combat round; the result determines the winner of that round. \par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Special Circumstances\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A Terrible hit never damages the target, even if it beats the opponent\rquote s sub-Terrible result.\par When multiple opponents attack a single target, the lone fighter is at \endash 1 to skill for each foe beyond the first. The player rolls once; compare the result with each of the opponents\rquote  rolls. The solo combatant has to defeat or tie all of the opponents in order to inflict a wound. If he beats all of his foes, he may hit one of his choice. Otherwise, he can only wound another whose result is at least two levels below his. The lone fighter takes multiple wounds if two or more enemies hit him.\par Unlike \ldblquote star\rdblquote  NPCs, who are treated much like PCs, \ldblquote cannon fodder\rdblquote  opponents will always get results equal to their trait levels. You can treat this as an Unopposed Action with a Difficulty Level equal to the NPC\rquote s combat skill.\par When \ldblquote cannon fodder\rdblquote  NPCs gang up on a player character, use the \ldblquote multiple opponents\rdblquote  rule above, but compare the outnumbered fighter\rquote s result with the NPCs\rquote  combat skill levels (not \ldblquote rolled degrees\rdblquote ).\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Wounds\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When a character wins a combat round, use the following formula to determine the damage done:\par \par Winner\rquote s Offensive Damage Factor (including Scale)\par \tab \tab plus\par Relative Degree (number of levels won by)\par \tab \tab minus\par Loser\rquote s Defensive Damage Factor (including Scale)\par \tab equals Damage Points Inflicted\par \par If the result is 0 or less, no damage is inflicted. If the result is positive, look at the table below to determine the severity of the particular wound. \par \par \tab 1,2\tab 3,4\tab 5,6\tab 7,8\tab 9+\par \tab Scratch\tab Hurt\tab Very Hurt\tab Incapacitated\tab Near Death\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \par \par The boxes below the wound levels represent how many of each wound type a character can take. The player checks off one box for each wound received. A 6-point wound requires the \ldblquote Very Hurt\rdblquote  box to be checked, and so on. If there is no open box for a given wound result, the character takes the next highest wound for which there is an open box.\par A wounded character suffers penalties to most actions:\par Scratch: no penalty\par Hurt: \endash 1 to most actions\par Very Hurt: \endash 2 to most actions\par Incapacitated: incapable of any but the most basic, painfully slow actions\par Near Death: unconscious, will die in less than an hour unless helped\par Penalties are not cumulative. Only the penalty for the highest recorded wound level counts. Scratches go away after a battle, provided the character has five or ten minutes to attend to them. See section 4.8 for rules for healing wounds.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Stun, Knockout, and Pulling Punches\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A character may try to stun or knock out his opponent rather than wound her, in which case a Hurt result is called a \ldblquote Stun\rdblquote  and the \endash 1 penalty associated with being \ldblquote Hurt\rdblquote  lasts for one combat round only. A Very Hurt result would be \ldblquote Very Stunned\rdblquote  and the \endash 2 penalty lasts 2 combat rounds. An \ldblquote Incapacitated\rdblquote  result indicates the opponent has been knocked out.\par A character may also pull his punches. The player simply announces the maximum wound level his character will inflict if he wins the combat round. See section 4.62 for more information.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Situational Rolls\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 A Situational Roll is used to show luck, outside events, or the overall situation. It isn\rquote t based on any character traits. Simply roll the dice. A Situational Roll of \endash 2 gives a Poor result; the situation is not good.\par The GM can use a Situational Roll to determine anything from the weather to a non-player character\rquote s attitude. \par A Situational Roll can also be used to check a creature\rquote s \ldblquote morale\rdblquote  during combat, especially when the creature is first wounded, and again if it becomes Very Hurt. A \endash 1 or worse Situational Roll in the midst of combat may mean that the NPC will try to surrender or run away. You may add the NPC\rquote s current modifiers due to wounds to the \ldblquote morale\rdblquote  roll. A Hurt creature with a \endash 1 Situational Roll would actually be experiencing a Poor reaction to the combat, and would probably be doing whatever it could to get out of the fight\u8230\'c9.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Fudge Points\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Fudge Points allow players to \ldblquote fudge\rdblquote  a game result. Spending a Fudge Point will allow the player or character to: \par \bullet \tab Accomplish an Unopposed action automatically and with panache. The GM may veto this use for actions with a Difficulty Level beyond Superb, or greater than 3 levels higher than the character\rquote s skill or attribute used in the roll.\par \bullet \tab Alter a die roll one level, up or down as desired. The die roll can be one the player makes, or one the GM makes that directly concerns the player\rquote s character.\par \bullet \tab Declare that wounds aren\rquote t as bad as they first looked. This reduces one wound by one level (a Hurt becomes a Scratch, etc.).\par \bullet \tab Get an automatic +4 result.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 The Only Rule You Really Need To Know\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 When in doubt, just fudge it! Simply have things happen in a way that will let the players have fun. If you don\rquote t see a rule that covers a particular in-game situation, just use your best judgment.\par \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Sample Characters\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\kerning1 \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Azrath (Mage)\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Reasoning\tab Good\par Perception\tab Fair\par Willpower\tab Good\par Strength\tab Fair\par Agility\tab Fair\par Health\tab Fair\par Knowledge Skills (1 point)\par \tab Literacy\tab Fair\par \tab Thaumatology\tab Fair\par \tab Arcane Lore\tab Fair\par \tab History\tab Mediocre\par Combat Skills (1 point, Narrow Focus)\par \tab Long Knife\tab Good\par \tab Brawling\tab Mediocre\par Outdoor Skills (1 point)\par \tab Navigation\tab Fair\par \tab Map Sketching\tab Fair\par \tab Observation\tab Fair\par \tab Survival\tab Mediocre\par Magic Skills (2 Points)\par \tab Elementalism\tab Good\par \tab Wizardry\tab Fair\par \ta