480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 (Fantasy Fudge Bestiary)\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Here are some sample creatures for use with Fantasy Fudge. Feel free to taylor their descriptions and traits to fit your campaign world.\par See Section 6.5, Animal & Creature Examples, for more sample creatures and tips on creating your own beasts for Fudge. Monster descriptions from other roleplaying games are usually easily converted to Fudge.\par \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Basilisk\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Fair (animal)\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Poor\par \tab Agility:\tab Fair\par \tab Health:\tab Poor\par Supernatural Powers:\par \tab Venomous Breath\par Scale:\tab \endash 10\par Combat Skill:\tab Poor\par Attacks:\tab Bite, Breath (special attack)\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab \endash 10 (melee)\par \tab Defensive:\tab \endash 10 (melee)\par The basilisk, sometimes called the cockatrice by peasants, is a grayish serpent that grows to no more than two feet in length. It has white markings on its head that resemble a crown. Popular legend holds that the basilisk can kill with a mere glance, but this is untrue. The basilisk\rquote s danger lies in its venom. The venomous breath of a basilisk withers plants, scorches the earth and can kill any creature up to the size of an elephant.\par In combat, a basilisk breathes a nearly invisible, cone-shaped cloud of venom that affects foes up to fifteen feet away. Any living creature caught in the cloud must make a Health roll at Great Difficulty or be immediately slain.\par Basilisks are also dangerous in melee combat. Any blow that successfully damages the creature can cause the creature\rquote s foul venom to pass up through the weapon and affect the wielder. Any time a Basilisk is struck with a melee weapon, the GM should roll a dF. On a roll of \endash 1, the victim must make a Health roll as above or die.\par A basilisk is created from an egg that is laid by a cockerel and then incubated by a toad in a dung heap.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 --Anthony Roberson\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Dragon\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Fair\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Fair (Scale +4)\par \tab Agility:\tab Fair\par \tab Health:\tab Fair\par Gifts:\par \tab Tough Hide (+2 Defensive Damage Factor)\par \tab Wings\par \tab Fiery Breath\par Supernatural Powers (optional):\par \tab Magical Talent: Innate\par \tab Magical Talent: Scholarly Magic\par Skills:\par \tab Varies with individual; most Athletic, Knowledge, Magic, Scouting, and Social skills are possible.\par Scale:\tab +4\par Combat Skill:\tab Good\par Attacks:\tab Bite, Fiery Breath, Claws\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +6 (Claws); +5 (Bite); +6 Breath (on a Situational Roll of Mediocre or worse, the target of Fiery Breath catches on fire for an additional +2 damage per combat round until extinguished). Add Strength bonuses to Claws and Bite.\par \tab Defensive:\tab \endash 6 (Scale and Tough Hide)\par Dragons are large intelligent reptiloids. Many are known for their vanity.\par The GM should feel free to customize dragons to taste.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 --John Ughrin\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Ghost\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes:\par \tab Not Applicable\par Faults:\par \tab Unholy (optional)\par Supernatural Powers:\par Insubstantial (no physical attacks, can float through walls)\par Cause Fear (may force characters to make Great Willpower checks to avoid being scared off.)\par Scale:\tab n/a\par Combat Skill:\tab n/a\par Attacks:\tab n/a\par Damage Factors (including Scale): n/a\par Ghosts are the leftover psychic residue of someone who has perished. Generally speaking, there is no physical method of removing or harming them. Some ghosts can be put to rest if a special task is completed. Usually the completion of the task is what makes the spirit hang around after its original owner perished. Ghosts are generally resentful creatures and their deep emotional disturbance puts animals at unease.\par Ghosts may be influenced, confined, banished, or released by various applications of Clerical Magic or Scholarly Magic (especially Shamanism or Necromancy).\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 --John Ughrin\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Ghoul\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Poor\par \tab Perception:\tab Good\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Good\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab Mediocre\par Gifts:\par \tab Tough Hide (+2 Defensive Damage Factor)\par \tab Damage Capacity Good (+1 Defensive Damage Factor)\par \tab Claws (+1 Offensive Damage Factor, Poisonous)\par Skills:\par \tab Ghouls retain the skills they had when human, but at a \endash 1 penalty.\par Scale:\tab 0\par Combat Skill:\tab Good\par Attacks:\tab Bite, Claws\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +2 (Bite), +2 (Claws) plus poison (see below)\par \tab Defensive:\tab \endash 3 (Tough Hide, Damage Capacity)\par Ghouls (also know as Gh\u251\'9els and Raveners) are once-human creatures whose minds have been destroyed. They have grey, jellylike flesh, yellow fangs, and filthy, broken nails which infect their victims with a sinister toxin.\par Ghouls usually inhabit underground lairs near graveyards and similar places, where a supply of their noxious \ldblquote food\rdblquote  may be found. Ghouls usually travel in packs of 3-12, with the most powerful and intelligent member as a leader. Their usual prey is carrion, but they will attack living humans if driven to it by hunger or by a powerful master. \par Ghouls attack with their claws and teeth in a mindless frenzy. The poison in their claws drains vitality. The victim must make a Health roll, difficulty level Fair, or lose one level of health per combat round. Victims reduced to below Terrible Health become stiff and helpless.\par Any human succumbing to a ghoul attack will be taken to their lair and buried. This live internment, in addition to the ghoulish poison, deranges the mind and causes physical changes that result in the victim becoming a ghoul. If sufficiently hungry, the ghouls may simply devour the victim.\par Ghouls can be turned by the Repel Undead Clerical Magic skill, difficulty level Good. The clerical Ward ability keeps ghouls completely at bay.  A clerical Healing can neutralize the poison if a victim has not entirely become a ghoul.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Kent Matthewson\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Giant Worm\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Perception:\tab Good\par \tab Strength:\tab Good\par Gifts:\par \tab Tough Hide (+2 Defensive Damage Factor)\par \tab Tail Stinger (+2 Offensive Damage Factor)\par \tab Magic Resistance: Good\par Skills: \par \tab Not Applicable\par Scale:\tab +10 or more\par Combat Skill:\tab Mediocre\par Attacks:\tab Swallow, or Stinging Tail\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +12 or more (stinging tail)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +12 or more (Tough Hide)\par \tab \tab +1 if attacking from inside, see below\par These giant, carnivorous worms grow to be 150\rquote  long. They can bore through solid rock and are a menace to explorers in deep caverns.\par A worm\rquote s favorite attack is to stick its head out of a hole and swallow any creature of Scale 6 or less. Victims may attempt to dodge (Opposed Action, Victim\rquote s Agility versus the worm\rquote s Combat Skill). If the worm wins, the victim is swallowed.\par A creature may attempt to attack a worm from the inside., difficulty level Terrible (any attack of Terrible or better has a chance of doing damage) and DDF +1. There is little room to swing weapons. 15 points of cumulative damage done to the same area within the worm allows a victim to cut an escape hole, or might cause the worm to regurgitate. \par Meanwhile, the victim is being digested. He or she takes a Scratch each combat round after being swallowed. If the victim has no Scratch boxes left, the Scratch will be a Hurt; if there are no Hurt boxes left on the victim\rquote s wound track, the result will be Very Hurt, and so on until death.\par If attacked from the rear, a giant worm will lash out with a bone-like stinger on its tail. It can do this the same round as attempting to swallow. \par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Peter Mikelsons\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Goblin\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Strength:\tab Fair\par \tab Agility:\tab Fair\par \tab Health:\tab Fair\par Gifts:\par \tab Dark Vision\par \tab Toughness (+1 Defensive Damage Factor)\par Scale:\tab \endash 1\par Combat Skill:\tab Fair\par Attacks:\tab By weapon\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +1 (shortsword)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +1 (leather armor)\par Goblins are short (4\rquote  tall), evil humanoids that are found in wild forests or mountainous areas. Goblins are tribal and matriarchal. A tribe will normally consist of between 50 and 200 individuals. The leader of the tribe is usually a female of prodigious size and foul temperament.\par Goblins are not particularly fearsome opponents in battle unless they are backed by overwhelming numbers or led by a charismatic general. Goblin tribes go through periods of very high birth rates every 5-10 years. This results in periodic invasions of surrounding lands by hordes of goblins on the move due to overpopulation and starvation.\par Goblins fear and hate dwarves, since dwarves often enslave them and put them to work in their mines. The average goblin is armed with a wicked-looking serrated short sword and protected by a patchwork of leather armor.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 -- Anthony Roberson\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Great Weasel\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Fair (animal)\par \tab Perception:\tab Good\par \tab Agility:\tab Great\par \tab Speed:\tab Superb\par Skills:\par \tab Move Quietly\tab Great\par Scale:\tab \endash 5\par Combat Skill:\tab Superb\par Attacks:\tab Bite and Claws\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab \endash 3 (bite or claws)\par \tab Defensive:\tab \endash 5\par Great weasels are 3\rquote  long with razor-sharp claws, needle-like teeth, lightning reflexes and a bad attitude. Giant rats are their preferred prey. Great Weasels may be tamed.\par With their speed and ability to move quietly, great weasels can attack their prey without warning, gaining an Unopposed attack, Difficulty Fair in the first combat round. If a great weasel wins an attack with a relative degree of +4 or more, it has bitten a major blood vessel. The victim will bleed to death in several minutes, unless first aid or healing is applied. The victim must make a Health roll (Difficulty Fair) every minute or bleed to death. GMs who allow NPCs to have Fudge points should give great weasels one point.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 -- Peter Mikelsons\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Hydra\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Fair\par \tab Perception:\tab Great\par \tab Strength:\tab Great\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab Fair\par Supernatural Powers:\par \tab Many Heads (usually 5)\par \tab Head Regeneration (see below)\par Scale:\tab +8 (each head Scale +2)\par Combat Skill:\tab Good\par Attacks:\tab Bite (1 from each head)\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +5 (bite)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +2 (each head) or +8 (body)\par Its origins shrouded in mystery, the hydra is one of the most feared creatures. It appears as a large reptile, with many heads. Its regeneration makes it nearly unstoppable and its appetite is insatiable.\par Each of a hydra\rquote s head can attack independently. For combat purposes, treat each head as a scale +2 creature whose teeth do +5 damage due to sharpness and strength.\par Any wound of Incapacitated or Near Death inflicted on a head severs it from its neck. A new head will regenerate to replace the lost one. If the hydra makes a Superb Health check, two heads are regenerated. The regeneration process takes 4 combat rounds. A Hurt or worse wound inflicted by fire will prevent regeneration. Magic weapons may have similar effects.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 --Steven Hammond\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Hyeena\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Good (animal)\par \tab Perception:\tab Good\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Good\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab Good\par Gifts:\par \tab Magical Defense (see below)\par \tab Toughness (+1 Defensive Damage Factor)\par Skills:\par \tab Mimicry\tab Great (see below)\par Scale:\tab +0\par Combat Skill:\tab Good\par Attacks:\tab Bite\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +2 (sharp teeth)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +1 (toughness)\par The hyeena is a horrible beast that resembles a large hound with a spiny ridge running along its back. It lives in tombs or catacombs and feeds on the dead. It will also dig up graves in the search for bodies. Some hyeenas stalk rural areas by night and prey on shepherds or late travelers.\par The hyeena has an unusual magical defense. Any creature that treads on a hyeena\rquote s shadow is immediately struck dumb and unable to speak. The effect lasts until the hyeena is killed or an hour has passed.\par The hyeena also has an uncanny talent for imitating the human voice, and uses this trick to lure its prey into an ambush.\par Alchemists prize the hyeena\rquote s eyes because they can be distilled into small stones that can be used to foretell the future.  An alchemist will pay a good fee for a pair of hyeena eyes if they are fresh or have been properly preserved in salt or strong alcohol.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 -- Anthony Roberson\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Imp\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Good\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Strength:\tab Mediocre to Good\par \tab Agility:\tab Mediocre to Great\par \tab Health:\tab Fair\par Supernormal Powers:\par \tab Magical Talent (Demonic Magic; see below)\par \tab Magical Toughness (+3 Defensive Damage Factor)\par Skills:\par \tab Demonic Magic\tab Great\par \tab GM may choose  other skills appropriate to individual.\par Scale:\tab \endash 3 or smaller\par Combat Skill:\tab Fair\par Attacks:\tab Magic or bite\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab \endash 2 (sharp teeth)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +0 (magical toughness)\par (adjust Damage Factors for Scale if less than \endash 3)\par Imps are small demonic entities, which are either summoned or sent to this plane to aid a sorcerer or priest in some evil scheme. Imps come in many shapes, from man-like to grotesque.\par Imps are skilled in Demonic Magic, which works the same way Scholarly Magic does. Demonic Magic excels at magical feats that cause confusion and misery. Most imps have 5 magical power points, and can channel 1- or 2-point spells.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 -- John Ughrin\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Medusa\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Fair\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Fair\par \tab Agility:\tab Fair\par \tab Health:\tab Fair\par Supernormal Powers:\par \tab Petrification (see below)\par Skills:\par \tab Assassination\tab Good\par Scale:\tab +0\par Combat Skill:\tab Good\par Attacks:\tab Bow\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +2 (bow; add Strength bonus if any)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +0\par Medusae are cursed by gods. In ages past, the mother of all medusae compared her own beauty with that of the gods. For this, she and all her descendants were made so hideous, that any who saw them were turned to stone. (Any character who sees a medusa\rquote s face must make a Willpower check at a Great Difficulty level, or turn to stone.)\par A medusa may attempt to take residence in an old villa or abandoned home. There, slowly but surely, a statue garden will begin to grow. The services of a hero may be needed to find a way of killing the poor creature. It has been rumored that when a medusa is slain, her victims return to the flesh.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 -- John Ughrin\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Rathent\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Fair\par \tab Perception:\tab Good\par \tab Willpower:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Strength:\tab Fair\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab Good\par Gifts:\par \tab Keen Senses (especially eyesight)\par \tab Quick Reflexes\par \tab 1 in 10 Rathent possess a Magical Talent Gift (see below)\par Faults:\par \tab Cowardly\par \tab Damage Capacity Mediocre (\endash 1 to DDF)\par \tab Jerk (Few Rathent have any regard for anything but themselves. This can translate in several ways.)\par Skills:\par \tab Setting Traps\tab Good\par \tab Ambush\tab Good\par \tab Move Quietly\tab Great\par \tab Athletic Skills\tab Fair\par \tab Outdoor Skills\tab Fair\par \tab Other skills as appropriate for individual\par Scale:\tab \endash 1 to +0\par Combat Skill:\tab Fair to Great\par Attacks:\tab Claws or Weapon\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +0 (claws)\par \tab \tab +1 to +3 (scavenged weapons)\par \tab (adjust Offensive Damage Factors for Strength if needed)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +0 (cobbled together armor)\par Rathent are odd creatures, most likely the result of some magical hybridization gone awry. They resemble humanoid birds, with large, curved beaks and offset eyes. Feathers cover their head, upper torso and arms. Their plumage is generally dark or mottled and unkempt and greasy. Many Rathent have hands ending talon-like claws. Most Rathent have human-like leg structure. Rare individuals will have bird-like legs or vestigial wings, and are generally regarded as gruk (retard or throwback). This is a reflection of cultural bias rather than actual ability or intelligence.\par The structure of Rathent society is loosely tribal with the strongest or most cunning being the skwarka (chieftain). The skwarka leads the tribe in battle and receives the most prestige and breeding privileges.\par Rathent are extremely protective of their females, as they have a relatively low birthrate. Only one in five members of a typical Rathent tribe are female.\par Rathent males serve as hunters and generally engage in banditry, thievery, and murder to eke out an existence. They are cowardly scavengers by nature and will feed on carrion with glee when there is nothing better.\par Most Rathent provide only for themselves, but offer tribute to the skwarka and his harem. Warriors that do not pay tribute regularly to the skwarka are either exiled or more likely killed.\par Rathent may be encountered in semi-civilized areas on the outskirts of forests and mountains. Their villages are clusters of rude tree houses similar to nests in structure. The skwarka\rquote s nest is the largest and centrally located, and is built into the largest tree available.\par Rathent have fair craftsmanship skills, but rarely produce anything of exceptional quality. Most of their weaponry is scavenged or stolen. When left to their own means they will produce javelins, war darts, and spears. Rathent armor is usually cobbled together from bits and pieces scavenged in their raids.\par Some Rathent have an innate talent for simple magic. Clerical Magic and Hedge Magic is most common. Scholarly Magic (Elementalism or Necromancy) is also possible, but no Rathent will have more than one level of the Magical Talent: Scholarly Magic Gift. Rathents with Magical Talent are known as kuzkwa. Most are female. All magically talented Rathent are sterile and considered sexless. Many are also albino. These Rathent serve as shamans and spiritual advisors.\par Rathent spirituality is a grim affair centered around the malevolent figure Kzukwa-skwark (Old Lord Dread). Homage is paid to this fearsome entity by murdering as many non-Rathent as possible. This ensures that the afterlife will be only moderately painful, rather than an eternity of anguish and torture.\par Rathent have an irrational attraction to shiny objects, and will often quarrel over relatively useless objects that glitter.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Sedge Lewis\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Ratlings\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Strength:\tab Fair\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab Mediocre\par Scale:\tab \endash 1 (or less)\par Combat Skill:\tab Fair\par Attacks:\tab Claws or Bite\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +0 (claws), +1 (bite)\par \tab Defensive:\tab \endash 1\par Ratlings are small humanoid creatures whose head, claws and tail look like those of a rat. Their legs are also more ratlike than human. Ratlings have a low life expectancy due to disease resulting from poor living conditions. Ratlings can speak as well as humans, and usually speak the local dominant language. Their claws are dexterous enough to allow a Ratling to use equipment made for humans.\par Ratlings were created by a Grand Mage who later allowed his experiments to leave his laboratory. In the few years since their creation, the Ratlings have established themselves amid the slums and backways of the city.\par The GM may involve Ratlings in the city\rquote s political scene if desired. Examples: The local ruler has placed a bounty on Ratling skins; Ratlings are active in the Thieves\rquote  or Beggars\rquote  Guilds; etc.\par The GM may adjust Ratlings to be smaller and more ratlike, if she likes. Suggested Scale: \endash 5 or less (remember to adjust Offensive and Defensive Damage Factors).\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Gordon McCormick\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Restless Dead\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Poor\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab n/a (mindless)\par \tab Strength:\tab Fair\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab n/a (not alive)\par Gifts:\par \tab Immune to Mind Magic\par \tab Skeletal (Half damage from slashing weapons; piercing weapon damage is reduced to 1)\par \tab Unaffected by Sunlight (unlike many Undead)\par Faults:\par \tab Susceptible to Fire\par \tab Destroyed by running water (dispels animating magic)\par \tab Undead (can be banished, etc.)\par Scale:\tab \endash 2 to +2 (as when alive)\par Combat Skill:\tab Fair\par Attacks:\tab Weapon\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab by weapon\par \tab Defensive:\tab +2 (Light Armor and Shield)\par Time and time again, necromancers turn to dead humanoids when trying to inexpensively create tireless, fearless guardians. Corpses are versatile, readily available, and the once-living bones lend themselves well to enchantment. A lesser nether-spirit is bound to the dead bones, animating them and providing a rudimentary, malevolent intelligence. The resulting creatures need no sustenance, are infinitely patient, and obey the commands of their creators without question. They are often set to guard tombs, fortresses, and hiding places of all sorts.\par The Restless Dead appear as piles of old bones scattered around the places they guard. They have no odor (prior to enchantment, the corpses are usually stripped of all flesh by being placed onto anthills or in maggot pits). It takes a Perception roll of Great or above to detect the thin webwork of sigils covering the bones from any distance.\par When anyone or anything comes near, the bones reassemble into malevolent, skeletal forms and spring into action.\par Though not terribly strong, the Restless Dead are agile and tenacious. They are often equipped with rusty, patchwork armor (+1), shields (+1), and various weapons such as maces, swords, axes, and spears (+1 to +3).\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Dmitri Zagidulin\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Soldier, Professional\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Good\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab Fair\par Skills: (choose as appropriate to the individual)\par \tab Athletic Skills\tab Fair - Good\par \tab Social Skills\tab Mediocre - Good\par Gifts: (choose as appropriate to the individual)\par \tab Common soldierly Gifts include Danger Sense, Pain Tolerance, Quick Reflexes, Tough Hide, or Veteran.\par Faults: (choose as appropriate to the individual)\par \tab Common soldierly Faults include Code of Honor, Compulsive Gambling, Duty, One Eye.\par Scale:\tab +0\par Combat Skill:\tab Good - Great\par Attacks:\tab by weapon\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab by weapon\par \tab \tab (add Strength bonus if applicable)\par \tab Defensive:\tab by armor\par \tab \tab (add Tough Hide bonus if applicable)\par A professional soldier is a trained, well-equipped warrior. This template may be used for town guards.\par Soldiers usually have at least Good morale and discipline. However, many only have Mediocre mental attributes. A squad of soldiers is usually led by an officer with Good or better Combat and mental attributes.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Peter Mikelsons\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Thug\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Fair\par \tab Agility:\tab Fair\par \tab Health:\tab Fair\par Skills: (choose as appropriate to the individual)\par \tab Athletic Skills\tab Mediocre - Good\par \tab Social Skills\tab Poor - Fair\par Gifts: (choose as appropriate to the individual)\par \tab Common Gifts for Thugs include Pain Tolerance, Resistant to Poison, and Tough Hide.\par Faults: (choose as appropriate to the individual)\par \tab Common Faults for Thugs include Appearance, Outlaw, or Quick Tempered.\par Scale:\tab +0\par Combat Skill:\tab Mediocre - Fair\par Attacks:\tab by weapon\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab \endash 1 (fist), or by weapon\par \tab \tab (add Strength bonus if applicable)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +1 (leather, or partial heavier armor)\par \tab \tab (add Tough Hide bonus if applicable)\par A Thug is an untrained, none-too-bright, poorly equipped person who may start trouble with PCs because of alcohol, testosterone, or commands from an arch-villain.\par In any crowd of Thugs, there is at least one with an additional +1 or +2 Offensive Damage Factor due to unusual strength.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Peter Mikelsons\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Troll\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Poor\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Great\par \tab Agility:\tab Fair\par \tab Health:\tab Great\par Gifts:\par \tab Toughness (+3 DDF)\par \tab Stench (\endash 2 to opponents combat skills; see below)\par Scale:\tab +3\par Combat Skill:\tab Good\par Attacks:\tab weapon or claws\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +5 (claws), +8 (massive club)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +8\par Trolls are huge, loathsome creatures. Many are identified by the areas where they live. There are Hill Trolls, Swamp Trolls, Wood Trolls, and countless others.\par The average troll stands well over 9\rquote  tall and usually wields a massive club. A troll\rquote s presence is easily identified by the horrible stench that always accompanies them.  They are carnivores and most are not terribly bright.\par Anyone facing a Troll in melee combat must make a Good difficulty Willpower roll or suffer a \endash 2 penalty to all combat skills for the duration of the combat, due to the creature\rquote s overwhelming smell.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Anthony Roberson\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Wall Crawler\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Poor (animal)\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Poor\par \tab Strength:\tab Poor\par \tab Agility:\tab Good\par \tab Health:\tab Poor\par Gifts:\par \tab Toxic Spines (see below)\par Scale:\tab \endash 6\par Combat Skill:\tab Mediocre\par Attacks:\tab bite\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab \endash 6\par \tab Defensive:\tab \endash 6\par The wall crawler resembles nothing so much as a nightmarish cross between a giant centipede and a black, furry caterpillar. A wall crawler is usually 1\rquote  to 1\rquote  6\rdblquote  long and, except for its head, is completely covered with 6\rdblquote  long black spines. The crawler skitters along on sixteen feet that are equipped with an array of tiny hook-like protrusions. These allow the creature to travel over almost any surface. It can traverse a cave ceiling or dungeon wall as easily as it does the ground.\par Wall crawlers are found in dark places and fill the role of scavengers, devouring the dead and sometimes the dying.  Wall crawlers rarely attack living creatures unless in defense or if the creature is badly injured. They are usually encountered in groups of 7-12 individuals.\par In combat, a wall crawler can deliver a painful bite that sometimes becomes infected. Its real danger, however, lies in the spines that cover its body. These spines are sharp and can easily pierce cloth or the leather sole of a boot.  The hollow spines contain a toxin that causes confusion and hallucinations. If an adventurer contacts a spine, he must make a Fair difficulty Health Roll. If he fails the roll, he will become confused and disoriented within minutes.  For the next 2-4 hours he will be effectively incapacitated by hallucinations, unable to fight or find his way without assistance.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \endash  Anthony Roberson\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Zombie\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab n/a (mindless)\par \tab Perception:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Willpower:\tab n/a (mindless)\par \tab Strength:\tab Great\par \tab Agility:\tab Poor\par \tab Health:\tab Great\par Supernatural Powers:\par \tab Immune to Pain (no penalties due to wounds)\par \tab Immune to Fear\par \tab Tough (+2 to Defensive Damage Factor)\par Faults:\par \tab VileStench\par \tab Horrid Appearance\par \tab Disease Carriers (optional; see below)\par Scale:\tab 0\par Combat Skill:\tab Poor\par Attacks:\tab arm swing or drag down\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +1 (unarmed, Strength bonus)\par \tab Defensive:\tab +2\par Zombies are walking corpses, with shreds of flesh still attached. They are animated through evil magics (Necromancy, Sorcery, or some evil Clerical Magic) and obey the instructions of their creators. Zombies continue to decay, giving them a vile stench and a horrifying appearance. They may also be disease carriers. The GM may require characters exposed to zombies to make a Health Roll (Difficulty Level Mediocre) to avoid contracting some suitably noxious disease.\par Zombies have no initiative, relying on their master for instructions. Feeling no fear or pain, they make excellent shock troops. They are almost indestructible, requiring a Near Death result to \ldblquote kill\rdblquote  them.\par Zombies are unable to wield weapons. They attack with their hands and nails, pummeling their opponents with mindless intensity. They will attempt to surround and overwhelm difficult opponents.\par Zombies are unintelligent (mindless), and so have no speech, skills, etc., although they may moan while attacking. They may be repelled with the Repel Undead Clerical Magic skill (Difficulty Level Mediocre).\par Zombies usually inhabit cemeteries, abandoned churches, necromancers\rquote  strongholds, or temples to evil gods.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  blended from submissions by Steven Hammond, Kent Matthewson, and Peter Mikelsons\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }{\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Zuvembie\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Attributes (individuals may vary):\par \tab Reasoning:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Perception:\tab Fair\par \tab Willpower:\tab Fair\par \tab Strength:\tab Great\par \tab Agility:\tab Mediocre\par \tab Health:\tab Mediocre\par Skills:\par \tab As when alive, but 2 levels lower\par Supernatural Powers:\par \tab Immune to Pain (no penalties due to wounds)\par \tab Immune to Fear\par \tab Tough (+2 to Defensive Damage Factor)\par Faults:\par \tab Horrid Appearance\par Scale:\tab 0\par Combat Skill:\tab Good\par Attacks:\tab Bony hands, or weapon\par Damage Factors (including Scale):\par \tab Offensive:\tab +2 (unarmed) or by weapon\par \tab Defensive:\tab +2\par An evil priest, sorcerer, or necromancer can create a Zuvembie by draining the life force from a man-sized humanoid creature via arcane magics and poisons. A Zuvembie\rquote s flesh becomes hard and its skin leathery as a result of the process, and Zuvembie bodies do not show the decay of true zombies. They retain some intelligence, unlike zombies, and can understand relatively complex instructions. They wield weapons (albeit clumsily), and may retain some of the skills they maintained in life, but reduced by 2 levels.\par As with zombies, Zuvembies are immune to pain and require a Near Death result to \ldblquote kill\rdblquote  them.\par Zuvembies usually inhabit their creators\rquote  residence. They may be Repelled with Great difficulty.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \emdash  Kent Matthewson\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\fs28\kerning1 Miscellaneous Charts and Information\par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 \par }\pard \sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs26\kerning1 Fudge Combat Tables\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\kerning1 \par }\pard \sa120\sl240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Sample Wound Factors\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Add all applicable Offensive Factors to determine the Offensive Damage Factor; add all applicable Defensive Factors to determine the Defensive Damage Factor.\par }{\i\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 Offensive factors:\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\kerning1 For Character\rquote s Strength\par (muscle-powered weapons only):\par Trait modifier (+3 for Superb, \endash 1 for Mediocre, etc.)\par \par For Attacker\rquote s Scale:\par Plus the attacker\rquote s Strength Scale\par (see Section 4.68, Non-human Scale in Combat).\par \par For Weapon\rquote s Strength\par (Guns, Crossbows, Beam weapons, etc.):\par +/\endash  Strength of weapon\par (see Section 4.4, Ranged Combat).\par \par For Muscle-Powered Weapon:\par \endash 1 for no weapon, not using a Martial Art skill.\par +0 Martial Art skill, or for small weapons\par +1 for medium-weight one-handed weapons\par +2 for la